INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2828,304,1,'Ad Hoc','Cloud costs are tracked reactively using basic billing reports from cloud service providers. There is no consistent tagging strategy, no cost allocation by team or workload, and no formal accountability for spend. Finance and Engineering operate in silos with no shared cloud financial vocabulary.','CSP-native billing dashboards only\u000aNo tagging governance or enforcement\u000aCost visibility limited to invoice level\u000aNo chargeback or showback mechanism\u000aNo designated FinOps ownership',NULL,1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2829,304,2,'Defined','A tagging policy is defined and partially enforced. Showback reports are produced for major business units, enabling basic cost awareness. A FinOps practice or Cloud Financial Management function is formally established with named ownership. Unit cost baselines are being established for primary workload types.','Tagging policy documented and partially enforced\u000aShowback reporting available for major BUs\u000aFinOps role or function formally named\u000aCloud cost allocation model defined\u000aBasic rightsizing recommendations reviewed monthly\u000aReserved instance or savings plan coverage tracked',NULL,1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2830,304,3,'Integrated','Cost visibility is comprehensive and near real-time across all environments. Tagging compliance exceeds 90%. Chargeback is operational — teams receive accurate cost allocations and are held accountable. Unit economics (cost per transaction, cost per user) are tracked. Anomaly detection alerts are configured and acted upon. FinOps is integrated into sprint planning and architecture review processes.','Tagging compliance >90% enforced via policy-as-code\u000aChargeback operational with team-level P&L visibility\u000aUnit cost metrics tracked per workload/product\u000aAnomaly detection configured with <24hr response SLA\u000aCommitment coverage (RIs/Savings Plans) >60%\u000aFinOps integrated into architecture review board\u000aCloud waste identification and remediation backlog active',NULL,1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2831,304,4,'Intelligent','FinOps practices are data-driven and predictive. ML-based forecasting provides accurate 30/60/90-day spend projections by team and product. Automated rightsizing and idle resource termination are in place. Cost efficiency is a tracked engineering KPI. Cloud unit economics feed product pricing decisions. Commitment utilisation exceeds 80% with automated recommendations.','ML-based spend forecasting with <10% variance\u000aAutomated rightsizing and idle resource termination\u000aCost efficiency embedded as engineering team KPI\u000aCloud unit economics feed product/pricing decisions\u000aCommitment utilisation >80% with automated optimisation\u000aReal-time cost anomaly auto-remediation for low-risk cases\u000aFinOps dashboard embedded in executive reporting',NULL,1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2832,304,5,'Adaptive','Cloud economics are fully integrated into enterprise financial planning and product strategy. Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) and Return on Cloud Investment (ROCI) are standard board-level metrics. FinOps practices extend to SaaS, hybrid, and edge environments. Continuous optimisation is fully automated with human oversight reserved for strategic decisions. The organisation contributes to and benchmarks against external FinOps Foundation standards.','ROCI and TCO as board-level reporting metrics\u000aFinOps scope covers cloud, SaaS, hybrid, and edge\u000aFully automated continuous optimisation pipeline\u000aBenchmarking against FinOps Foundation industry standards\u000aCloud economics integrated into enterprise financial planning cycle\u000aAutonomous commitment management with policy guardrails\u000aExternal contribution to FinOps community or standards bodies',NULL,1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2833,305,1,'Ad Hoc','No formal supply chain security process. Third-party components are used without inventory or vetting. No SBOM generated.','No SBOM | No dependency scanning | No supplier security requirements | Vulnerabilities discovered reactively','No structured approach to third-party risk in software supply chain',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2834,305,2,'Defined','SBOM generation initiated for critical applications. Basic dependency scanning in CI pipeline. Supplier security questionnaire exists.','SBOM generated for critical apps | Dependency scanner integrated | Supplier questionnaire in use | Known CVEs tracked','Defined process exists but coverage is incomplete and not systematically enforced',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2835,305,3,'Integrated','SBOM mandatory for all production software. Automated dependency scanning with policy gates blocking high-severity CVEs. Supplier attestation required for Tier 1 vendors.','SBOM 100% production coverage | Policy gates blocking Critical/High CVEs | Tier 1 supplier attestation | Build pipeline integrity checks active','Integrated into SDLC and procurement; exceptions tracked and risk-accepted formally',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2836,305,4,'Intelligent','Continuous supply chain risk monitoring with automated remediation triggering. SBOM feeds live vulnerability intelligence. Supplier risk scoring automated and integrated into vendor management.','Real-time SBOM/vulnerability correlation | Automated remediation workflows | Supplier risk scores integrated into procurement decisions | Regulatory reporting automated (NIS2/SOCI)','Proactive and intelligence-driven; supply chain risk is a first-class input to security decisions',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2837,305,5,'Adaptive','Supply chain security is embedded in all third-party relationships and procurement contracts. Organisation contributes to and consumes industry threat intelligence on supply chain attacks. Zero-trust posture applied to all third-party components.','Industry threat intelligence sharing | Contract-embedded security requirements | Zero-trust applied to all vendor code | Board-level supply chain risk reporting | NIST 800-161 fully aligned','Adaptive and ecosystem-aware; supply chain security is a competitive differentiator and regulatory benchmark',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2838,306,1,'Ad Hoc','Perimeter-based network security only. No Zero Trust principles applied. Implicit trust granted to users and devices inside the network boundary.','Flat network with implicit trust | No micro-segmentation | VPN-only remote access | No device trust scoring','No Zero Trust posture; network access based on location not identity',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2839,306,2,'Defined','Zero Trust principles documented and adopted as strategy. Identity-aware access piloted for one or more workloads. Micro-segmentation initiated in critical zones.','Zero Trust strategy documented | Identity-aware access pilot active | Critical zone segmentation started | MFA enforced for privileged access','Strategy defined, initial pilots underway; broad implementation not yet achieved',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2840,306,3,'Integrated','ZTNA enforced for all remote access and cloud workloads. Micro-segmentation covering production environments. Device trust scoring integrated with IAM. Lateral movement significantly constrained.','ZTNA enforced for remote and cloud | Production micro-segmentation complete | Device trust scoring operational | Continuous session verification active','Zero Trust enforced for primary access patterns; some legacy systems still on perimeter model',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2841,306,4,'Intelligent','Full ZTNA coverage across hybrid estate including legacy systems. Automated policy enforcement based on real-time risk signals. East-west traffic fully controlled and anomaly-detected.','Full estate ZTNA coverage | Risk-adaptive access policies | East-west anomaly detection | Automated policy response to threat signals | Integration with SIEM/SOAR','Intelligent and adaptive; access decisions made dynamically based on continuous risk assessment',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2842,306,5,'Adaptive','Zero Trust is the universal access model with no legacy perimeter exceptions. Continuous verification extended to supply chain and third-party access. Organisation benchmarks and contributes to ZTNA standards.','No perimeter exceptions | Third-party/supply chain ZTNA | Industry benchmarking contribution | Zero trust maturity formally assessed against NIST SP 800-207','Universal Zero Trust posture; organisation is a reference architecture for peers',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2843,307,1,'Ad Hoc','No formal security controls for AI/ML systems. AI deployments not inventoried from a security perspective. Vulnerabilities in models and prompts not assessed.','No AI asset inventory | No model threat modelling | No prompt injection controls | AI incidents not tracked separately','AI treated as any other application; no recognition of AI-specific threat surface',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2844,307,2,'Defined','AI security policy drafted. Critical AI/LLM deployments inventoried. Basic prompt injection and output validation controls applied to public-facing AI.','AI security policy exists | LLM inventory for public-facing systems | Prompt injection controls on public APIs | AI incidents captured in security log','Policy defined, controls applied to highest-visibility systems only',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2845,307,3,'Integrated','AI threat modelling mandatory for all production AI deployments. Model integrity verification in CI/CD. LLM guardrails and output filtering systematically applied. AI red-teaming conducted for critical systems.','AI threat model required for production | Model integrity checks in CI/CD | LLM guardrails and output filtering | AI red-team exercises conducted | Adversarial input testing integrated','Integrated into AI development lifecycle; controls systematic not ad hoc',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2846,307,4,'Intelligent','Continuous model monitoring for drift, poisoning signals, and anomalous output patterns. Automated adversarial input detection. AI security risk integrated into enterprise risk management.','Continuous model integrity monitoring | Automated adversarial detection | AI risk in enterprise risk register | Regulatory AI security obligations tracked (EU AI Act)','Proactive and intelligence-driven; AI security is a first-class risk domain',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2847,307,5,'Adaptive','AI security controls are self-improving based on observed attack patterns. Organisation participates in AI security threat intelligence sharing. Full alignment to EU AI Act, NIST AI RMF, and applicable national standards.','Self-improving AI security controls | Industry threat intelligence contribution | EU AI Act/NIST AI RMF alignment | Board-level AI risk reporting','Adaptive and ecosystem-contributing; AI security posture evolves with the threat landscape',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2848,308,1,'Ad Hoc','Technical debt exists but is not formally identified or tracked. Debt accumulates organically. No visibility of the cost or risk associated with technical debt.','No debt inventory | No debt taxonomy | Debt addressed reactively when systems fail | No investment allocated to debt reduction','Unmanaged debt; risk and cost are invisible to leadership',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2849,308,2,'Defined','Technical debt taxonomy defined (code, architectural, test, infrastructure, documentation). Debt backlog established for critical systems. Basic debt scoring applied.','Debt taxonomy documented | Debt backlog exists for critical systems | Basic severity scoring | Some sprint capacity allocated to debt reduction','Debt is visible and categorised; remediation is ad hoc and under-resourced',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2850,308,3,'Integrated','Debt inventory covers all production systems. Debt scoring integrated into architectural reviews and project intake. Remediation backlog managed alongside feature development with formal capacity allocation.','Full production inventory | Debt gates in architectural review | Formal remediation capacity (10–20% of sprint) | Debt trend tracked quarter-on-quarter | Integration with App Portfolio Management','Debt is systematically governed; reduction is funded and prioritised alongside new development',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2851,308,4,'Intelligent','Debt accumulation rate and projected remediation cost tracked as financial metrics. Debt risk integrated into investment cases and technology refresh decisions. Automated code analysis feeds debt backlog continuously.','Debt cost quantified in financial terms | Automated code analysis feeding backlog | Debt factored into investment cases | DORA metrics correlated with debt levels','Debt is a managed financial and risk metric; leadership makes data-driven decisions on remediation investment',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2852,308,5,'Adaptive','Technical debt is near-zero by design through continuous refactoring culture, architectural guardrails, and automated quality gates. Debt accumulation is a leading indicator in engineering health dashboards.','Near-zero debt as steady state | Automated quality gates prevent new debt | Debt as engineering health KPI | Continuous refactoring culture embedded | Industry benchmarking of debt levels','Debt prevention is embedded in engineering culture; debt as a concept is a lagging rather than leading indicator',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2853,309,1,'Ad Hoc','GenAI tools used ad hoc by individuals without governance. No enterprise LLM deployment. No prompt standards or output validation. Data privacy in LLM interactions uncontrolled.','Ad hoc personal LLM tool use | No enterprise deployment | No prompt governance | Data leakage risk unmanaged | No cost tracking','Shadow AI; GenAI usage uncontrolled and untracked',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2854,309,2,'Defined','Enterprise LLM platform selected and piloted. Prompt engineering guidelines published. Basic PII filtering and output review process defined. Token cost monitoring initiated.','Enterprise LLM platform piloted | Prompt guidelines published | PII filtering in place | Token cost dashboard operational | Use case catalogue started','Controlled pilot; governance defined but not yet systematically enforced',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2855,309,3,'Integrated','GenAI platform operational for approved use cases. RAG pipelines integrated with enterprise knowledge sources. Hallucination monitoring and output quality scoring active. Prompt versioning and A/B testing in place. Cost per use case tracked.','RAG pipelines integrated | Hallucination monitoring active | Prompt versioning and testing | Cost per use case tracked | Model selection framework in use | Responsible AI guardrails enforced','Operationally integrated; GenAI is a managed platform capability not a point tool',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2856,309,4,'Intelligent','Continuous evaluation of model performance, retrieval quality, and output accuracy. Automated model switching based on performance and cost signals. Fine-tuned models operational for domain-specific use cases. GenAI ROI measured and reported.','Continuous model evaluation and switching | Domain fine-tuning operational | GenAI ROI formally measured | Retrieval quality scoring automated | Integration with enterprise data governance','Intelligence-driven; GenAI platform self-optimises on cost and quality signals',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2857,309,5,'Adaptive','GenAI capabilities are embedded across the enterprise value chain and continuously evolve with model advances. Organisation contributes to responsible GenAI standards. Full alignment to EU AI Act and NIST AI RMF for GenAI-specific obligations.','GenAI embedded in enterprise value chain | Model capability roadmap actively managed | Industry standards contribution | Full regulatory alignment | Board-level GenAI value reporting','Adaptive and industry-leading; GenAI is a strategic organisational capability',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2858,310,1,'Ad Hoc','No digital twin capability. Simulation done manually or not at all. Infrastructure and application behaviour modelled through observation rather than predictive tools.','No digital twin tooling | Manual capacity modelling | No simulation-based change impact assessment | No energy/sustainability modelling','No simulation posture; decisions based on observation rather than prediction',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2859,310,2,'Defined','Digital twin concept adopted for one or more domains (e.g. infrastructure capacity). Basic simulation tooling in use. Use cases identified and prioritised.','Digital twin strategy documented | Pilot twin operational for one domain | Simulation tooling selected | Use case register exists','Strategy and pilot in place; limited operational coverage',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2860,310,3,'Integrated','Infrastructure digital twins operational covering capacity and performance simulation. Application dependency twins supporting change impact modelling. Twin data synchronised with live monitoring data.','Infrastructure twin operational | Application dependency twin for change impact | Live monitoring data feeds twin | Capacity planning uses twin simulation | Change risk scored via twin','Integrated for primary operational use cases; twins are part of operational decision-making',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2861,310,4,'Intelligent','Predictive simulation drives capacity, cost, and sustainability decisions. Failure mode and what-if scenarios routinely modelled before implementation. Sustainability twins feeding carbon footprint optimisation.','Predictive capacity and cost simulation | Failure mode simulation pre-implementation | Sustainability/carbon twin operational | Twin accuracy validated against actuals | FinOps integration for cost simulation','Intelligent and predictive; digital twins are a primary decision-support tool',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2862,310,5,'Adaptive','Digital twins span the full enterprise technology estate including edge, hybrid cloud, and OT environments. Twin models are self-updating and feed autonomous operations. Organisation is a reference for digital twin practice.','Full estate twin coverage including edge/OT | Self-updating twin models | Twin feeds autonomous operations | Industry reference architecture | R&D investment in twin advancement','Adaptive and autonomous; digital twin is a core strategic and operational asset',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2863,311,1,'Ad Hoc','Features engineered manually per project with no reuse','No feature registry; training-serving skew common; features duplicated across teams','No shared feature store; all feature pipelines bespoke per model',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2864,311,2,'Emerging','Informal feature library exists but ungoverned','Some feature reuse within teams; no versioning; no point-in-time correctness','Shared scripts or notebooks; inconsistent naming conventions; manual hand-off to training',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2865,311,3,'Defined','Managed feature store with versioning and registry in place','Feature registry operational; point-in-time retrieval for tabular data; drift alerts configured','Centralised feature store (Feast, Tecton, or equivalent); versioned; serving latency SLOs defined',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2866,311,4,'Governed','Feature store integrated across training and serving with governance','Cross-team feature reuse >50%; drift monitoring automated; feature lineage tracked','Feature quality metrics reported; SLA on feature freshness; data contract enforcement',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2867,311,5,'Optimised','AI-driven feature discovery and automated feature engineering','Auto-feature engineering active; feature impact scoring guides model development; real-time streaming features at scale','Sub-5ms feature serving p99; automated feature candidacy scoring; zero training-serving skew SLA',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2868,312,1,'Ad Hoc','Models evaluated informally, metric choices inconsistent','No standardised evaluation framework; metrics chosen ad hoc; no baseline comparison','Evaluation done manually in notebooks; no regression testing; no A/B framework',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2869,312,2,'Emerging','Basic evaluation metrics established per model type','Accuracy/F1 tracked; no shadow deployment; limited LLM evaluation','Evaluation scripts exist; no automated pipeline; no hallucination benchmarks for LLMs',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2870,312,3,'Defined','Standardised evaluation suite with pre-deployment gates','Evaluation pipeline automated; shadow deployment used; LLM eval metrics (RAGAS, hallucination rate) defined','Evaluation CI/CD gate before production promotion; baseline comparison enforced; cost-per-token benchmarked',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2871,312,4,'Governed','Continuous benchmarking with regression detection and stakeholder reporting','Automated regression alerts; benchmark results published to governance board; A/B test results inform retraining decisions','Evaluation dashboard live; model leaderboard maintained; statistical significance tested for A/B results',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2872,312,5,'Optimised','Self-improving evaluation with automated benchmark evolution','Evaluation frameworks auto-updated as models evolve; adversarial red-teaming continuous; benchmark drift detected and remediated','Red-team evaluation continuous; benchmark suite versioned alongside models; evaluation cost <2% of total AI spend',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2873,313,1,'Ad Hoc','No systematic bias testing; fairness not considered in model development','No bias metrics defined; protected attributes not tracked; no fairness audits','Models deployed without demographic analysis; bias discovered reactively post-deployment',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2874,313,2,'Emerging','Basic demographic analysis performed on request','Some disparate impact testing; no structured remediation process; ad hoc reviews','Fairness checks performed manually for high-profile models only; no tooling; no cadence',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2875,313,3,'Defined','Structured bias testing integrated into model lifecycle gates','Fairness metrics defined (demographic parity, equalised odds); bias testing pre-deployment; remediation playbook exists','Bias testing automated in evaluation pipeline; protected attribute analysis required for all customer-facing models; aligned to Australian AI Ethics Principles',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2876,313,4,'Governed','Continuous bias monitoring post-deployment with governance reporting','Bias drift monitored in production; fairness audit reports to risk committee quarterly; regulatory submissions ready','Bias dashboard live; third-party audits conducted annually; ISO/IEC TR 24027 aligned; NIST AI RMF MAP-2 evidenced',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2877,313,5,'Optimised','Proactive bias prevention embedded across data, model, and deployment pipeline','Bias prevention at data collection; counterfactual fairness by design; adversarial debiasing automated','Industry-leading fairness metrics; published AI fairness report; zero regulatory findings; benchmark for sector',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2878,314,1,'Ad Hoc','No explainability capability; black-box models deployed without explanation','No SHAP/LIME tooling; regulators cannot audit decisions; customer disputes cannot be resolved','All AI decisions opaque; no explanation logging; EU AI Act non-compliant for high-risk systems',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2879,314,2,'Emerging','Basic feature importance available for some models','SHAP implemented for selected models; no counterfactual explanations; no stakeholder-ready dashboards','Ad hoc explanations produced on request; not integrated into model serving; explanation latency unmanaged',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2880,314,3,'Defined','Standardised explainability framework integrated into model serving','SHAP/LIME or attention maps generated automatically; explanation API available; counterfactual generator for high-stakes decisions','Explanation pipeline automated; explanation quality reviewed in model governance; EU AI Act Article 13 requirements met for in-scope systems',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2881,314,4,'Governed','Explanation quality governed and auditable; regulatory submissions ready','Explanation fidelity metrics tracked; audit trail of explanations retained; business stakeholders trained on reading explanations','Regulatory-grade explanation documentation produced; explanation SLA defined; third-party audit passed',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2882,314,5,'Optimised','Explanation-by-design approach; interpretable models preferred where accuracy-equivalent','Intrinsically interpretable models selected where feasible; explanation quality improves continuously; explanations embedded in UX','Zero unexplained high-risk decisions; explanation latency <200ms p99; industry citation for XAI practice',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2883,315,1,'Ad Hoc','No AI-specific compliance framework; regulations not monitored','EU AI Act, APRA CPG 234, Australia AI Ethics not assessed; no AI risk register','AI deployments unclassified for regulatory risk; no horizon scanning; reactive to enforcement',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2884,315,2,'Emerging','Initial AI risk classification underway; some frameworks reviewed','EU AI Act risk tiers being mapped; some APRA guidance reviewed; informal risk register exists','Compliance efforts siloed; no cross-functional AI risk committee; no regulatory engagement plan',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2885,315,3,'Defined','AI risk register maintained; compliance obligations mapped and tracked','All AI systems classified under EU AI Act tiers; APRA CPG 234 gap assessment complete; compliance roadmap active','AI risk committee meeting quarterly; regulatory change monitored; conformity assessment process defined for high-risk AI',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2886,315,4,'Governed','Continuous compliance monitoring with regulatory engagement','Regulatory submissions prepared; post-market monitoring active for deployed systems; proactive engagement with APRA, ASIC, EU notified bodies','Compliance dashboard live; audit evidence maintained; regulatory enquiries responded to within SLA; zero material findings',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2887,315,5,'Optimised','Regulatory leadership; compliance embedded in AI product lifecycle by design','Regulatory participation in standards bodies (ISO SC 42, NIST AI RMF); compliance automation; industry benchmark for AI governance','Published AI compliance framework adopted by peers; zero enforcement actions; active contribution to regulatory design',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2888,316,1,'Ad Hoc','Forecasting done manually in spreadsheets; no ML models in production','No time-series models; forecasts based on intuition or simple averages; no accuracy tracking','Finance and operations forecasts produced manually; high variance; no feedback loop',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2889,316,2,'Emerging','Basic statistical forecasting models deployed for some use cases','Simple regression or ARIMA models for 1-2 use cases; accuracy tracked informally; no automated retraining','Models built in notebooks; deployed manually; limited to data science team use; no business integration',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2890,316,3,'Defined','Standardised forecasting platform with automated retraining and business integration','Forecasting CI/CD pipeline; ensemble models (gradient boosting, Prophet, LSTM) deployed; accuracy KPIs tracked; forecasts surfaced in business dashboards','Forecast accuracy reported to business leaders; retraining triggered by drift; 3+ use cases in production; business users trained',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2891,316,4,'Governed','Enterprise-wide forecasting capability with governed model lifecycle and business impact measurement','Forecast accuracy improvement tracked against baseline; financial value of forecasting quantified; model decisions auditable','Forecast governance board; ROI of forecasting investments reported; probabilistic forecasts with confidence intervals standard',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2892,316,5,'Optimised','Real-time adaptive forecasting with causal and external signal integration','Causal inference integrated; external data (macro, weather, market signals) enriching forecasts; forecasts update in near-real-time','Forecast error <5% MAPE for primary use cases; zero manual overrides; real-time streaming forecast pipeline operational',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2893,317,1,'Ad Hoc','No agentic AI capability; LLMs used in isolation only','No multi-agent systems; no tool-use frameworks; no autonomous workflow execution','LLM usage limited to chat interfaces; no integration with enterprise systems; no orchestration layer',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2894,317,2,'Emerging','Initial agent experiments; single-agent workflows in pilot','Basic tool-calling implemented for 1-2 use cases; human oversight manual; no enterprise guardrails','LangChain or similar framework in pilot; limited to data science team; no production deployment',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2895,317,3,'Defined','Agentic workflow framework operational with enterprise guardrails','Multi-agent orchestration (LangGraph, AutoGen) in production for defined use cases; human-in-the-loop checkpoints enforced; cost controls active','Agent framework deployed; escalation policies documented; agent actions logged; cost-per-run tracked; 3+ production agent workflows',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2896,317,4,'Governed','Agent governance board; agent risk assessment embedded in lifecycle; cross-enterprise agent reuse','Agent risk tiers defined; sensitive action approval workflows enforced; agent performance and cost reported to governance','Agent registry maintained; third-party agent risk assessed; audit trail complete; cross-team agent library with 10+ reusable agents',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2897,317,5,'Optimised','Self-improving agent systems with continuous evaluation and automated capability extension','Agents autonomously identify capability gaps and request extensions; adversarial testing of agent boundaries continuous; agent ROI tracked','Agent task success rate >95%; autonomous handling of Tier-1 enterprise workflows; benchmark for agentic AI in sector',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2898,318,1,'Ad Hoc','Keyword search only; no semantic or vector retrieval capability','No vector database; no embedding models; RAG not implemented; knowledge retrieval manual','Enterprise search limited to keyword index (SharePoint, Elasticsearch BM25); no AI-augmented retrieval',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2899,318,2,'Emerging','Semantic search piloted for specific knowledge domains','Embedding model selected; vector database in pilot (Pinecone, pgvector); basic RAG for 1-2 use cases','Retrieval quality not formally measured; chunking strategy ad hoc; hybrid search not implemented; no governance',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2900,318,3,'Defined','Hybrid search operational with governed knowledge base and retrieval quality metrics','Hybrid BM25 + dense retrieval deployed; MRR/NDCG tracked; chunking and indexing strategy documented; knowledge base lifecycle managed','3+ use cases in production; retrieval quality dashboard live; embedding model versioning managed; knowledge base refresh cadence defined',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2901,318,4,'Governed','Knowledge graph integration; retrieval quality continuously improved; enterprise knowledge lifecycle governed','Knowledge graph traversal augmenting vector search; entity linking active; retrieval quality improvement measured quarter-on-quarter','Knowledge governance board; retrieval SLA defined; data freshness SLA enforced; audit trail of knowledge base changes',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2902,318,5,'Optimised','Self-curating knowledge base with automated quality assurance and adaptive retrieval','Knowledge base automatically updated from authoritative sources; retrieval automatically adapts to query patterns; hallucination rate tracked and minimised','Retrieval precision >90% on benchmark sets; hallucination rate <2% in RAG responses; knowledge latency <1hr from source update',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2903,319,1,'Ad Hoc','GPU usage ad hoc; no managed AI compute platform','Cloud GPU provisioned manually per experiment; no scheduling; no cost visibility','GPU idle time high; compute costs untracked; no model serving infrastructure; CUDA environment conflicts common',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2904,319,2,'Emerging','Basic GPU cluster management; some scheduling in place','Kubernetes GPU operators configured; basic scheduling (job queuing); model serving ad hoc','Compute costs monitored but not optimised; no inference server; quantisation not applied; InfiniBand not managed',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2905,319,3,'Defined','Managed AI compute platform with scheduling, serving, and cost tracking','SLURM or Kubernetes GPU scheduling operational; Triton/vLLM inference server deployed; compute cost allocated to teams','GPU utilisation >60%; inference latency SLOs defined; quantisation applied to reduce serving cost; spot/preemptible GPU used for training',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2906,319,4,'Governed','Compute governance with financial accountability and efficiency benchmarks','GPU utilisation targets set and reported; compute cost per model tracked; optimisation recommendations automated','GPU utilisation >80%; cost-per-inference tracked by model; FinOps integration for AI compute; carbon footprint of AI compute reported',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2907,319,5,'Optimised','Elastic AI compute with automated optimisation across training and inference','Compute auto-scaling driven by inference demand; speculative decoding and continuous batching maximising GPU efficiency; multi-cluster orchestration','GPU utilisation >90%; zero idle GPU cost; inference cost reduction >40% vs baseline through optimisation; energy efficiency benchmark met',1);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2908,320,1,'Ad Hoc','The organizational mission exists but has little to no connection to cybersecurity considerations. Cybersecurity decisions are made reactively without reference to organizational mission or strategic objectives.','Mission statement lacks cybersecurity considerations | Cybersecurity decisions made in isolation from business strategy | No documented relationship between mission and security requirements | Ad-hoc security responses without mission alignment','Look for absence of documented connections between organizational mission and cybersecurity activities, with security treated as a separate technical function.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2909,320,2,'Defined','The organizational mission is clearly documented and leadership recognizes the need to align cybersecurity with mission objectives. Basic processes exist to consider mission impact when making cybersecurity decisions.','Mission statement acknowledges cybersecurity importance | Documented process for mission-aligned security decisions | Leadership awareness of mission-security relationship | Basic mission impact assessments for major security initiatives','Look for documented processes that explicitly connect organizational mission to cybersecurity decision-making, even if implementation is inconsistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2910,320,3,'Integrated','The organizational mission systematically drives cybersecurity strategy and risk management decisions across the enterprise. Cybersecurity objectives are derived from and aligned with mission-critical business processes and outcomes.','Cybersecurity strategy explicitly derived from organizational mission | Mission-critical assets and processes clearly identified and prioritized | Regular assessment of mission impact on security requirements | Cross-functional teams align security with business objectives','Look for systematic integration where cybersecurity strategies and risk decisions consistently reference and align with documented organizational mission and critical business processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2911,320,4,'Intelligent','The organization uses data analytics and threat intelligence to continuously optimize the alignment between mission objectives and cybersecurity investments. Mission-driven metrics and automated processes ensure cybersecurity resources are dynamically allocated based on mission criticality.','Data-driven mission impact analysis for cybersecurity investments | Automated monitoring of mission-critical system security posture | Predictive analytics link mission disruption to security events | Dynamic resource allocation based on mission priority and threat landscape','Look for evidence of data-driven optimization where analytics and intelligence actively inform how cybersecurity resources and attention are allocated based on mission impact.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2912,320,5,'Adaptive','The organization demonstrates a self-improving capability where mission understanding and cybersecurity alignment continuously evolve together. The organization proactively adapts its mission interpretation and cybersecurity approach based on emerging threats, business changes, and lessons learned.','Continuous refinement of mission-security alignment based on lessons learned | Proactive mission evolution considers emerging cyber threats | Self-optimizing security controls adapt to mission changes | Organization influences industry standards for mission-driven cybersecurity','Look for evidence of continuous organizational learning and adaptation where both mission understanding and cybersecurity approaches evolve together through feedback loops and proactive improvement.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2913,321,1,'Ad Hoc','The organization has limited awareness of who their internal and external stakeholders are regarding cybersecurity. Stakeholder identification occurs reactively, typically only when issues arise or when stakeholders directly raise concerns.','Stakeholder identification is inconsistent and reactive | No formal process exists to understand stakeholder cybersecurity expectations | Stakeholder cybersecurity needs are addressed on a case-by-case basis | Limited documentation of stakeholder requirements','Look for absence of systematic stakeholder identification processes and reactive responses to stakeholder cybersecurity concerns.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2914,321,2,'Defined','The organization has formally identified key internal and external stakeholders and documented their basic cybersecurity expectations. A defined process exists for understanding stakeholder needs, though it may not be consistently applied across all areas.','Formal stakeholder register includes cybersecurity considerations | Documented process for identifying stakeholder cybersecurity requirements | Basic stakeholder engagement activities are defined | Initial assessment of stakeholder risk tolerance completed','Look for documented stakeholder identification processes and evidence of formal capture of cybersecurity expectations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2915,321,3,'Integrated','Stakeholder cybersecurity needs and expectations are systematically captured and integrated into the organization''s risk management processes. Regular engagement occurs with stakeholders to ensure their evolving requirements are understood and addressed.','Stakeholder cybersecurity requirements integrated into risk assessment processes | Regular stakeholder engagement schedule established and followed | Stakeholder feedback mechanisms are operational | Cybersecurity requirements traceability maintained across business functions','Look for evidence of regular stakeholder engagement and integration of their cybersecurity requirements into organizational risk management practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2916,321,4,'Intelligent','The organization proactively analyzes stakeholder cybersecurity needs using data-driven insights and predictive approaches. Stakeholder expectations are continuously monitored and measured, with performance metrics used to optimize engagement strategies.','Data analytics used to predict stakeholder cybersecurity needs | Performance metrics track stakeholder satisfaction with cybersecurity measures | Automated monitoring of stakeholder requirement changes | Benchmarking against industry standards for stakeholder management','Look for evidence of data-driven stakeholder analysis and measurable approaches to understanding and meeting cybersecurity expectations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2917,321,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a dynamic, self-improving stakeholder management capability that automatically adapts to changing cybersecurity landscapes and stakeholder needs. Machine learning and advanced analytics enable predictive stakeholder requirement management and real-time optimization of cybersecurity risk approaches.','AI-driven stakeholder behavior analysis and requirement prediction | Automated adaptation of cybersecurity measures based on stakeholder feedback | Real-time stakeholder sentiment monitoring and response | Self-optimizing stakeholder engagement strategies','Look for evidence of automated, self-improving systems that predict and adapt to stakeholder cybersecurity needs in real-time.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2918,322,1,'Ad Hoc','Legal, regulatory, and contractual cybersecurity requirements are addressed reactively when issues arise or are discovered. The organization has minimal visibility into applicable obligations and relies on individual knowledge rather than systematic processes.','Cybersecurity obligations are identified only when problems occur | No centralized repository or tracking of legal/regulatory requirements | Compliance activities are performed inconsistently across different areas | Limited or no dedicated resources for regulatory compliance management','Look for reactive responses to compliance issues with no systematic approach to identifying or managing cybersecurity obligations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2919,322,2,'Defined','The organization has established basic processes to identify and document key legal, regulatory, and contractual cybersecurity requirements. Responsibilities for compliance management are assigned, though implementation may be inconsistent across the organization.','Documented inventory of major cybersecurity regulations and contractual obligations | Assigned roles and responsibilities for compliance management | Basic processes exist for reviewing new contracts and regulations | Periodic compliance assessments are conducted for key requirements','Look for documented processes and assigned responsibilities for managing cybersecurity obligations, even if implementation is not fully consistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2920,322,3,'Integrated','Legal, regulatory, and contractual cybersecurity requirements are systematically integrated into business processes and risk management activities. The organization maintains comprehensive tracking and ensures consistent compliance across all relevant areas.','Comprehensive compliance program integrated with cybersecurity governance | Regular monitoring and reporting of compliance status to leadership | Standardized contract review processes that include cybersecurity requirements | Cross-functional coordination between legal, compliance, and cybersecurity teams','Look for systematic integration of compliance requirements into cybersecurity governance with consistent implementation across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2921,322,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages advanced tools and analytics to proactively monitor regulatory changes and automatically assess compliance gaps. Predictive capabilities enable anticipation of future requirements and optimization of compliance strategies.','Automated tools monitor regulatory changes and assess impact on operations | Predictive analytics identify potential compliance risks before they materialize | Advanced metrics and dashboards provide real-time compliance visibility | Proactive engagement with regulators and industry bodies on emerging requirements','Look for advanced automation and predictive capabilities that enable proactive management of cybersecurity obligations with real-time monitoring.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2922,322,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously adapts its cybersecurity compliance approach based on dynamic threat landscapes, evolving regulations, and changing business contexts. Machine learning and AI capabilities enable self-optimizing compliance processes that anticipate and respond to regulatory evolution.','AI-driven compliance optimization adapts to changing regulatory landscape | Self-learning systems automatically adjust controls based on new requirements | Dynamic compliance frameworks that evolve with business and regulatory changes | Active contribution to industry standards and regulatory development processes','Look for self-adapting compliance systems that continuously evolve and optimize based on changing requirements with minimal human intervention.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2923,323,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities are undefined or exist only informally within the organization. When cybersecurity issues arise, individuals respond reactively without clear authority or accountability structures.','No documented cybersecurity roles or responsibilities | Cybersecurity tasks handled on ad-hoc basis by whoever is available | Unclear accountability when security incidents occur | Limited or no communication about who handles cybersecurity matters','Look for absence of documented cybersecurity roles and evidence that security responsibilities are handled reactively without clear ownership.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2924,323,2,'Defined','Basic cybersecurity roles and responsibilities are documented and assigned to specific individuals or teams. Clear lines of authority exist for cybersecurity decision-making, though implementation may be inconsistent across the organization.','Documented cybersecurity roles and responsibilities exist | Key cybersecurity positions are formally assigned | Basic reporting structures for cybersecurity are established | Some communication of roles to relevant stakeholders has occurred','Look for documented evidence of assigned cybersecurity roles with clear responsibilities and basic organizational communication of these assignments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2925,323,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities are well-integrated into broader organizational structures and consistently implemented across all business units. Regular communication and training ensure all personnel understand their cybersecurity responsibilities and accountability mechanisms are enforced.','Cybersecurity roles integrated into organizational charts and job descriptions | Regular training on cybersecurity responsibilities for all relevant personnel | Consistent implementation of roles across all business units | Established accountability mechanisms and performance measures for cybersecurity roles','Look for evidence that cybersecurity roles are systematically integrated into organizational operations with consistent implementation and regular reinforcement through training and accountability.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2926,323,4,'Intelligent','The organization continuously monitors the effectiveness of cybersecurity roles and responsibilities, using data-driven insights to optimize role definitions and assignments. Advanced metrics and analytics inform decisions about role evolution and resource allocation based on threat landscape changes and organizational needs.','Regular assessment and optimization of cybersecurity role effectiveness | Data-driven insights used to refine roles and responsibilities | Advanced metrics track performance of cybersecurity roles | Proactive adjustment of roles based on emerging threats and organizational changes','Look for evidence of systematic measurement and data-driven optimization of cybersecurity roles with proactive adjustments based on performance analytics and threat intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2927,323,5,'Adaptive','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities dynamically evolve in real-time based on changing threat conditions, business requirements, and lessons learned from the broader cybersecurity community. The organization maintains flexible, resilient role structures that can rapidly adapt while maintaining clear accountability and authority.','Dynamic role adaptation based on real-time threat intelligence and business changes | Flexible role structures that maintain accountability during rapid changes | Integration of external threat intelligence and industry best practices into role evolution | Advanced predictive capabilities for anticipating role and responsibility needs','Look for evidence of dynamic, real-time adaptation of cybersecurity roles with sophisticated predictive capabilities and seamless integration of external intelligence while maintaining organizational resilience.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2928,324,1,'Ad Hoc','Dependencies on external outcomes, capabilities, and services are poorly understood and exist primarily in individuals'' heads rather than documented systems. Communication about dependencies is reactive and occurs only when issues arise or during crisis situations.','No formal documentation of external dependencies exists | Dependency information is scattered across individuals and teams | Communication about dependencies happens only during incidents | Limited visibility into supply chain or third-party service risks','Look for absence of formal dependency documentation and evidence that dependency knowledge exists only in tribal knowledge without systematic communication.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2929,324,2,'Defined','Critical dependencies are identified and documented through established processes and procedures. Regular communication channels exist to share dependency information with relevant stakeholders, though this may be limited to specific teams or functions.','Documented inventory of critical third-party services and suppliers exists | Defined processes for identifying and cataloging dependencies | Regular reporting on dependency status to management | Clear ownership assigned for managing key dependencies','Look for formal documentation of dependencies and evidence of established processes for identifying and communicating about external dependencies to stakeholders.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2930,324,3,'Integrated','Dependency management is integrated across organizational functions with comprehensive mapping of interdependencies and cascading effects. Communication about dependencies is systematic and integrated into broader risk management and business continuity planning processes.','Comprehensive dependency mapping includes cascading effects and interdependencies | Integration with risk management and business continuity processes | Cross-functional collaboration on dependency assessment and management | Regular dependency reviews integrated into business planning cycles','Look for evidence of comprehensive dependency mapping that shows interconnections and cascading effects, with systematic integration into organizational planning and risk processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2931,324,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and monitoring provide real-time visibility into dependency health and performance with predictive capabilities. Communication is enhanced through automated alerts, dashboards, and intelligence-driven insights that enable proactive dependency management.','Real-time monitoring and analytics of dependency performance and health | Predictive analytics identify potential dependency failures before they occur | Automated alerting and dashboard reporting on dependency status | Intelligence-driven decision making for dependency optimization and risk mitigation','Look for advanced monitoring systems, predictive analytics capabilities, and evidence of proactive decision-making based on real-time dependency intelligence and automated reporting.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2932,324,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains dynamic, self-adjusting dependency management that automatically adapts to changing conditions and optimizes based on continuous learning. Communication systems provide contextual, personalized information that enables autonomous adjustment of dependencies based on real-time conditions and strategic objectives.','Autonomous dependency optimization based on real-time conditions and learning | Self-healing systems that automatically adjust to dependency changes or failures | Continuous learning algorithms improve dependency management strategies | Dynamic communication adapts to stakeholder needs and organizational context changes','Look for evidence of autonomous systems that self-adjust dependency management strategies and communication approaches based on continuous learning and real-time optimization of organizational outcomes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2933,325,1,'Ad Hoc','Risk management objectives are either absent or exist only informally without documented agreement from stakeholders. When objectives do exist, they are typically reactive responses to specific incidents rather than proactive strategic guidance.','No formally documented risk management objectives | Risk activities occur reactively in response to incidents | Stakeholder agreement on risk objectives is informal or non-existent | Risk management goals vary inconsistently across different areas of the organization','Look for absence of documented risk management objectives and lack of formal stakeholder agreement on risk management direction.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2934,325,2,'Defined','Basic risk management objectives have been documented and formally agreed upon by key organizational stakeholders. These objectives provide clear direction for risk management activities but may lack detailed implementation guidance or regular review processes.','Documented risk management objectives exist and are formally approved | Key stakeholders have explicitly agreed to the established objectives | Objectives provide clear direction for risk management activities | Regular review and update processes for objectives are defined but may not be consistently followed','Look for documented risk management objectives with evidence of formal stakeholder agreement and approval.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2935,325,3,'Integrated','Risk management objectives are well-integrated with business strategy and consistently applied across the organization. Stakeholders regularly review and update objectives to ensure alignment with changing business needs and risk landscape.','Risk objectives are clearly aligned with and support overall business strategy | Consistent application of risk objectives across all organizational units | Regular stakeholder review and update processes are established and followed | Risk objectives include measurable targets and success criteria','Look for evidence that risk management objectives are consistently applied organization-wide and regularly reviewed by stakeholders with clear alignment to business strategy.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2936,325,4,'Intelligent','Risk management objectives are data-driven and supported by comprehensive metrics and analytics that inform stakeholder decisions. The organization uses advanced risk intelligence to continuously optimize objectives based on performance data and emerging risk trends.','Risk objectives are informed by comprehensive data analytics and risk intelligence | Automated monitoring and reporting systems track progress against objectives | Stakeholders receive real-time dashboards and risk metrics to inform decision-making | Predictive analytics help anticipate needed adjustments to risk objectives','Look for evidence of data-driven risk objectives supported by advanced analytics, automated monitoring, and intelligent reporting systems that inform stakeholder decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2937,325,5,'Adaptive','Risk management objectives dynamically adapt to changing conditions through continuous learning and automated adjustment mechanisms. The organization maintains a self-improving risk management framework that evolves objectives based on emerging threats, business changes, and stakeholder feedback in real-time.','Automated systems continuously adapt risk objectives based on changing conditions | Machine learning and AI support dynamic optimization of risk management goals | Real-time stakeholder feedback loops enable immediate objective refinement | Risk objectives automatically align with emerging business opportunities and threat landscapes','Look for evidence of automated, adaptive systems that continuously evolve risk management objectives based on real-time conditions, stakeholder input, and emerging risk intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2938,326,1,'Ad Hoc','Risk appetite and tolerance are undefined or inconsistently understood across the organization. Risk-related decisions are made reactively without clear guidance on acceptable risk levels. There is little to no documentation of organizational risk boundaries or preferences.','No formal risk appetite or tolerance statements exist | Risk decisions are made inconsistently across business units | Leadership provides ad-hoc guidance on risk acceptance | Risk tolerance varies significantly between similar situations','Assessor should confirm the absence of documented risk appetite and tolerance statements and evidence of inconsistent risk decision-making across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2939,326,2,'Defined','Basic risk appetite and tolerance statements have been developed and documented. These statements provide general guidance for risk decision-making but may lack specificity or comprehensive coverage of all risk types. Communication of these statements is limited and may not reach all relevant stakeholders.','Formal risk appetite and tolerance statements exist but may be high-level | Statements are approved by senior leadership | Limited communication of risk statements to key stakeholders | Risk statements may not cover all business areas or risk types','Assessor should verify the existence of documented risk appetite and tolerance statements that have been formally approved but may lack comprehensive implementation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2940,326,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive risk appetite and tolerance statements are established, regularly communicated across the organization, and integrated into business processes. These statements are specific enough to guide consistent risk decision-making and are actively used by management in strategic and operational decisions. Regular review and maintenance processes ensure statements remain current.','Detailed risk appetite and tolerance statements cover all major risk categories | Statements are actively communicated organization-wide | Risk statements are integrated into business decision-making processes | Regular review and update processes are established','Assessor should confirm that comprehensive risk statements exist, are actively used in decision-making, and demonstrate evidence of regular communication and maintenance.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2941,326,4,'Intelligent','Risk appetite and tolerance statements are dynamically informed by advanced analytics, threat intelligence, and business performance data. The organization uses sophisticated metrics and monitoring to track adherence to risk statements and automatically alerts management when risk levels approach tolerance thresholds. Risk statements are continuously optimized based on emerging risks and business strategy evolution.','Risk statements are supported by advanced analytics and real-time monitoring | Automated alerting systems notify management of risk threshold approaches | Risk appetite is dynamically adjusted based on threat intelligence and business conditions | Sophisticated metrics track risk statement adherence across the organization','Assessor should validate the presence of advanced analytics supporting risk statements, automated monitoring systems, and evidence of dynamic adjustment capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2942,326,5,'Adaptive','Risk appetite and tolerance statements are continuously and automatically adapted based on real-time risk intelligence, predictive modeling, and changing business conditions. The organization maintains an adaptive risk management ecosystem that self-adjusts risk parameters while maintaining alignment with strategic objectives. Risk statements evolve proactively to address emerging threats and opportunities before they fully materialize.','Fully automated risk appetite adjustment based on predictive models and real-time intelligence | Self-learning systems continuously optimize risk tolerance parameters | Proactive risk statement evolution anticipates emerging threats and opportunities | Seamless integration with adaptive business strategy and operations','Assessor should confirm the existence of fully automated, self-adapting risk appetite systems that demonstrate predictive capabilities and seamless integration with business strategy evolution.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2943,327,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity risk management operates independently from enterprise risk management with minimal coordination. Risk activities are fragmented and cybersecurity risks are managed in isolation from other business risks.','Cybersecurity risks are tracked separately from business risks | No formal integration between cybersecurity and enterprise risk teams | Risk reporting occurs through different channels and formats | Ad hoc communication about cyber risks to enterprise risk management','Look for evidence that cybersecurity risk activities operate in silos with no systematic integration into enterprise risk management processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2944,327,2,'Defined','Basic processes exist to incorporate cybersecurity risks into enterprise risk management frameworks. Standard procedures define how cybersecurity risks should be communicated and escalated to enterprise risk functions.','Documented processes for cybersecurity risk reporting to enterprise risk management | Regular meetings between cybersecurity and enterprise risk teams | Cybersecurity risks included in enterprise risk registers | Standardized risk taxonomy covers cybersecurity domains','Look for documented processes and evidence of regular, structured communication between cybersecurity and enterprise risk management functions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2945,327,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity risk management is systematically integrated into enterprise risk management processes with consistent methodologies and shared governance. Risk decisions consider cybersecurity impacts alongside other business risks using unified frameworks.','Unified risk assessment methodology covers cybersecurity and business risks | Cybersecurity personnel participate in enterprise risk committees | Integrated risk dashboards include cybersecurity metrics | Cross-functional risk response planning incorporates cybersecurity considerations','Look for evidence of systematic integration where cybersecurity risks are consistently managed using the same frameworks, governance, and decision-making processes as other enterprise risks.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2946,327,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence capabilities enhance the integration of cybersecurity risks into enterprise risk management. Data-driven insights enable predictive risk modeling and automated correlation between cybersecurity events and business impact.','Automated correlation between cybersecurity threats and business risk scenarios | Predictive modeling incorporates cybersecurity risk factors | Real-time risk dashboards provide integrated cyber-business risk views | Machine learning enhances risk prioritization across domains','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation, and predictive capabilities that enhance how cybersecurity risks are integrated with and inform enterprise risk management decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2947,327,5,'Adaptive','The organization demonstrates dynamic, self-improving integration of cybersecurity risk management that continuously evolves based on changing threat landscapes and business contexts. Integration processes automatically adapt to emerging risks and optimize enterprise risk management effectiveness.','Self-adapting risk models adjust to new cyber threats and business changes | Continuous optimization of integration processes based on outcomes | Dynamic risk appetite adjustment based on cybersecurity posture | Automated risk scenario generation considers evolving cyber-business interdependencies','Look for evidence of adaptive, self-improving capabilities where cybersecurity risk integration continuously evolves and optimizes based on changing conditions and lessons learned.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2948,328,1,'Ad Hoc','Risk response decisions are made reactively on a case-by-case basis without formal guidance or strategic direction. There is no established framework for determining appropriate risk response options across the organization.','Risk responses vary significantly between incidents | No documented risk response strategy or guidelines | Decision-making authority for risk responses is unclear | Risk response options are not consistently communicated','Look for absence of documented risk response guidance and inconsistent approaches to handling similar risks across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2949,328,2,'Defined','Basic strategic direction for risk management has been documented, outlining standard risk response options such as accept, mitigate, transfer, or avoid. This guidance is communicated to relevant stakeholders but may not be consistently applied across all business areas.','Documented risk response strategy exists | Standard risk response options are defined (accept, mitigate, transfer, avoid) | Risk response guidance is communicated to key stakeholders | Basic criteria for selecting response options are established','Look for documented risk response strategy that defines standard options and has been communicated to stakeholders, even if implementation is inconsistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2950,328,3,'Integrated','Strategic direction for risk management is well-integrated across business functions with clear risk response criteria and decision-making processes. Risk response options are consistently applied and aligned with organizational risk appetite and business objectives.','Risk response strategy is integrated across all business functions | Clear decision-making processes and authorities are established | Risk responses are consistently aligned with risk appetite | Regular communication and training on risk response options occurs','Look for evidence that risk response strategy is consistently implemented across the organization with clear processes and regular reinforcement through training and communication.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2951,328,4,'Intelligent','Risk response strategies leverage data analytics and performance metrics to optimize decision-making and resource allocation. The organization uses predictive capabilities and trend analysis to proactively adjust risk response approaches based on changing conditions.','Risk response decisions are supported by data analytics and metrics | Predictive capabilities inform proactive risk response adjustments | Performance of risk responses is continuously monitored and measured | Advanced risk modeling supports strategic direction','Look for evidence of data-driven risk response decisions, predictive analytics capabilities, and continuous performance monitoring that informs strategic adjustments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2952,328,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a highly adaptive risk management strategy that automatically adjusts risk response options based on real-time threat intelligence, business context, and emerging risks. Strategic direction evolves dynamically while maintaining alignment with organizational objectives and stakeholder expectations.','Real-time adaptation of risk response strategies based on threat intelligence | Automated adjustment of risk response options based on changing conditions | Dynamic alignment with evolving business objectives and stakeholder expectations | Continuous innovation in risk response approaches','Look for evidence of real-time, automated adaptation of risk response strategies that dynamically align with changing threat landscapes and business conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2953,329,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity risk communication occurs sporadically and informally across the organization. Communication about risks from suppliers and third parties is inconsistent and typically reactive to incidents or issues as they arise.','Ad-hoc emails or meetings about cybersecurity issues | No formal communication channels or protocols established | Third-party risks communicated only during crisis situations | Communication depends on individual initiative rather than process','Look for evidence of informal, reactive communication with no established channels or processes for cybersecurity risk information sharing.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2954,329,2,'Defined','Formal communication channels and protocols are established for cybersecurity risks within the organization. Basic procedures exist for communicating risks from suppliers and third parties, though implementation may be inconsistent across different business units.','Documented communication protocols for cybersecurity risks | Designated points of contact for cybersecurity communication | Regular reporting structures for internal cybersecurity risks | Basic third-party risk communication procedures established','Look for documented communication protocols and designated roles, even if implementation varies across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2955,329,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity risk communication is systematically integrated across all organizational levels and business functions. Comprehensive communication flows exist for both internal risks and those from suppliers and third parties, with consistent implementation organization-wide.','Integrated risk communication across all business units | Systematic escalation procedures for different risk levels | Regular stakeholder communication including third-party risks | Coordinated communication between internal teams and external partners','Look for evidence of systematic, organization-wide implementation of risk communication with consistent processes across all functions and clear third-party integration.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2956,329,4,'Intelligent','Communication systems leverage advanced analytics and intelligence to prioritize and tailor cybersecurity risk messages based on audience, risk severity, and business context. Automated systems support real-time communication of critical risks from both internal and external sources.','Risk-based prioritization of communication content | Automated alerts and communication systems for critical risks | Tailored communication based on audience and business context | Advanced analytics informing communication strategies for third-party risks','Look for evidence of intelligent, data-driven communication systems that automatically prioritize and customize risk information based on context and analytics.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2957,329,5,'Adaptive','Communication systems continuously evolve and self-optimize based on effectiveness metrics, changing threat landscapes, and organizational learning. The organization maintains dynamic communication networks that automatically adapt to new risks and stakeholder needs including emerging third-party risk scenarios.','Self-optimizing communication systems based on effectiveness metrics | Dynamic adaptation to emerging threats and risk scenarios | Continuous learning and improvement of communication strategies | Predictive communication for anticipated risks from suppliers and third parties','Look for evidence of communication systems that demonstrate continuous evolution, self-optimization, and predictive capabilities that adapt automatically to changing risk environments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2958,330,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity risk responses are handled reactively on a case-by-case basis with no established process or methodology. Risk management decisions are made informally by individuals without consistent documentation or organizational guidance.','Risk responses are improvised when incidents occur | No documented risk management procedures exist | Decision-making authority for risk responses is unclear | Risk management activities are not communicated across the organization','Look for absence of documented risk response procedures and evidence that risk management decisions are made reactively without established processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2959,330,2,'Defined','A basic standardized process for cybersecurity risk management has been documented and established. The process includes defined steps for risk identification, assessment, and response, with clear roles and responsibilities assigned.','Documented risk management process exists with defined steps | Roles and responsibilities for risk management are clearly assigned | Standard risk response options are defined (accept, avoid, mitigate, transfer) | Process has been communicated to relevant stakeholders','Look for documented risk management procedures that define standard processes, roles, and response options that have been communicated to the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2960,330,3,'Integrated','The standardized risk response process is consistently implemented across the organization and integrated with other business processes. Risk management activities are regularly executed according to the defined process with appropriate governance oversight.','Risk management process is consistently followed organization-wide | Process is integrated with business planning and decision-making | Regular risk assessments and reviews are conducted according to schedule | Risk management activities are tracked and reported to leadership','Look for evidence that the risk management process is consistently applied across the organization and integrated with broader business operations and governance.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2961,330,4,'Intelligent','The risk response process leverages data analytics and metrics to optimize decision-making and resource allocation. Performance of risk management activities is continuously monitored and measured to identify trends and improve effectiveness.','Risk management decisions are supported by data analytics and metrics | Key performance indicators track effectiveness of risk responses | Process performance is regularly analyzed for optimization opportunities | Risk management tools provide automated insights and recommendations','Look for evidence that risk management decisions are data-driven with established metrics and analytics that inform process optimization and resource allocation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2962,330,5,'Adaptive','The risk response process continuously evolves and adapts based on changing threat landscape, business context, and lessons learned. The organization proactively adjusts its risk management approach using predictive analytics and emerging intelligence.','Process automatically adapts to changing risk landscape and threat intelligence | Predictive analytics inform proactive risk management decisions | Continuous learning mechanisms improve process effectiveness over time | Risk management approach influences and shapes industry best practices','Look for evidence that the risk management process continuously evolves and adapts proactively based on predictive analytics, threat intelligence, and organizational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2963,331,1,'Ad Hoc','The organisation has no formal recognition or consideration of strategic cybersecurity opportunities. Any identification of positive risks occurs randomly through individual insights rather than systematic processes.','No documented process for identifying strategic opportunities | Cybersecurity discussions focus solely on threats and vulnerabilities | Strategic opportunities identified sporadically by individuals | No integration of positive risks in risk registers','Look for absence of any formal process to identify or discuss strategic cybersecurity opportunities, with risk discussions focusing exclusively on negative impacts.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2964,331,2,'Defined','The organisation has established basic processes to identify and document strategic cybersecurity opportunities. There is awareness of positive risks and some effort to include them in risk management discussions.','Basic process exists for identifying strategic opportunities | Strategic opportunities are documented in risk registers | Some inclusion of positive risks in cybersecurity risk discussions | Limited integration with broader business strategy discussions','Look for documented processes and evidence that strategic opportunities are regularly identified and recorded, though integration may be limited.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2965,331,3,'Integrated','Strategic cybersecurity opportunities are systematically characterised and consistently integrated into organisational risk discussions. There is clear alignment between cybersecurity opportunities and business objectives.','Systematic characterisation of strategic opportunities with defined criteria | Regular integration of positive risks in executive and board-level discussions | Clear linkage between cybersecurity opportunities and business strategy | Established metrics for measuring opportunity realisation','Look for systematic integration of strategic opportunities in regular risk discussions with clear connections to business strategy and measurable outcomes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2966,331,4,'Intelligent','The organisation uses advanced analytics and intelligence to proactively identify and optimise strategic cybersecurity opportunities. Data-driven insights inform opportunity prioritisation and investment decisions.','Advanced analytics used to identify emerging strategic opportunities | Predictive modelling for opportunity assessment and prioritisation | Real-time monitoring of opportunity realisation metrics | Integration with threat intelligence to identify market advantages','Look for evidence of advanced analytical capabilities and data-driven decision making in identifying and prioritising strategic cybersecurity opportunities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2967,331,5,'Adaptive','The organisation continuously evolves its approach to strategic opportunities through machine learning and adaptive processes. Strategic opportunity identification and realisation capabilities self-improve based on outcomes and changing threat landscapes.','Continuous learning algorithms enhance opportunity identification processes | Adaptive frameworks that evolve based on realised outcomes | Real-time adjustment of opportunity strategies based on threat landscape changes | Automated integration of external intelligence sources for opportunity discovery','Look for self-improving systems that automatically adapt opportunity identification and realisation processes based on outcomes, feedback, and environmental changes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2968,332,1,'Ad Hoc','Leadership has minimal awareness of cybersecurity responsibilities and accountability is unclear or non-existent. Cybersecurity is viewed as an IT problem rather than a business risk, with sporadic or reactive engagement from senior management.','No formal assignment of cybersecurity accountability to leadership roles | Cybersecurity discussions absent from board or executive meetings | Leadership involvement only occurs after security incidents | No established cybersecurity culture or messaging from leadership','Assessor should look for absence of documented leadership cybersecurity responsibilities and minimal evidence of executive engagement in cybersecurity matters.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2969,332,2,'Defined','Leadership roles and cybersecurity responsibilities are formally documented and assigned. Senior management demonstrates basic understanding of cybersecurity risks but cultural change initiatives are limited or inconsistent.','Formal documentation of leadership cybersecurity roles and responsibilities | Designated executive sponsor or champion for cybersecurity | Regular cybersecurity reporting to senior management | Basic cybersecurity awareness messaging from leadership','Assessor should look for documented assignment of cybersecurity accountability and evidence of regular leadership engagement through meetings and communications.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2970,332,3,'Integrated','Leadership actively demonstrates cybersecurity accountability through consistent decision-making and resource allocation. A risk-aware culture is being systematically developed with leadership modeling expected behaviors and integrating cybersecurity into business processes.','Leadership regularly participates in cybersecurity decision-making and risk discussions | Cybersecurity performance metrics included in executive accountability frameworks | Structured culture change programs with leadership participation | Cybersecurity considerations integrated into strategic planning processes','Assessor should look for evidence of leadership actively participating in cybersecurity governance and systematic efforts to build organizational cybersecurity culture.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2971,332,4,'Intelligent','Leadership leverages data-driven insights to make informed cybersecurity decisions and demonstrates sophisticated understanding of cyber risk. The organization exhibits a mature risk-aware culture with embedded ethical practices and continuous improvement mechanisms driven by leadership example.','Leadership uses cybersecurity metrics and threat intelligence to guide strategic decisions | Established feedback mechanisms to measure and improve cybersecurity culture | Leadership actively promotes ethical behavior and continuous learning | Advanced governance structures with clear escalation and decision-making processes','Assessor should look for evidence of data-driven cybersecurity leadership decisions and mature cultural practices with measurable continuous improvement initiatives.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2972,332,5,'Adaptive','Leadership demonstrates dynamic and anticipatory cybersecurity accountability that evolves with changing threat landscapes and business contexts. The organization exhibits a self-improving, adaptive culture where cybersecurity excellence is deeply embedded in organizational DNA and continuously refined through innovation.','Leadership proactively adapts cybersecurity strategy based on emerging threats and business changes | Organization serves as a cybersecurity culture benchmark for industry peers | Innovation in cybersecurity governance practices with continuous experimentation | Leadership demonstrates thought leadership in cybersecurity risk management','Assessor should look for evidence of anticipatory and innovative cybersecurity leadership that influences industry practices and demonstrates continuous cultural evolution.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2973,333,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities are undefined, informal, or exist only at a high level without clear delineation. Staff members may assume cybersecurity duties reactively when issues arise, often without clear authority or accountability structures.','No formal cybersecurity role definitions or job descriptions | Cybersecurity responsibilities assigned reactively during incidents | Unclear authority structures for cybersecurity decision-making | Limited or no communication of cybersecurity expectations to staff','Assessor should look for absence of formal cybersecurity role documentation and evidence that cybersecurity duties are handled informally or reactively.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2974,333,2,'Defined','Basic cybersecurity roles, responsibilities, and authorities are documented and assigned to specific individuals or teams. These definitions are communicated to relevant staff, though enforcement and understanding may be inconsistent across the organization.','Documented cybersecurity roles and responsibilities exist | Key cybersecurity positions are formally assigned | Basic communication of roles through policies or procedures | Some evidence of role-based accountability for cybersecurity tasks','Assessor should look for documented cybersecurity role definitions with clear assignments and evidence of basic communication to relevant personnel.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2975,333,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity roles, responsibilities, and authorities are well-defined, consistently communicated organization-wide, and integrated into job descriptions and performance management. Regular training and awareness programs ensure staff understand their cybersecurity obligations.','Cybersecurity responsibilities integrated into job descriptions and performance metrics | Regular training programs on cybersecurity roles and expectations | Clear escalation paths and decision-making authorities established | Consistent enforcement of cybersecurity responsibilities across departments','Assessor should look for integration of cybersecurity roles into formal HR processes and evidence of consistent understanding and enforcement across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2976,333,4,'Intelligent','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities are dynamically managed with clear metrics and regular assessment of effectiveness. The organization uses data-driven approaches to optimize role assignments and continuously improves role clarity based on emerging threats and organizational changes.','Metrics tracked for cybersecurity role effectiveness and compliance | Regular assessment and optimization of role assignments | Data-driven approach to identifying gaps in responsibilities | Automated systems support role-based access and accountability','Assessor should look for evidence of measurement, monitoring, and data-driven optimization of cybersecurity role effectiveness and assignments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2977,333,5,'Adaptive','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities automatically adapt to changing threat landscapes, business contexts, and organizational structures. The organization maintains a self-optimizing system that continuously evolves role definitions and authorities based on real-time risk intelligence and predictive analytics.','Automated adaptation of roles based on threat intelligence and risk changes | Predictive analytics inform role evolution and resource allocation | Real-time adjustment of authorities and responsibilities during incidents | Continuous learning systems optimize role effectiveness and coverage','Assessor should look for evidence of automated, predictive, and self-optimizing systems that continuously evolve cybersecurity roles based on changing conditions and intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2978,334,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity resource allocation is reactive and inconsistent, typically driven by immediate incidents or crises. Resources are allocated without clear connection to cybersecurity risks or strategic priorities, often resulting in under-resourced security functions.','No formal cybersecurity budget or resource planning process | Security staffing levels determined arbitrarily without risk assessment | Security tools and technologies acquired reactively after incidents | Resources allocated based on availability rather than cybersecurity needs','Look for absence of systematic resource planning with cybersecurity investments made only in response to incidents or immediate pressures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2979,334,2,'Defined','Basic cybersecurity resource allocation processes are documented and follow established procedures. Resources are allocated based on defined cybersecurity roles and responsibilities, though alignment with actual risk levels may be inconsistent.','Documented cybersecurity budget with defined allocation categories | Established staffing levels for key cybersecurity roles | Standard procurement processes for security tools and technologies | Basic resource allocation tied to documented cybersecurity policies','Look for documented resource allocation processes that connect to defined cybersecurity roles and responsibilities, even if risk alignment is limited.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2980,334,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity resource allocation is systematically aligned with risk assessments and integrated across business functions. Resources are allocated based on comprehensive understanding of cybersecurity risks and strategic objectives, with regular review and adjustment processes.','Resource allocation directly tied to cybersecurity risk assessment outcomes | Cross-functional coordination of cybersecurity resource planning | Regular review and adjustment of resource allocation based on changing risks | Integration of cybersecurity resource needs into enterprise resource planning','Look for systematic integration of risk-based resource allocation that spans organizational functions and includes regular review mechanisms.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2981,334,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and metrics drive cybersecurity resource allocation decisions with predictive capabilities. Resource allocation is optimized through data-driven insights, performance metrics, and continuous monitoring of resource effectiveness against cybersecurity outcomes.','Data analytics used to optimize cybersecurity resource allocation | Predictive modeling for future cybersecurity resource needs | Performance metrics track resource effectiveness and ROI | Automated resource allocation adjustments based on threat intelligence and risk changes','Look for evidence of data-driven resource optimization with measurable outcomes and predictive capabilities for future resource needs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2982,334,5,'Adaptive','Cybersecurity resource allocation is fully adaptive and self-optimizing, with real-time adjustment capabilities based on dynamic risk conditions. The organization demonstrates continuous learning and innovation in resource allocation strategies, with seamless adaptation to emerging threats and changing business conditions.','Real-time adaptive resource allocation based on dynamic risk conditions | Machine learning optimizes resource distribution automatically | Continuous innovation in resource allocation approaches | Seamless integration with ecosystem partners for resource sharing and optimization','Look for evidence of autonomous, real-time resource adaptation with continuous learning mechanisms that innovate resource allocation approaches.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2983,335,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity considerations are rarely or inconsistently included in human resources practices. HR activities such as hiring, onboarding, training, and offboarding occur without systematic integration of cybersecurity requirements.','No formal cybersecurity requirements in job descriptions | Background checks performed inconsistently or not at all | Ad hoc or missing cybersecurity awareness during onboarding | Offboarding processes lack systematic access revocation procedures','Look for minimal or sporadic inclusion of cybersecurity elements in HR processes with no documented procedures or consistent application.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2984,335,2,'Defined','Basic cybersecurity requirements are documented and included in key HR processes. Standard procedures exist for incorporating cybersecurity into hiring, onboarding, training, and employee lifecycle management activities.','Documented cybersecurity requirements integrated into HR policies | Background checks required for sensitive positions | Basic cybersecurity awareness included in onboarding process | Standardized offboarding checklist includes access termination','Look for documented HR procedures that systematically include cybersecurity requirements across major HR processes with evidence of consistent implementation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2985,335,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity is comprehensively embedded throughout all HR practices with role-based requirements and regular monitoring. HR and cybersecurity teams collaborate effectively to ensure security considerations are consistently applied across the employee lifecycle.','Role-based cybersecurity requirements integrated across all HR processes | Regular cybersecurity training and awareness programs implemented | Insider threat considerations incorporated into HR practices | Performance management includes cybersecurity responsibilities','Look for comprehensive integration where cybersecurity requirements are tailored to different roles and consistently applied with evidence of cross-functional collaboration between HR and security teams.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2986,335,4,'Intelligent','HR practices leverage data analytics and automated tools to enhance cybersecurity integration and decision-making. The organization uses metrics and behavioral analysis to optimize security-related HR processes and identify potential risks.','Automated tools support cybersecurity-integrated HR processes | Behavioral analytics used to identify insider threat indicators | Metrics track effectiveness of cybersecurity HR practices | Predictive capabilities inform hiring and security clearance decisions','Look for evidence of data-driven HR processes that use analytics, automation, and metrics to enhance cybersecurity integration and enable proactive risk management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2987,335,5,'Adaptive','HR cybersecurity practices continuously evolve through advanced analytics, machine learning, and real-time adaptation to emerging threats. The organization dynamically adjusts HR security requirements based on threat intelligence, business context, and predictive risk modeling.','Machine learning enhances insider threat detection and prevention | Real-time adaptation of HR security practices based on threat landscape | Continuous optimization through advanced analytics and feedback loops | Dynamic role-based security requirements adjust automatically to risk levels','Look for evidence of continuously evolving HR cybersecurity practices that leverage advanced technologies and real-time threat intelligence to dynamically adapt security requirements and processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2988,336,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity policies are either non-existent or exist only as informal, undocumented practices. Any security measures are reactive and implemented on an as-needed basis without consideration of organizational context or strategic alignment.','No formal cybersecurity policy documentation exists | Security decisions are made reactively without documented guidance | Individual departments or staff handle cybersecurity matters inconsistently | Leadership has limited visibility into cybersecurity practices','Look for absence of formal cybersecurity policy documentation and evidence that security practices are handled informally or reactively without organizational guidance.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2989,336,2,'Defined','Basic cybersecurity policies have been documented and approved by leadership. The policies address fundamental security requirements but may lack comprehensive coverage of organizational context and strategic alignment.','Written cybersecurity policy exists and is formally approved | Policy covers basic security requirements and responsibilities | Communication of policy to staff has occurred through standard channels | Basic enforcement mechanisms are in place','Look for documented cybersecurity policies that have been formally approved and communicated, with evidence of basic enforcement mechanisms being applied.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2990,336,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive cybersecurity policies are well-established, regularly reviewed, and clearly aligned with organizational strategy and risk appetite. Policies are consistently communicated across the organization and systematically enforced with defined consequences.','Policy framework comprehensively covers organizational cybersecurity risks | Regular policy review and update processes are established | Policy enforcement is consistent with documented consequences | Staff training and awareness programs support policy compliance','Look for comprehensive policy frameworks that demonstrate clear alignment with organizational strategy, systematic enforcement mechanisms, and evidence of regular review and update processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2991,336,4,'Intelligent','Cybersecurity policies are dynamically informed by continuous risk assessment, threat intelligence, and organizational changes. The policy framework includes automated monitoring and enforcement capabilities with data-driven policy effectiveness measurement.','Policies are regularly updated based on threat intelligence and risk assessments | Automated policy monitoring and compliance tracking systems are implemented | Policy effectiveness is measured through key performance indicators | Integration with business processes ensures policy relevance','Look for evidence that policies are continuously updated based on threat intelligence and risk data, with automated monitoring systems and measurable effectiveness indicators in place.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2992,336,5,'Adaptive','The cybersecurity policy framework continuously evolves and self-adjusts based on real-time threat landscape changes, organizational transformation, and predictive analytics. Policies serve as a strategic enabler for business innovation while maintaining optimal security posture.','Predictive analytics inform proactive policy adjustments | Policy framework adapts in real-time to emerging threats and business changes | Continuous optimization based on advanced metrics and stakeholder feedback | Policy innovation supports business agility and competitive advantage','Look for evidence of predictive analytics driving policy evolution, real-time adaptation capabilities, and policies that demonstrably enable business innovation while maintaining security effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2993,337,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity policies exist but are rarely reviewed or updated in a systematic manner. Updates occur reactively, often only after incidents or when compliance demands require immediate attention. Policy communication and enforcement is inconsistent across the organization.','Policies have not been reviewed in over 2 years | Updates are made only after security incidents or audit findings | No formal process exists for policy review and approval | Staff are often unaware of current policy versions','Look for evidence of outdated policies, reactive-only updates, and lack of systematic review processes or schedules.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2994,337,2,'Defined','A formal process exists for reviewing and updating cybersecurity policies on a scheduled basis. Policy updates are documented and communicated through established channels. Basic enforcement mechanisms are in place, though consistency may vary across different organizational units.','Policies are reviewed annually or bi-annually on a defined schedule | Formal approval process exists for policy updates | Policy changes are communicated through official channels | Basic compliance monitoring is conducted','Look for documented review schedules, formal approval processes, and evidence of regular policy updates being communicated to relevant stakeholders.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2995,337,3,'Integrated','Policy review and updates are integrated with risk management processes and consider changes in threat landscape, technology, and business requirements. Policy updates are consistently communicated across all organizational levels with clear accountability for compliance. Enforcement is systematic with regular monitoring and corrective actions.','Policy reviews incorporate threat intelligence and risk assessments | Updates consider business changes and emerging technologies | Training is provided when policies are updated | Compliance is monitored with metrics and regular reporting','Look for evidence that policy updates are driven by risk assessments, threat intelligence, and business changes, with consistent enforcement and compliance monitoring across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2996,337,4,'Intelligent','Policy management leverages data analytics and intelligence to proactively identify when updates are needed based on threat trends, technology changes, and organizational evolution. Automated systems support policy distribution, tracking, and compliance monitoring. Policy effectiveness is measured and used to drive continuous improvements.','Automated systems track policy compliance and effectiveness | Data analytics inform when policy updates are needed | Policy impact is measured through key performance indicators | Stakeholder feedback is systematically collected and incorporated','Look for evidence of data-driven policy management, automated compliance tracking systems, and measurable outcomes that demonstrate policy effectiveness and drive improvements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2997,337,5,'Adaptive','Policy management is fully adaptive and self-improving, using artificial intelligence and machine learning to predict policy gaps and automatically trigger reviews based on emerging threats, regulatory changes, and organizational shifts. The organization continuously optimizes its policy framework based on real-time intelligence and predictive analytics.','AI/ML systems predict policy needs and trigger proactive updates | Real-time threat intelligence automatically influences policy reviews | Policy framework adapts dynamically to organizational and environmental changes | Continuous optimization based on predictive analytics and outcome measurement','Look for evidence of AI/ML-driven policy management, predictive capabilities that anticipate policy needs, and a self-optimizing policy framework that adapts in real-time to changing conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2998,338,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity strategy reviews occur sporadically or only in response to major incidents or external pressure. Reviews are typically informal, lack structured processes, and may not result in meaningful strategy adjustments.','Reviews triggered only by incidents or crises | No formal review schedule or process | Limited documentation of review outcomes | Strategy adjustments are reactive and inconsistent','Look for evidence that cybersecurity strategy reviews happen irregularly without established processes or consistent follow-through on findings.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(2999,338,2,'Defined','Formal processes exist for reviewing cybersecurity strategy outcomes on a scheduled basis. Reviews follow documented procedures and involve designated stakeholders, though the process may not be consistently applied across all areas.','Scheduled review meetings with defined agenda | Documented review procedures and responsibilities | Basic metrics tracked for strategy effectiveness | Review findings documented with some action items identified','Look for established review processes with documented procedures and evidence of regular scheduled reviews being conducted.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3000,338,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity strategy reviews are integrated into broader organizational governance processes and occur consistently. Reviews utilize comprehensive metrics and stakeholder input to systematically evaluate strategy effectiveness and drive coordinated improvements.','Reviews integrated with business planning cycles | Comprehensive metrics dashboard for strategy outcomes | Cross-functional stakeholder participation in reviews | Systematic tracking and implementation of review recommendations','Look for evidence that cybersecurity strategy reviews are embedded in organizational governance with comprehensive metrics and consistent implementation of improvements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3001,338,4,'Intelligent','Reviews leverage advanced analytics and threat intelligence to provide deep insights into strategy performance. The organization uses predictive analysis and benchmarking to anticipate needed strategy adjustments before gaps become critical.','Advanced analytics used to assess strategy effectiveness | Predictive modeling for future risk scenarios | Benchmarking against industry standards and peers | Proactive strategy adjustments based on trend analysis','Look for sophisticated analytical capabilities that enable predictive insights and proactive strategy optimization based on comprehensive data analysis.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3002,338,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a continuous, real-time review capability that automatically adapts cybersecurity strategy based on evolving threat landscapes and business conditions. Strategy adjustments are dynamic, evidence-based, and seamlessly implemented across the enterprise.','Real-time monitoring of strategy performance indicators | Automated alerts for strategy effectiveness thresholds | Dynamic strategy adaptation based on threat intelligence feeds | Continuous optimization through machine learning and AI-driven insights','Look for evidence of real-time, adaptive review capabilities that automatically trigger strategy adjustments based on continuous monitoring and advanced analytical insights.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3003,339,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity risk management strategy reviews occur sporadically or only when prompted by incidents or external requirements. There is no systematic approach to evaluating whether the strategy covers organizational requirements and risks. Reviews are reactive and lack structured processes or clear criteria.','Reviews triggered only by incidents or compliance deadlines | No formal process for strategy evaluation | Limited documentation of review findings | Ad-hoc involvement of stakeholders','Evidence shows cybersecurity strategy reviews happen irregularly with no formal process or systematic evaluation of organizational coverage.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3004,339,2,'Defined','A formal process exists for reviewing the cybersecurity risk management strategy on a scheduled basis. The organization has defined procedures for assessing strategy coverage against organizational requirements and risks. Reviews follow documented processes but may not be consistently executed across all areas.','Documented review process and schedule established | Defined criteria for evaluating strategy coverage | Regular review meetings with key stakeholders | Basic documentation of review outcomes and adjustments','Evidence demonstrates a documented, scheduled process for reviewing cybersecurity strategy with defined evaluation criteria and stakeholder involvement.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3005,339,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity strategy reviews are consistently integrated with broader business planning cycles and risk management processes. The organization systematically evaluates strategy effectiveness and alignment with evolving organizational requirements. Review processes incorporate multiple perspectives and data sources for comprehensive assessment.','Strategy reviews integrated with business planning cycles | Systematic evaluation using multiple data sources | Cross-functional involvement in review process | Regular tracking of strategy performance metrics','Evidence shows cybersecurity strategy reviews are consistently integrated with business processes and systematically evaluate coverage using comprehensive assessment methods.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3006,339,4,'Intelligent','The organization uses advanced analytics and continuous monitoring to inform cybersecurity strategy reviews and adjustments. Data-driven insights from threat intelligence, risk assessments, and performance metrics automatically trigger strategy evaluations. The review process leverages predictive capabilities to anticipate future organizational requirements and emerging risks.','Automated monitoring triggers for strategy reviews | Advanced analytics inform strategy adjustments | Predictive assessment of future requirements and risks | Real-time dashboard tracking of strategy effectiveness','Evidence demonstrates the use of advanced analytics and continuous monitoring to automatically inform and trigger intelligent cybersecurity strategy reviews and adjustments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3007,339,5,'Adaptive','The cybersecurity risk management strategy dynamically adapts in real-time based on continuous learning from internal and external environments. The organization maintains a self-optimizing system that automatically adjusts strategy elements based on emerging threats, changing business conditions, and lessons learned. Strategy evolution is seamlessly integrated with organizational transformation and innovation processes.','Real-time strategy adaptation based on environmental changes | Self-optimizing system with machine learning capabilities | Seamless integration with organizational transformation processes | Continuous feedback loops from multiple intelligence sources','Evidence shows a self-optimizing cybersecurity strategy that dynamically adapts in real-time through automated learning and continuous integration with organizational evolution.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3008,340,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity performance evaluation occurs sporadically, typically only after significant incidents or when prompted by external requirements. Reviews are informal, inconsistent, and lack structured methodology or documentation.','Performance reviews triggered only by incidents or compliance deadlines | No formal evaluation criteria or metrics defined | Limited or no documentation of review findings | Ad-hoc reporting to leadership without regular schedule','Look for evidence that cybersecurity performance evaluation happens reactively with minimal structure, documentation, or consistency.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3009,340,2,'Defined','Basic cybersecurity performance evaluation processes are established with defined procedures and metrics. Regular reviews occur according to a documented schedule, though analysis may be limited and adjustments are made slowly.','Documented cybersecurity performance evaluation procedures exist | Basic metrics and KPIs are defined and measured | Scheduled reviews occur at defined intervals | Review findings are documented and reported to management','Look for documented evaluation processes with defined metrics that are consistently followed on a regular schedule.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3010,340,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity performance evaluation is integrated with broader organizational risk management and business processes. Comprehensive metrics align with business objectives, and review findings consistently drive timely program adjustments.','Performance metrics aligned with business objectives and risk appetite | Regular trend analysis and benchmarking against industry standards | Review findings systematically drive program improvements | Integration with enterprise risk management processes','Look for comprehensive evaluation processes that are integrated with business objectives and consistently drive meaningful program adjustments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3011,340,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence capabilities enable sophisticated cybersecurity performance evaluation with predictive insights. Automated monitoring and reporting systems provide real-time visibility, enabling proactive adjustments based on emerging trends and threats.','Advanced analytics and predictive modeling used in performance evaluation | Real-time monitoring and automated reporting capabilities | Proactive identification of performance gaps and emerging risks | Evidence-based decision making using multiple data sources','Look for advanced analytical capabilities that provide predictive insights and enable proactive, data-driven performance improvements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3012,340,5,'Adaptive','Cybersecurity performance evaluation continuously evolves through machine learning and AI-driven insights, automatically adapting evaluation criteria and thresholds based on changing threat landscapes and business context. The organization demonstrates leading practices that influence industry standards.','AI/ML-driven performance evaluation with self-adapting criteria | Continuous optimization of metrics based on threat intelligence and business changes | Industry leadership in performance evaluation practices | Dynamic adjustment of evaluation frameworks in response to emerging risks','Look for evidence of AI/ML-driven evaluation systems that continuously adapt and evolve, with the organization demonstrating industry-leading practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3013,341,1,'Ad Hoc','The organisation has minimal or no formal cybersecurity supply chain risk management programme in place. Supply chain cybersecurity considerations are handled reactively when issues arise, with no consistent approach or stakeholder agreement on processes.','No documented supply chain cybersecurity policies or procedures | Supply chain security activities are reactive and incident-driven | Limited or no stakeholder awareness of supply chain cybersecurity risks | Vendor security assessments are performed inconsistently if at all','Evidence shows absence of formal documentation and processes, with supply chain cybersecurity managed reactively without stakeholder coordination.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3014,341,2,'Defined','A basic cybersecurity supply chain risk management programme has been established with documented policies and procedures. Key stakeholders have agreed to the programme structure, though implementation may be inconsistent across the organisation.','Documented supply chain cybersecurity policy and basic procedures exist | Key stakeholders have formally acknowledged the programme | Basic vendor security assessment processes are defined | Supply chain risk management roles and responsibilities are documented','Evidence demonstrates formal documentation of supply chain cybersecurity programme with stakeholder agreement, though implementation consistency may vary.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3015,341,3,'Integrated','The cybersecurity supply chain risk management programme is well-integrated into broader organisational risk management and business processes. Regular monitoring and consistent implementation across all relevant business units demonstrates organisational maturity.','Supply chain cybersecurity is integrated with enterprise risk management | Consistent implementation across all business units and procurement processes | Regular monitoring and reporting of supply chain cybersecurity metrics | Supply chain security requirements are embedded in vendor contracts and SLAs','Evidence shows consistent, organisation-wide implementation with supply chain cybersecurity integrated into standard business and risk management processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3016,341,4,'Intelligent','The organisation employs advanced analytics and intelligence to enhance supply chain risk management decisions. Data-driven insights inform programme improvements and enable predictive risk identification across the supply chain ecosystem.','Advanced analytics and threat intelligence inform supply chain risk decisions | Automated monitoring and assessment tools provide real-time visibility | Predictive risk modelling identifies emerging supply chain threats | Continuous improvement processes driven by performance metrics and threat landscape changes','Evidence demonstrates use of advanced analytics, automation, and threat intelligence to drive intelligent, data-informed supply chain risk management decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3017,341,5,'Adaptive','The cybersecurity supply chain risk management programme dynamically adapts to changing threat landscapes, business needs, and regulatory requirements. The organisation demonstrates industry leadership through innovation and sharing of best practices with supply chain partners.','Programme automatically adapts to emerging threats and changing business requirements | Real-time collaboration and information sharing with supply chain partners | Innovation in supply chain security practices influences industry standards | Continuous optimisation based on machine learning and AI-driven insights','Evidence shows a self-adapting programme that responds dynamically to changes while demonstrating industry leadership and innovation in supply chain cybersecurity practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3018,342,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities for suppliers, customers, and partners are undefined or inconsistently applied. Communication about cybersecurity expectations occurs on an informal, case-by-case basis with limited coordination between internal teams and external parties.','Verbal or informal agreements on cybersecurity responsibilities | Inconsistent communication of security expectations to third parties | Ad hoc coordination during security incidents | Limited or no documentation of supplier cybersecurity roles','Look for absence of formal documentation defining cybersecurity roles and responsibilities for third parties, with evidence of informal or reactive approaches to supplier security coordination.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3019,342,2,'Defined','Basic cybersecurity roles and responsibilities for suppliers, customers, and partners are documented and formally communicated. Standard processes exist for establishing and communicating these responsibilities, though coordination may still be limited to specific business units or functions.','Documented cybersecurity roles and responsibilities in contracts or agreements | Standardized communication templates for security expectations | Designated points of contact for cybersecurity coordination | Basic supplier security requirements clearly defined','Look for formal documentation and standardized processes that define and communicate cybersecurity roles and responsibilities to third parties, even if implementation is not yet fully coordinated across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3020,342,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities for suppliers, customers, and partners are consistently established, communicated, and coordinated across all relevant business functions. Integration between internal teams ensures aligned expectations and coordinated management of third-party cybersecurity responsibilities.','Cross-functional coordination of supplier cybersecurity requirements | Regular communication and review of third-party security responsibilities | Integrated approach to managing customer and partner security expectations | Consistent enforcement of cybersecurity roles across all third-party relationships','Look for evidence of coordinated, organization-wide approach to establishing and managing cybersecurity roles and responsibilities with third parties, including regular communication and cross-functional alignment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3021,342,4,'Intelligent','Cybersecurity roles and responsibilities for third parties are dynamically managed using data-driven insights and automated coordination mechanisms. The organization leverages intelligence about supplier capabilities, threat landscapes, and performance metrics to optimize role definitions and communication strategies.','Automated monitoring and reporting of third-party cybersecurity performance | Data-driven adjustment of supplier security responsibilities based on risk profiles | Intelligent coordination tools that facilitate real-time communication | Performance metrics used to optimize role definitions and expectations','Look for evidence of data-driven optimization of third-party cybersecurity roles and responsibilities, including automated monitoring capabilities and intelligent coordination mechanisms that enhance communication effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3022,342,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a continuously evolving and self-improving approach to cybersecurity roles and responsibilities for suppliers, customers, and partners. The system adapts in real-time to changing threat landscapes, business relationships, and regulatory requirements while driving innovation in third-party cybersecurity coordination practices.','Self-adapting frameworks for third-party cybersecurity roles based on emerging threats | Continuous learning and improvement of coordination mechanisms | Real-time adjustment of responsibilities based on changing business and threat contexts | Innovation in cybersecurity coordination practices that influence industry standards','Look for evidence of continuous adaptation and innovation in third-party cybersecurity role management, including self-improving systems that respond to emerging threats and changing business contexts while contributing to industry best practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3023,343,1,'Ad Hoc','Supply chain cybersecurity risks are managed reactively and in isolation from broader risk management processes. There is little to no formal integration between supply chain risk activities and enterprise risk management or cybersecurity programs.','Supply chain risk activities occur sporadically and independently | No formal connection between supply chain assessments and enterprise risk processes | Cybersecurity supply chain considerations are addressed only when incidents occur | Limited documentation of supply chain risk management activities','Assessor should confirm that supply chain cybersecurity risk management operates independently with no systematic integration into enterprise processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3024,343,2,'Defined','Basic processes exist for integrating supply chain cybersecurity risk management into enterprise risk frameworks. Documented procedures outline how supply chain risks should be incorporated into risk assessments and cybersecurity programs.','Documented procedures for integrating supply chain risks into enterprise risk management | Supply chain risk considerations included in formal risk assessment templates | Basic reporting mechanisms connect supply chain risks to cybersecurity leadership | Initial coordination between procurement and cybersecurity teams established','Assessor should verify that documented processes exist that explicitly describe integration of supply chain cybersecurity risks into broader organizational risk management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3025,343,3,'Integrated','Supply chain cybersecurity risk management is systematically integrated into enterprise risk management, cybersecurity programs, and organizational improvement processes. Cross-functional coordination ensures consistent application of integrated approaches across the organization.','Supply chain cybersecurity risks consistently included in enterprise risk registers | Regular coordination meetings between supply chain, cybersecurity, and enterprise risk teams | Integrated risk assessment processes include supply chain cybersecurity as standard component | Supply chain risk findings systematically inform improvement initiatives','Assessor should confirm that supply chain cybersecurity risk management is consistently and systematically embedded within existing organizational risk and cybersecurity processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3026,343,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence capabilities enable dynamic integration of supply chain cybersecurity risks with enterprise-wide risk management. Data-driven insights automatically inform risk assessments and trigger coordinated response across multiple organizational functions.','Automated systems correlate supply chain intelligence with enterprise risk data | Real-time dashboards provide integrated view of supply chain cybersecurity risks | Predictive analytics inform proactive supply chain risk management decisions | Machine learning capabilities enhance supply chain risk assessment accuracy','Assessor should identify advanced analytical capabilities that automatically integrate supply chain cybersecurity intelligence into enterprise risk management systems.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3027,343,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously evolves its integrated supply chain risk management approach based on emerging threats, changing business requirements, and lessons learned. Self-improving systems automatically adapt integration mechanisms to optimize organizational resilience.','Integration mechanisms automatically adapt based on threat landscape changes | Continuous learning systems improve supply chain risk integration effectiveness | Dynamic risk models adjust in real-time to supply chain context changes | Self-optimizing processes enhance cross-functional coordination based on performance feedback','Assessor should observe evidence of self-adapting systems that continuously improve the integration of supply chain cybersecurity risk management based on evolving conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3028,344,1,'Ad Hoc','The organization has minimal awareness of its suppliers and lacks a comprehensive inventory. Supplier identification occurs reactively when issues arise or contracts are renewed, with no systematic approach to cataloging or prioritizing suppliers based on criticality.','No centralized supplier inventory exists | Supplier information is scattered across departments or individuals | Critical suppliers are not formally identified or differentiated | Supplier discovery happens only during incidents or contract renewals','Look for the absence of any structured supplier inventory and reactive identification of suppliers only when problems occur.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3029,344,2,'Defined','The organization maintains a basic supplier inventory with documented processes for identifying and cataloging suppliers. Initial efforts are made to categorize suppliers by criticality, though the criteria and methodology may be inconsistent or incomplete.','Basic supplier inventory exists with key contact information | Documented process for adding new suppliers to inventory | Initial criticality categories defined but may lack detail | Supplier inventory is maintained but may not be current or complete','Look for evidence of a documented supplier inventory process and basic criticality categorization, even if implementation is inconsistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3030,344,3,'Integrated','The organization maintains a comprehensive and current supplier inventory with well-defined criticality criteria consistently applied across all business units. Supplier prioritization is integrated into procurement and risk management processes with regular updates and validation.','Complete supplier inventory with standardized criticality criteria | Regular inventory updates and validation processes | Supplier criticality integrated into procurement decisions | Cross-functional coordination ensures inventory completeness and accuracy','Look for a comprehensive, regularly updated supplier inventory with consistent criticality assessment integrated across business processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3031,344,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages automated tools and data analytics to maintain real-time supplier inventory and dynamic criticality assessments. Advanced metrics and risk indicators inform supplier prioritization, with predictive capabilities identifying potential supply chain vulnerabilities.','Automated supplier discovery and inventory management tools | Dynamic criticality scoring based on multiple risk factors | Real-time monitoring of supplier status and risk indicators | Predictive analytics identify emerging supplier risks or dependencies','Look for automated inventory management with dynamic risk-based prioritization and predictive analytics capabilities for supplier assessment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3032,344,5,'Adaptive','The organization''s supplier inventory system continuously evolves and self-optimizes based on threat intelligence, market conditions, and business changes. Machine learning enhances criticality assessments and the system automatically adapts prioritization criteria based on emerging risks and lessons learned.','Self-optimizing inventory system that adapts to changing conditions | Machine learning improves criticality assessments over time | Automated integration of external threat intelligence and market data | System learns from supply chain incidents to refine supplier prioritization','Look for evidence of a self-adapting supplier inventory system that continuously improves its criticality assessments through machine learning and external intelligence integration.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3033,345,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity requirements for suppliers are inconsistently included in agreements, often as an afterthought or in response to specific incidents. When requirements are included, they tend to be generic, boilerplate language without consideration of specific risks or supplier criticality.','Cybersecurity clauses missing from most supplier contracts | Generic security language copied from templates when present | No systematic approach to identifying which suppliers need security requirements | Requirements developed reactively after security incidents','Look for evidence that cybersecurity requirements in supplier agreements are sporadic, generic, and developed without systematic risk consideration.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3034,345,2,'Defined','Standard cybersecurity requirements have been documented and are systematically included in supplier agreements. Requirements are based on established policies and cover key security areas, though they may not be tailored to specific supplier risks or criticality levels.','Documented standard cybersecurity requirements for supplier agreements | Consistent inclusion of security clauses in new contracts | Requirements cover key areas like data protection and incident reporting | Basic risk-based categorisation of suppliers for different requirement sets','Look for evidence of documented, standardised cybersecurity requirements that are consistently applied to supplier agreements with basic risk differentiation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3035,345,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity requirements are systematically integrated into all supplier relationship management processes and tailored based on comprehensive risk assessments. Requirements are prioritised according to supplier criticality, data access levels, and specific threat landscapes relevant to each supplier relationship.','Risk-based tailoring of requirements for different supplier categories | Integration with broader supplier risk management processes | Regular review and updating of contractual security requirements | Cross-functional collaboration between procurement, legal, and cybersecurity teams','Look for evidence that cybersecurity requirements are risk-based, integrated across supplier management processes, and regularly maintained through cross-functional collaboration.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3036,345,4,'Intelligent','Cybersecurity requirements in supplier agreements are dynamically optimised based on continuous threat intelligence, supplier performance data, and automated risk analytics. The organisation leverages advanced metrics and predictive capabilities to proactively adjust requirements and identify emerging supply chain risks.','Threat intelligence integration into requirement development | Automated monitoring of supplier security performance against contractual obligations | Predictive analytics to identify high-risk supplier relationships | Dynamic adjustment of requirements based on changing risk profiles','Look for evidence of intelligent, data-driven optimisation of supplier cybersecurity requirements using threat intelligence, performance analytics, and predictive risk assessment capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3037,345,5,'Adaptive','The organisation maintains a fully adaptive supply chain cybersecurity requirements framework that automatically evolves based on machine learning insights, real-time threat landscapes, and continuous ecosystem feedback. Requirements are dynamically personalised for each supplier relationship and automatically trigger adaptive responses to emerging risks.','Machine learning-driven requirement optimisation and personalisation | Real-time adaptive responses to emerging supply chain threats | Automated contract amendment processes for critical security updates | Ecosystem-wide sharing and learning from supply chain security intelligence','Look for evidence of autonomous, machine learning-enabled adaptation of supplier cybersecurity requirements with real-time threat response and ecosystem-wide intelligence sharing capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3038,346,1,'Ad Hoc','Supplier planning and due diligence activities are informal and inconsistent across the organization. Risk assessments of potential suppliers are performed on an ad-hoc basis with no standardized approach or criteria.','No formal supplier risk assessment process exists | Due diligence activities vary significantly between procurement teams | Limited or no documentation of supplier cybersecurity requirements | Supplier selection decisions made without consistent security considerations','Look for absence of formal processes and inconsistent application of supplier security assessments across different organizational units.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3039,346,2,'Defined','Basic supplier due diligence processes and procedures are documented and implemented. The organization has established minimum cybersecurity requirements for suppliers and conducts standardized risk assessments before entering into supplier relationships.','Documented supplier cybersecurity requirements and assessment procedures | Standard due diligence questionnaires or checklists are used | Basic risk categorization of suppliers is performed | Security considerations are formally included in supplier selection criteria','Look for documented processes, standard assessment tools, and evidence that security requirements are consistently applied during supplier selection.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3040,346,3,'Integrated','Supplier planning and due diligence processes are integrated with broader organizational risk management and procurement activities. Risk assessments are tailored based on supplier criticality and data sensitivity, with clear approval workflows and governance oversight.','Risk-based approach with different assessment levels for different supplier types | Integration between procurement, security, and risk management teams | Executive approval required for high-risk supplier relationships | Due diligence results influence contract terms and ongoing monitoring requirements','Look for risk-based differentiation in assessment approaches and clear integration between security, procurement, and risk management functions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3041,346,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and threat intelligence inform supplier risk assessments and due diligence activities. The organization leverages automation, external risk ratings, and continuous monitoring capabilities to enhance pre-contract risk evaluation and decision-making.','Use of third-party risk rating services and external threat intelligence | Automated collection and analysis of supplier security posture data | Predictive risk modeling informs supplier selection decisions | Real-time risk alerts influence pre-contract evaluations','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, external intelligence sources, and automated tools that enhance traditional due diligence processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3042,346,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously evolves its supplier planning and due diligence capabilities based on emerging threats, industry best practices, and lessons learned. AI-driven insights and dynamic risk modeling enable proactive adaptation of assessment criteria and processes to address evolving cyber risks.','Machine learning algorithms continuously improve risk assessment accuracy | Dynamic adjustment of due diligence requirements based on threat landscape changes | Collaborative intelligence sharing with industry peers enhances supplier risk insights | Self-optimizing processes adapt to new supplier risk patterns','Look for evidence of continuous process improvement, AI-driven capabilities, and dynamic adaptation of due diligence approaches based on evolving threat intelligence and organizational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3043,347,1,'Ad Hoc','The organization has minimal or inconsistent understanding of supplier-related cybersecurity risks. Risk identification and management activities for critical suppliers occur sporadically, often in response to incidents or when specifically requested, with little to no formal documentation or systematic approach.','Limited or no formal supplier risk assessment processes | Reactive approach to supplier security issues | Minimal documentation of supplier risks or controls | Ad hoc communication with suppliers about security requirements','Look for absence of formal supplier risk management processes and predominantly reactive, undocumented responses to supplier security concerns.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3044,347,2,'Defined','The organization has established basic processes and procedures for identifying and assessing cybersecurity risks from critical suppliers. Standard risk assessment templates and criteria are defined, though implementation may be inconsistent across different supplier relationships and business units.','Documented supplier risk assessment procedures and templates | Basic risk categorization and prioritization criteria established | Regular security questionnaires or assessments for critical suppliers | Initial supplier risk register or tracking mechanism implemented','Look for documented procedures and evidence of regular risk assessments being conducted for critical suppliers, even if implementation varies across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3045,347,3,'Integrated','Supplier cybersecurity risk management is systematically integrated across procurement, vendor management, and security functions. The organization consistently applies standardized risk assessment methodologies and maintains comprehensive tracking of supplier risks throughout the relationship lifecycle.','Integrated supplier risk management across business functions | Consistent application of risk assessment methodologies | Comprehensive supplier risk monitoring and reporting mechanisms | Established risk response and mitigation strategies for different risk levels','Look for evidence of systematic integration between procurement, security, and vendor management functions with consistent risk management practices across all critical supplier relationships.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3046,347,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages advanced analytics, threat intelligence, and automated monitoring to enhance supplier risk visibility and decision-making. Risk assessments incorporate real-time threat data and predictive capabilities to proactively identify and address emerging supplier-related cybersecurity risks.','Advanced analytics and threat intelligence integrated into supplier risk assessments | Automated monitoring and alerting for supplier security posture changes | Predictive risk modeling for supplier relationships | Data-driven optimization of supplier risk management strategies','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation, and threat intelligence being actively used to enhance supplier risk identification, assessment, and response capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3047,347,5,'Adaptive','The supplier cybersecurity risk management program continuously evolves and adapts based on emerging threats, lessons learned, and changing business requirements. The organization demonstrates industry leadership through innovative approaches and actively contributes to supplier risk management best practices.','Continuous improvement and adaptation of supplier risk management practices | Innovation in supplier security risk assessment and monitoring techniques | Active contribution to industry standards and best practices | Dynamic risk management strategies that evolve with threat landscape','Look for evidence of continuous innovation, adaptation, and industry leadership in supplier cybersecurity risk management practices that evolve proactively with emerging threats and business needs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3048,348,1,'Ad Hoc','Third-party involvement in incident activities occurs sporadically and reactively, typically only when incidents directly impact supplier systems or services. There are no formal processes or agreements defining how suppliers should participate in incident planning, response, or recovery activities.','Suppliers are contacted ad-hoc only when their services are directly affected by incidents | No formal incident notification requirements exist in supplier contracts | Third-party involvement in incident response is inconsistent and unplanned | Incident recovery activities with suppliers are handled case-by-case without standardized procedures','Look for reactive, informal supplier involvement in incidents with no documented processes or contractual requirements for third-party participation in incident activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3049,348,2,'Defined','Basic incident reporting requirements and processes are documented and included in supplier contracts and agreements. Key suppliers are identified and have defined roles in incident response activities, though implementation may be inconsistent across different supplier relationships.','Incident notification requirements are included in supplier contracts and service agreements | Key suppliers are identified and have documented incident response contact information | Basic incident escalation procedures involving third parties are defined | Supplier incident reporting timelines and communication channels are established','Look for documented incident reporting requirements in contracts and basic processes that define supplier roles, even if implementation is not fully consistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3050,348,3,'Integrated','Suppliers and third parties are systematically integrated into incident planning, response, and recovery activities through standardized processes and regular coordination. Incident response plans include specific supplier roles and responsibilities, with established communication channels and escalation procedures.','Suppliers participate in incident response planning and tabletop exercises | Integrated incident communication systems include relevant third parties | Supplier incident response capabilities are assessed and validated regularly | Joint incident recovery procedures are established and tested with key suppliers','Look for systematic integration of suppliers in incident processes with evidence of regular testing, validation, and coordinated response activities across the supplier ecosystem.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3051,348,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and threat intelligence are used to proactively identify supplier-related incident risks and optimize third-party involvement in response activities. Real-time monitoring and automated systems enable rapid coordination with suppliers during incidents, with continuous improvement based on incident metrics and supplier performance data.','Threat intelligence and risk analytics inform supplier incident response strategies | Automated incident notification and coordination systems integrate supplier response capabilities | Supplier incident response performance is continuously monitored and analyzed | Predictive capabilities help anticipate supplier-related incident impacts and optimize response coordination','Look for evidence of analytics-driven supplier incident management with automated coordination systems and continuous optimization based on performance metrics and threat intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3052,348,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a dynamic, self-improving ecosystem for supplier incident management that automatically adapts based on emerging threats, changing business conditions, and lessons learned. Advanced AI and machine learning capabilities enable predictive supplier risk management and autonomous optimization of third-party incident response coordination.','AI-driven systems automatically adapt supplier incident response strategies based on evolving threat landscape | Self-learning algorithms optimize supplier coordination and resource allocation during incidents | Dynamic supplier incident response capabilities adjust in real-time based on business context and risk conditions | Autonomous systems predict and prevent supplier-related incidents through advanced analytics','Look for autonomous, AI-driven systems that continuously adapt supplier incident management strategies with evidence of self-improving processes and predictive capabilities that evolve without manual intervention.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3053,349,1,'Ad Hoc','Supply chain security assessments occur sporadically and are not integrated into broader risk management processes. Supplier security practices are evaluated on an ad-hoc basis, typically only when issues arise or during initial procurement decisions.','Supplier security assessments conducted reactively or inconsistently | No formal integration between supply chain security and enterprise risk management | Limited or no ongoing monitoring of supplier security performance throughout product lifecycles | Security assessments vary significantly across different procurement activities','Look for evidence of reactive, inconsistent supplier security assessments with no systematic integration into enterprise risk management processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3054,349,2,'Defined','Formal processes exist for conducting supplier security assessments and integrating them into cybersecurity risk management programmes. Basic monitoring procedures are established for tracking supplier security performance during the technology lifecycle.','Documented procedures for supplier security assessments and integration requirements | Formal processes link supply chain security to cybersecurity risk management programmes | Basic monitoring mechanisms track supplier security performance | Standard security assessment criteria applied consistently across suppliers','Look for documented processes that formally integrate supplier security assessments into cybersecurity risk management with basic monitoring capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3055,349,3,'Integrated','Supply chain security assessments are fully integrated across cybersecurity and enterprise risk management programmes with comprehensive lifecycle monitoring. Security performance data is regularly collected and used to inform risk decisions throughout the supplier relationship.','Supply chain security fully integrated across both cybersecurity and enterprise risk management | Comprehensive monitoring covers entire technology product and service lifecycles | Regular performance data collection and analysis drives risk-based decisions | Cross-functional coordination between procurement, risk, and security teams','Look for comprehensive integration across all risk management programmes with systematic lifecycle monitoring and regular performance-based decision making.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3056,349,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence capabilities enable sophisticated supplier security risk assessment and monitoring. Automated systems provide real-time insights into supplier security posture and performance trends, enabling proactive risk management decisions.','Advanced analytics and automated monitoring provide real-time supplier security insights | Predictive capabilities identify potential security risks before they materialize | Intelligent systems correlate supplier performance data with broader threat intelligence | Dynamic risk scoring adjusts supplier management strategies based on evolving security posture','Look for advanced analytics and automation that provide predictive insights and real-time supplier security intelligence for proactive risk management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3057,349,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously evolves its supplier security integration approach based on emerging threats, changing business needs, and ecosystem feedback. Self-improving systems automatically adjust assessment criteria and monitoring parameters to optimize supply chain security outcomes.','Continuous improvement processes automatically adapt supplier security integration approaches | Self-learning systems optimize assessment criteria and monitoring based on outcomes | Dynamic integration adjusts to emerging threats and changing business requirements | Ecosystem-wide collaboration enhances collective supply chain security intelligence','Look for evidence of continuous adaptation and self-improving systems that automatically evolve supplier security integration based on threat landscape changes and performance outcomes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3058,350,1,'Ad Hoc','The organization has minimal or no formal planning for cybersecurity activities that occur after partnerships or service agreements end. Post-contract cybersecurity considerations are handled reactively on a case-by-case basis with no standardized approach.','No documented procedures for post-contract cybersecurity activities | Data and asset recovery handled informally when agreements end | Limited consideration of ongoing cybersecurity risks after partnership termination | Reactive approach to addressing security issues after contract conclusion','Look for absence of documented post-contract cybersecurity procedures and evidence of purely reactive, informal handling of security matters when partnerships end.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3059,350,2,'Defined','The organization has documented basic procedures for cybersecurity activities that should occur when partnerships or service agreements conclude. These procedures are standardized but may not be consistently implemented across all contract terminations.','Documented procedures exist for post-contract cybersecurity activities | Basic data recovery and asset return processes defined | Standard security requirements included in contract termination clauses | Inconsistent application of procedures across different partnerships','Look for documented procedures covering post-contract cybersecurity activities, even if implementation is inconsistent or limited in scope.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3060,350,3,'Integrated','Post-contract cybersecurity procedures are consistently integrated into all partnership agreements and systematically executed when contracts end. The organization has established processes for data sanitization, asset recovery, and ongoing risk monitoring after partnership termination.','Consistent implementation of post-contract security procedures across all partnerships | Integrated data sanitization and secure asset return processes | Regular monitoring of residual risks after contract termination | Clear accountability and ownership for post-contract security activities','Look for consistent implementation of comprehensive post-contract security procedures across all partnership terminations with clear accountability structures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3061,350,4,'Intelligent','The organization uses data-driven insights and automated tools to optimize post-contract cybersecurity activities. Procedures are risk-based and tailored according to the sensitivity of partnerships, with continuous monitoring of effectiveness and improvement opportunities.','Risk-based approach to post-contract security activities based on partnership sensitivity | Automated tools support data discovery and secure deletion processes | Continuous monitoring and measurement of post-contract security effectiveness | Data-driven optimization of termination procedures based on lessons learned','Look for evidence of risk-based, automated approaches to post-contract security with continuous monitoring and data-driven optimization of procedures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3062,350,5,'Adaptive','Post-contract cybersecurity procedures continuously evolve based on threat intelligence, emerging risks, and partnership ecosystem changes. The organization proactively anticipates and adapts to new post-contract security challenges while sharing insights with industry partners.','Dynamic adaptation of procedures based on emerging threats and partnership ecosystem changes | Predictive modeling to anticipate post-contract security risks | Industry collaboration and intelligence sharing on post-contract security practices | Continuous innovation in post-contract security approaches and technologies','Look for evidence of dynamic, predictive approaches to post-contract security that continuously evolve based on threat intelligence and ecosystem changes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3063,351,1,'Ad Hoc','Hardware asset inventory is incomplete, inconsistent, or maintained only when problems arise. Asset tracking relies heavily on individual knowledge and manual processes with no standardized approach. Hardware assets may be discovered reactively during incidents or when equipment fails.','Partial or outdated hardware lists maintained in spreadsheets or informal records | Asset discovery happens reactively when issues occur | No standardized process for tracking hardware acquisitions or disposals | Significant gaps between actual hardware and recorded inventory','Look for informal, incomplete inventory records with evidence of reactive asset discovery and no systematic tracking processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3064,351,2,'Defined','A formal hardware asset inventory process is documented and followed, with designated responsibilities for maintaining asset records. The organization maintains a structured inventory database or system that captures basic hardware information. Regular inventory updates occur but may still be primarily manual and not fully comprehensive.','Documented procedures for hardware asset inventory management | Designated roles and responsibilities for asset tracking | Structured database or system containing basic hardware asset information | Regular scheduled inventory reviews and updates','Look for documented inventory procedures, assigned responsibilities, and evidence of regular manual inventory maintenance with structured data capture.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3065,351,3,'Integrated','Hardware asset inventory is integrated with other business processes and systems, enabling automated discovery and tracking capabilities. The inventory includes detailed hardware specifications, locations, ownership, and lifecycle information. Asset management processes are coordinated across departments and linked to procurement, deployment, and disposal workflows.','Automated asset discovery tools and network scanning capabilities | Integration with procurement, deployment, and disposal processes | Comprehensive hardware attributes tracked including specifications, locations, and ownership | Regular reconciliation between physical assets and inventory records','Look for automated discovery capabilities, process integration across departments, and comprehensive asset attributes with evidence of regular reconciliation activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3066,351,4,'Intelligent','The hardware asset inventory leverages advanced analytics and intelligence to provide real-time visibility and predictive insights. The system automatically correlates asset data with security, performance, and business impact metrics. Intelligent alerts and dashboards provide stakeholders with actionable information about hardware asset status, risks, and optimization opportunities.','Real-time asset monitoring with intelligent alerting and dashboards | Predictive analytics for hardware lifecycle and maintenance planning | Automated correlation of asset data with security and performance metrics | Risk-based asset prioritization and impact analysis capabilities','Look for real-time monitoring capabilities, predictive analytics features, and evidence of intelligent correlation between asset data and business/security metrics.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3067,351,5,'Adaptive','The hardware asset inventory system continuously evolves and adapts to changing business needs, threat landscape, and technological advances. Machine learning and AI capabilities automatically optimize inventory processes, predict future requirements, and adapt to new asset types. The system provides strategic insights that drive business decisions and automatically adjusts security and operational controls based on asset intelligence.','Machine learning algorithms optimize inventory accuracy and processes automatically | Self-adapting system that evolves with new hardware types and business changes | Strategic asset intelligence drives business and security decision-making | Automated adjustment of security controls based on asset risk profiles and changes','Look for evidence of machine learning optimization, self-adapting capabilities that respond to business changes, and strategic decision-making driven by asset intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3068,352,1,'Ad Hoc','Software asset inventories are maintained inconsistently across the organization with significant gaps in coverage. Most inventory activities are manual, reactive, and driven by immediate needs rather than systematic processes. Limited visibility exists into the complete software landscape, with many assets remaining undocumented.','Partial or outdated software inventories exist in spreadsheets or informal documents | Software discovery is primarily manual and reactive | No standardized inventory process or assigned ownership | Significant gaps in software asset visibility across the organization','Look for evidence of basic inventory efforts that are incomplete, inconsistent, and lack systematic processes or clear ownership.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3069,352,2,'Defined','The organization has established formal processes and procedures for maintaining software asset inventories. Clear roles and responsibilities are assigned for inventory management, and standardized methods are used to identify and catalog software assets. Regular inventory updates occur according to defined schedules.','Documented software inventory procedures and assigned responsibilities | Standardized software asset classification and cataloging methods | Regular scheduled inventory reviews and updates | Centralized inventory repository or database in use','Look for documented processes, assigned roles, and evidence of systematic inventory management activities occurring on a regular basis.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3070,352,3,'Integrated','Software asset inventory processes are integrated with other business and security processes across the organization. Automated discovery tools supplement manual efforts, and inventory data is shared with relevant stakeholders for decision-making. The inventory includes comprehensive metadata about software assets including dependencies and relationships.','Automated software discovery tools deployed and operational | Inventory integrated with IT service management and security processes | Comprehensive asset metadata including versions, dependencies, and relationships | Regular validation and reconciliation of inventory data','Look for evidence of integration between inventory processes and other organizational systems, plus automated tools that enhance inventory accuracy and completeness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3071,352,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages advanced analytics and intelligence to optimize software asset inventory management. Real-time monitoring and automated discovery provide continuous visibility into software assets, with predictive capabilities for identifying potential issues. Risk-based prioritization guides inventory management activities.','Real-time software asset monitoring and continuous discovery capabilities | Advanced analytics for software usage patterns and risk assessment | Automated anomaly detection for unauthorized or unknown software | Risk-based prioritization of inventory management activities','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, real-time monitoring capabilities, and risk-based approaches that demonstrate intelligent optimization of inventory processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3072,352,5,'Adaptive','Software asset inventory capabilities continuously evolve and adapt based on changing business needs, threat landscape, and emerging technologies. The organization uses machine learning and AI to enhance inventory accuracy and automate decision-making. Inventory processes seamlessly adapt to new software delivery models and organizational changes.','Machine learning algorithms optimize inventory accuracy and completeness | Self-adapting inventory processes adjust to organizational and technological changes | Predictive modeling for software asset lifecycle management | Seamless integration with DevOps and cloud-native software delivery pipelines','Look for evidence of adaptive technologies like machine learning, self-optimizing processes, and seamless adaptation to emerging software delivery models and organizational changes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3073,353,1,'Ad Hoc','Network and data flow documentation is minimal, inconsistent, or non-existent. Any representations that exist are created on an as-needed basis, often incomplete, and maintained by individual staff members without standardized formats or processes.','Informal network diagrams created by IT staff | No centralized repository for network documentation | Documentation exists only for specific incidents or projects | Network maps are outdated or incomplete','Look for absence of formal network documentation processes and reliance on individual knowledge or informal sketches.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3074,353,2,'Defined','Basic network diagrams and data flow representations exist with defined standards and templates. Documentation is created following established procedures, though it may not cover all network segments or be consistently maintained across the organization.','Standardized network diagram templates in use | Basic network topology maps documented | Data flow documentation for critical systems exists | Defined roles for creating and maintaining network representations','Look for documented standards for network representation and evidence of systematic creation of network diagrams.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3075,353,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive network and data flow representations are maintained across all organizational units with integrated processes. Documentation is regularly updated, version-controlled, and accessible to authorized personnel through centralized systems.','Comprehensive network documentation covering all segments | Integrated data flow maps showing internal and external connections | Regular review and update processes established | Centralized documentation management system in place','Look for comprehensive coverage of network assets with integrated maintenance processes and regular update cycles.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3076,353,4,'Intelligent','Network and data flow representations are automatically generated and maintained using intelligent tools and monitoring systems. Real-time visibility into network topology and data flows enables predictive analysis and proactive identification of unauthorized communications or anomalous patterns.','Automated network discovery and mapping tools deployed | Real-time network topology visualization | Intelligent analysis of data flow patterns | Automated alerts for unauthorized network communications','Look for automated tools that provide real-time network visibility and intelligent analysis capabilities for detecting anomalies.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3077,353,5,'Adaptive','Network and data flow representations continuously adapt based on machine learning, threat intelligence, and business context changes. The system automatically adjusts documentation and controls based on evolving network patterns, emerging threats, and organizational requirements.','Machine learning-driven network pattern analysis | Adaptive network representations based on threat intelligence | Self-updating documentation aligned with business changes | Predictive modeling for network security optimization','Look for evidence of machine learning capabilities that automatically adapt network representations based on changing threat landscapes and business contexts.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3078,354,1,'Ad Hoc','Service inventories from suppliers are maintained inconsistently or not at all, often relying on informal knowledge or ad-hoc documentation. When inventories exist, they are typically incomplete, outdated, or stored in disparate systems without standardized formats.','No formal process for maintaining supplier service inventories | Service information scattered across emails, spreadsheets, or individual knowledge | Inventories are significantly incomplete or outdated | Limited visibility into what services suppliers actually provide','Look for absence of systematic processes and reliance on informal or fragmented documentation of supplier services.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3079,354,2,'Defined','Basic processes and procedures are established for maintaining inventories of supplier services. Standard templates or formats are used to document services, though implementation may be inconsistent across different suppliers or business units.','Documented procedures exist for maintaining supplier service inventories | Standard templates or formats are used for service documentation | Basic service information is captured but may lack detail | Some gaps in inventory coverage or update frequency','Look for documented processes and standardized approaches to capturing supplier service information, even if implementation is not fully consistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3080,354,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive supplier service inventories are maintained using integrated systems and standardized processes across the organization. Regular updates ensure inventories remain current, and the information is accessible to relevant stakeholders for decision-making.','Centralized system for managing supplier service inventories | Regular update cycles with defined responsibilities | Comprehensive coverage of all supplier services | Integration with procurement and vendor management processes','Look for systematic, organization-wide processes with regular updates and integration across relevant business functions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3081,354,4,'Intelligent','Supplier service inventories are enhanced with automated data collection, analysis capabilities, and risk-based categorization. The organization leverages metrics and analytics to optimize service inventory management and identify potential gaps or redundancies.','Automated data collection and inventory updates where possible | Analytics and reporting capabilities for service inventory insights | Risk-based categorization and prioritization of services | Proactive identification of inventory gaps or inconsistencies','Look for automation, analytics capabilities, and data-driven approaches to managing and optimizing supplier service inventories.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3082,354,5,'Adaptive','Supplier service inventories are continuously optimized through advanced analytics, machine learning, and real-time integration with supplier systems. The organization maintains dynamic, self-updating inventories that adapt to changing business needs and automatically flag potential issues or opportunities.','Real-time integration with supplier systems for automatic updates | Advanced analytics and machine learning for predictive insights | Dynamic adaptation to changing business requirements | Automated anomaly detection and alerting for service changes','Look for advanced technologies enabling continuous optimization, real-time updates, and predictive capabilities in supplier service inventory management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3083,355,1,'Ad Hoc','Asset prioritisation occurs informally and inconsistently, typically driven by immediate operational needs or crisis situations. There is little to no systematic approach to classifying assets or determining their criticality to organisational objectives.','Asset priorities determined reactively during incidents | No formal asset classification scheme exists | Prioritisation decisions made by individual judgment without criteria | Limited understanding of asset criticality to business objectives','Look for absence of formal prioritisation processes and evidence that asset importance is only considered during emergencies or operational disruptions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3084,355,2,'Defined','Basic asset classification and prioritisation processes are documented and implemented. Assets are categorised using defined criteria, though the process may not be consistently applied across all asset types or organisational units.','Documented asset classification scheme exists | Basic prioritisation criteria defined (e.g., high/medium/low) | Some assets formally classified and prioritised | Prioritisation process known to asset management teams','Look for documented classification schemes and evidence that some assets have been formally prioritised using defined criteria, even if implementation is inconsistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3085,355,3,'Integrated','Asset prioritisation is systematically implemented across the organisation using comprehensive classification criteria that consider criticality, resources, and business impact. The prioritisation process is integrated with other business processes and regularly maintained.','Comprehensive asset inventory with classifications applied | Prioritisation considers multiple factors (criticality, cost, business impact) | Regular review and update of asset priorities | Prioritisation integrated with risk management and business continuity processes','Look for comprehensive implementation of asset prioritisation across the organisation with evidence of integration into other business processes and regular maintenance activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3086,355,4,'Intelligent','Asset prioritisation leverages advanced analytics, automated tools, and data-driven insights to dynamically assess and adjust priorities based on changing business conditions and threat landscape. The organisation continuously monitors and optimises prioritisation effectiveness.','Automated tools support dynamic asset prioritisation | Data analytics used to assess business impact and criticality | Real-time monitoring of asset importance to business objectives | Prioritisation effectiveness measured and optimised','Look for evidence of advanced tooling, data analytics, and automated processes that enable dynamic and optimised asset prioritisation based on real-time business and threat intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3087,355,5,'Adaptive','Asset prioritisation operates as a self-improving, adaptive system that automatically adjusts to emerging threats, changing business objectives, and lessons learned from incidents. The organisation continuously innovates its prioritisation approach and shares best practices with industry peers.','Self-adapting prioritisation based on threat intelligence and business changes | Machine learning enhances prioritisation accuracy over time | Prioritisation approach influences industry standards and practices | Continuous innovation in prioritisation methodologies','Look for evidence of self-improving systems that automatically adapt prioritisation based on emerging conditions, with the organisation leading industry innovation in asset prioritisation practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3088,356,1,'Ad Hoc','Data inventories are incomplete, inconsistent, or non-existent across the organization. When data inventories do exist, they are maintained manually in isolated spreadsheets or documents by individual teams without standardized formats or metadata capture.','No centralized data inventory exists | Data cataloging occurs sporadically when specifically requested | Metadata capture is minimal or inconsistent | Different teams maintain separate, incompatible data lists','Look for absence of systematic data inventory processes and evidence that data discovery relies primarily on tribal knowledge or ad-hoc searches.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3089,356,2,'Defined','Formal procedures exist for maintaining data inventories with defined metadata standards for designated data types. Data inventories are maintained in structured formats, though the process may still be largely manual and updates occur on scheduled intervals rather than in real-time.','Documented procedures for data inventory maintenance | Standardized metadata schema defined for key data types | Regular scheduled updates to data inventories | Designated roles responsible for data cataloging activities','Look for documented processes, standardized templates or schemas for data inventory, and evidence of regular maintenance schedules being followed.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3090,356,3,'Integrated','Data inventories are integrated across business units with automated discovery tools supplementing manual processes. Metadata collection is standardized enterprise-wide, and data inventories are regularly updated through established workflows that connect to business processes and system changes.','Automated data discovery tools deployed across multiple systems | Cross-functional data governance processes integrate inventory management | Data inventories linked to business processes and system lifecycle management | Standardized metadata collection integrated into data creation workflows','Look for evidence of automation in data discovery, cross-functional coordination in inventory management, and integration with broader business and IT processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3091,356,4,'Intelligent','Data inventories leverage advanced analytics and machine learning to automatically classify, tag, and maintain metadata with minimal human intervention. The system provides intelligent insights about data relationships, usage patterns, and potential gaps or inconsistencies in the inventory.','Machine learning algorithms automatically classify and tag data | Predictive analytics identify potential inventory gaps or inconsistencies | Intelligent data lineage tracking provides automated relationship mapping | Real-time inventory updates driven by system monitoring and data flow analysis','Look for evidence of AI/ML-driven automation in data classification and inventory maintenance, plus analytical capabilities that provide insights beyond basic cataloging.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3092,356,5,'Adaptive','The data inventory system continuously evolves and self-optimizes based on changing business needs, threat landscapes, and regulatory requirements. Advanced AI capabilities automatically adjust metadata schemas, discovery patterns, and inventory priorities based on real-time risk assessments and business value calculations.','Self-optimizing inventory processes adapt to changing business and risk contexts | Dynamic metadata schemas automatically evolve based on usage patterns and requirements | Continuous learning algorithms improve data discovery and classification accuracy over time | Inventory prioritization automatically adjusts based on real-time risk and business value assessments','Look for evidence of autonomous system adaptation, continuous improvement in inventory accuracy and relevance, and dynamic adjustment of processes based on changing organizational context.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3093,357,1,'Ad Hoc','Asset lifecycle management is performed reactively and inconsistently across the organization. Systems, hardware, software, services, and data are managed on an as-needed basis without formal processes or documentation.','No documented lifecycle management processes | Assets are managed reactively when issues arise | Inconsistent practices across different departments | Limited visibility into asset lifecycles','Look for absence of formal lifecycle management processes and evidence of purely reactive asset management practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3094,357,2,'Defined','Basic lifecycle management processes are documented and followed for most assets. The organization has established procedures for managing systems, hardware, software, services, and data from acquisition through disposal.','Documented lifecycle management procedures exist | Basic processes cover key lifecycle phases | Some standardization across organizational units | Asset management responsibilities are assigned','Look for documented lifecycle management procedures that are generally followed and evidence of basic standardization across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3095,357,3,'Integrated','Lifecycle management processes are consistently implemented across all organizational units with integrated tools and systems. Asset management is coordinated across teams with clear governance and regular reviews of lifecycle stages.','Integrated asset management tools and systems | Consistent implementation across all units | Regular lifecycle reviews and assessments | Cross-functional coordination in asset management','Look for consistent implementation of lifecycle management across all units with integrated tools and evidence of coordinated governance.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3096,357,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and automation are used to optimize asset lifecycle decisions with predictive capabilities. The organization leverages data-driven insights to proactively manage asset performance, maintenance, and replacement timing.','Automated lifecycle management workflows | Predictive analytics for asset replacement and maintenance | Data-driven lifecycle optimization | Proactive asset performance monitoring','Look for advanced automation and analytics capabilities that enable predictive and proactive asset lifecycle management decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3097,357,5,'Adaptive','Asset lifecycle management continuously evolves through machine learning and adaptive processes that optimize performance across changing business conditions. The system self-adjusts lifecycle strategies based on real-time risk, performance, and business value metrics.','Self-adapting lifecycle management systems | Machine learning-driven optimization | Dynamic adjustment to changing business conditions | Continuous improvement through AI-enabled insights','Look for evidence of self-adapting systems with machine learning capabilities that continuously optimize lifecycle management strategies based on changing conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3098,358,1,'Ad Hoc','Vulnerability identification occurs sporadically and reactively, typically only when security incidents arise or during crisis situations. There is no systematic approach to discovering, validating, or documenting vulnerabilities across organizational assets. Vulnerability management activities are largely dependent on individual initiative rather than established processes.','Vulnerabilities discovered only during incidents or breaches | No centralized vulnerability tracking or documentation | Limited or no use of automated vulnerability scanning tools | Vulnerability identification relies on ad-hoc manual efforts','Look for evidence of reactive vulnerability discovery with no systematic processes, tools, or documentation in place.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3099,358,2,'Defined','The organization has established basic vulnerability identification processes and procedures that are documented and followed. Regular vulnerability scanning is performed using standard tools, and discovered vulnerabilities are recorded in a centralized system. However, these activities may not cover all assets consistently and validation processes are still developing.','Documented vulnerability identification procedures exist | Regular vulnerability scans scheduled and performed | Central vulnerability tracking system implemented | Basic validation processes for confirmed vulnerabilities established','Look for documented processes, regular scanning activities, and centralized vulnerability recording with some validation mechanisms.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3100,358,3,'Integrated','Vulnerability identification is comprehensively integrated across all organizational assets with coordinated processes between different teams and systems. Multiple detection methods are employed including automated scanning, manual testing, and threat intelligence feeds. Vulnerabilities are consistently validated, prioritized based on risk, and tracked through their entire lifecycle with clear accountability.','Multiple vulnerability detection methods integrated across all asset types | Comprehensive validation and risk-based prioritization processes | Cross-functional coordination between security, IT, and business teams | Complete vulnerability lifecycle tracking with defined ownership and accountability','Look for comprehensive integration of vulnerability identification across all assets with coordinated processes, multiple detection methods, and complete lifecycle management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3101,358,4,'Intelligent','The organization employs advanced analytics, machine learning, and threat intelligence to enhance vulnerability identification capabilities. Predictive analytics help identify potential vulnerabilities before they become critical, and automated correlation with threat data provides intelligent prioritization. Performance metrics and continuous monitoring provide insights that drive ongoing optimization of vulnerability identification processes.','Advanced analytics and machine learning enhance vulnerability detection | Predictive capabilities identify potential future vulnerabilities | Automated correlation with threat intelligence for intelligent prioritization | Performance metrics drive continuous process optimization and improvement','Look for advanced analytics, predictive capabilities, intelligent automation, and metrics-driven optimization of vulnerability identification processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3102,358,5,'Adaptive','Vulnerability identification processes continuously evolve and adapt in real-time based on changing threat landscapes, business contexts, and emerging technologies. The system learns from new attack patterns, automatically adjusts scanning techniques and validation criteria, and dynamically optimizes resource allocation. The organization proactively contributes to and leverages collective intelligence from industry partnerships and threat sharing communities.','Real-time adaptation to evolving threats and attack patterns | Self-optimizing systems that automatically adjust identification techniques | Dynamic resource allocation based on changing risk profiles | Active participation in threat intelligence sharing communities and industry collaboration','Look for evidence of real-time adaptation, self-optimizing systems, dynamic resource allocation, and active contribution to industry threat intelligence sharing.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3103,359,1,'Ad Hoc','The organization occasionally receives cyber threat intelligence through informal channels or free public sources. There is no systematic approach to collecting, evaluating, or utilizing threat intelligence, with information gathering happening sporadically when specific incidents occur.','Threat intelligence gathered reactively during incidents | Reliance on free or public threat feeds only | No formal process for evaluating threat intelligence sources | Limited or no sharing of threat information with external entities','Look for evidence that threat intelligence collection is reactive, informal, and relies primarily on free public sources without systematic evaluation or integration processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3104,359,2,'Defined','The organization has established basic processes for receiving cyber threat intelligence from identified sources and information sharing forums. There are documented procedures for collecting threat intelligence, though the process may not be consistently applied across all organizational units.','Documented procedures for threat intelligence collection | Participation in industry threat sharing forums | Regular consumption of commercial or government threat feeds | Basic threat intelligence roles and responsibilities assigned','Look for documented processes and procedures for threat intelligence collection with evidence of participation in formal information sharing forums or use of established threat intelligence sources.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3105,359,3,'Integrated','Cyber threat intelligence is systematically integrated into the organization''s risk management and security operations processes. The organization actively participates in multiple information sharing communities and has established relationships with various threat intelligence providers and peers.','Threat intelligence integrated into security monitoring and incident response | Active participation in multiple threat sharing communities | Established relationships with government and industry partners | Threat intelligence informs risk assessments and security controls','Look for evidence that threat intelligence is systematically integrated into security operations, risk assessments, and decision-making processes across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3106,359,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages advanced analytics and automation to process and correlate threat intelligence from multiple sources. Threat intelligence is intelligently filtered, prioritized, and automatically integrated into security tools and processes based on organizational context and risk profile.','Automated threat intelligence processing and correlation | Contextualized threat intelligence based on organizational risk profile | Advanced analytics applied to threat data | Threat intelligence drives automated security responses and controls','Look for evidence of automated threat intelligence processing, advanced analytics capabilities, and intelligent integration of threat data that drives automated security responses based on organizational context.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3107,359,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a dynamic, self-improving threat intelligence capability that continuously adapts collection sources and methods based on the evolving threat landscape. The organization actively contributes high-quality intelligence back to the community and influences threat intelligence standards and practices.','Dynamic adaptation of threat intelligence sources and methods | Active contribution of threat intelligence to sharing communities | Influence on industry threat intelligence standards and practices | Continuous improvement of threat intelligence capabilities based on effectiveness metrics','Look for evidence of dynamic adaptation of threat intelligence capabilities, active contribution to the threat intelligence community, and continuous improvement processes that enhance the organization''s threat intelligence maturity.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3108,360,1,'Ad Hoc','Threat identification occurs sporadically and reactively, often in response to incidents or security events. There is no systematic approach to identifying internal and external threats, and documentation is inconsistent or non-existent.','Threats identified only after incidents occur | No formal threat identification process or methodology | Limited or no documentation of identified threats | Threat identification relies on individual knowledge rather than systematic approach','Look for reactive, incident-driven threat identification with minimal documentation and no formal process.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3109,360,2,'Defined','A formal process exists for identifying internal and external threats with documented procedures and assigned responsibilities. Threat identification occurs regularly using established methodologies, and identified threats are properly recorded and maintained.','Documented threat identification procedures and responsibilities | Regular threat identification activities using established methodologies | Formal threat register or database maintained | Basic categorization of internal and external threats','Look for documented processes, regular threat identification activities, and maintained threat registers with clear ownership.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3110,360,3,'Integrated','Threat identification is integrated across the organization with standardized processes that incorporate multiple threat intelligence sources. The organization systematically identifies threats across all business areas and maintains comprehensive threat documentation that informs risk management decisions.','Threat identification integrated across all business units and functions | Multiple threat intelligence sources utilized systematically | Comprehensive threat taxonomy and classification system | Threat information actively used to inform risk assessments and security decisions','Look for organization-wide integration of threat identification with multiple intelligence sources feeding comprehensive threat management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3111,360,4,'Intelligent','Advanced threat identification capabilities leverage automation, analytics, and real-time intelligence feeds to proactively identify emerging threats. The organization uses sophisticated tools and techniques to correlate threat data and predict potential threat scenarios.','Automated threat identification tools and analytics in use | Real-time threat intelligence feeds integrated into identification process | Predictive threat modeling and scenario analysis capabilities | Advanced correlation of internal and external threat indicators','Look for automated tools, real-time intelligence integration, and predictive threat analysis capabilities with sophisticated correlation techniques.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3112,360,5,'Adaptive','Threat identification processes continuously evolve and adapt based on changing threat landscapes, organizational learning, and industry intelligence. The organization maintains cutting-edge threat identification capabilities that automatically adjust methodologies and focus areas based on emerging patterns and intelligence.','Self-improving threat identification processes that adapt to new threat patterns | Continuous optimization based on threat landscape evolution and organizational learning | Industry-leading threat identification capabilities and methodologies | Proactive contribution to threat intelligence community and sharing','Look for self-adapting processes that continuously evolve based on threat landscape changes and demonstrate industry leadership in threat identification innovation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3113,361,1,'Ad Hoc','Impact and likelihood assessments are performed sporadically and informally when security incidents occur or when specific concerns arise. There is little to no documentation of these assessments, and they rely heavily on individual knowledge and gut feelings rather than structured methodologies.','Impact assessments conducted reactively after incidents | Likelihood estimations based on personal opinion rather than data | No standardized documentation or recording of threat-vulnerability combinations | Ad hoc verbal discussions about potential risks without formal analysis','Look for reactive, undocumented risk assessments that lack consistent methodology and are primarily driven by individual expertise rather than organizational processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3114,361,2,'Defined','The organization has established basic processes and templates for assessing potential impacts and likelihoods of threats exploiting vulnerabilities. These assessments are documented using standardized formats, though they may not be consistently applied across all systems or business areas.','Documented procedures for impact and likelihood assessment | Standardized templates or forms for recording risk assessments | Basic qualitative scales (high/medium/low) for impact and likelihood ratings | Regular but not comprehensive assessment of critical systems','Look for documented procedures and standardized templates that demonstrate a systematic approach to impact and likelihood assessment, even if not consistently applied organization-wide.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3115,361,3,'Integrated','Impact and likelihood assessments are systematically integrated into broader risk management processes and consistently applied across the organization. The organization uses both quantitative and qualitative methods, maintains a centralized repository of assessments, and regularly updates them based on changing threat landscapes.','Centralized risk register with documented impact and likelihood assessments | Integration with vulnerability management and threat intelligence processes | Regular reassessment cycles tied to business processes | Cross-functional teams involved in impact and likelihood determination','Look for evidence of systematic integration with other security processes, centralized documentation, and regular reassessment cycles that demonstrate mature risk assessment practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3116,361,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages advanced analytics, threat intelligence, and automated tools to enhance impact and likelihood assessments with data-driven insights. Machine learning and predictive modeling may be used to improve accuracy of assessments, and real-time threat feeds inform dynamic likelihood calculations.','Automated tools support impact and likelihood calculations | Integration with external threat intelligence feeds for dynamic likelihood updates | Use of historical incident data and statistical analysis for more accurate assessments | Predictive modeling to anticipate emerging risks and changing impact scenarios','Look for advanced analytical capabilities, automated tooling, and integration with threat intelligence that demonstrates sophisticated, data-driven approaches to impact and likelihood assessment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3117,361,5,'Adaptive','Impact and likelihood assessments continuously evolve through machine learning, real-time threat intelligence, and dynamic business context awareness. The system automatically adjusts assessments based on changing business conditions, emerging threats, and lessons learned from security events across the industry.','Real-time adaptive assessment capabilities that adjust to changing conditions | Machine learning models that improve assessment accuracy over time | Automated integration with business impact analysis and continuity planning | Predictive capabilities that anticipate future risk scenarios and proactively adjust assessments','Look for evidence of continuous, automated adaptation of assessments based on real-time data, machine learning capabilities, and proactive adjustment to emerging threat landscapes and business changes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3118,362,1,'Ad Hoc','Risk understanding occurs on an informal, reactive basis with limited systematic analysis of threats, vulnerabilities, likelihoods, and impacts. Risk assessments are typically performed in response to incidents or specific requests rather than as part of regular processes.','Risk assessments performed sporadically without standard methodology | Limited documentation of threats, vulnerabilities, and their potential impacts | Risk analysis relies heavily on individual knowledge and intuition | No consistent approach to likelihood estimation or impact assessment','Look for evidence of informal, inconsistent risk analysis practices with minimal documentation and no standardized methodology for assessing threats, vulnerabilities, likelihoods, and impacts.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3119,362,2,'Defined','Formal processes exist for identifying and analyzing threats, vulnerabilities, likelihoods, and impacts to understand risk. Standard methodologies and templates are established, though application may vary across different areas of the organization.','Documented risk assessment methodology that addresses threats, vulnerabilities, likelihoods, and impacts | Standardized templates and criteria for risk analysis | Regular risk assessments conducted using defined processes | Basic risk registers or databases maintained','Look for documented risk assessment processes and methodologies that systematically address all four components (threats, vulnerabilities, likelihoods, impacts) with evidence of regular application.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3120,362,3,'Integrated','Risk assessment processes are consistently applied across the organization with integrated threat intelligence, vulnerability management, and impact analysis capabilities. Risk information is actively used to inform decision-making and prioritize risk responses.','Integrated threat intelligence feeds inform risk assessments | Automated vulnerability scanning and assessment tools deployed | Quantitative and qualitative risk analysis methods consistently applied | Risk assessment results directly inform business and security decisions','Look for consistent organization-wide application of risk assessment processes with integrated tools and data sources that directly inform risk response prioritization and business decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3121,362,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and modeling techniques enhance risk understanding through sophisticated threat analysis, vulnerability correlation, and predictive likelihood assessments. Risk assessments leverage multiple data sources and provide actionable insights for proactive risk management.','Advanced threat modeling and attack simulation capabilities | Predictive analytics used for likelihood assessment and trend analysis | Correlation of vulnerability data with threat intelligence and business context | Risk assessment outcomes include confidence intervals and scenario analysis','Look for advanced analytical capabilities including predictive modeling, threat simulation, and sophisticated correlation of multiple risk factors that provide forward-looking risk insights.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3122,362,5,'Adaptive','Risk assessment processes continuously evolve and adapt based on changing threat landscapes, emerging vulnerabilities, and organizational context. Machine learning and AI enhance real-time risk analysis and enable dynamic adjustment of risk models and priorities.','Machine learning algorithms enhance threat detection and vulnerability prioritization | Real-time risk assessment and dynamic risk scoring capabilities | Self-improving risk models that adapt to new threats and organizational changes | Automated risk response recommendations based on continuously updated analysis','Look for evidence of self-adapting risk assessment capabilities that leverage AI/ML to continuously improve risk understanding and automatically adjust to changing threat and vulnerability landscapes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3123,363,1,'Ad Hoc','Risk responses are handled reactively on a case-by-case basis with no consistent approach. Decision-making around risk treatment is informal, undocumented, and depends on individual knowledge and availability.','Risk responses determined informally by available personnel | No documented risk treatment decisions or rationale | Communication of risk responses is ad-hoc and inconsistent | Risk treatment activities are not tracked or monitored','Look for absence of documented risk response processes and evidence that risk treatment decisions are made reactively without consistent methodology.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3124,363,2,'Defined','Basic processes exist for selecting and documenting risk responses, with some prioritisation criteria established. Risk treatment plans are created but tracking and communication may be inconsistent across different areas of the organisation.','Documented procedures for risk response selection and planning | Basic criteria established for prioritising risk treatments | Risk treatment plans are created and maintained | Some formal communication of risk responses to relevant stakeholders','Look for documented risk response procedures and evidence that risk treatment decisions follow established processes with some level of planning and communication.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3125,363,3,'Integrated','Risk response processes are consistently applied across the organisation with systematic prioritisation and planning. Regular tracking mechanisms are in place and communication is standardised to ensure all relevant stakeholders are informed of risk treatment activities.','Consistent risk response processes applied enterprise-wide | Systematic prioritisation using defined criteria and risk appetite | Regular tracking and reporting of risk treatment progress | Standardised communication channels for risk response updates','Look for consistent application of risk response processes across the organisation with systematic tracking and regular communication to stakeholders.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3126,363,4,'Intelligent','Risk response selection and prioritisation leverages advanced analytics and business intelligence to optimise decisions. Automated tracking systems provide real-time visibility into treatment progress, and communication is enhanced through dashboards and predictive insights.','Advanced analytics inform risk response selection and prioritisation | Automated tracking systems provide real-time progress monitoring | Intelligent dashboards and reporting enable data-driven decisions | Predictive capabilities support proactive risk response planning','Look for evidence of advanced analytics driving risk response decisions and automated systems providing intelligent tracking and reporting capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3127,363,5,'Adaptive','Risk response processes continuously evolve based on emerging threats, business changes, and performance outcomes. The organisation demonstrates self-improving capabilities that automatically adjust response strategies and communication approaches based on effectiveness metrics and changing risk landscapes.','Risk response strategies automatically adapt to changing threat landscape | Continuous learning mechanisms improve response selection over time | Dynamic prioritisation adjusts based on real-time risk and business context | Self-optimising communication adapts to stakeholder needs and preferences','Look for evidence of self-improving risk response processes that automatically adapt strategies based on changing conditions and continuously optimise effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3128,364,1,'Ad Hoc','Changes and exceptions are handled reactively with minimal documentation or risk consideration. There is no formal process for tracking or managing changes, and exceptions are granted on an ad hoc basis without consistent evaluation.','Changes implemented without formal approval processes | Exceptions granted informally without risk assessment | No centralized tracking of changes or exceptions | Risk impact of changes rarely evaluated before implementation','Look for evidence of informal, reactive change handling with little to no documentation or risk assessment processes in place.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3129,364,2,'Defined','Formal processes exist for managing changes and exceptions with basic risk assessment procedures. Documentation requirements are established and most changes follow defined approval workflows, though implementation may be inconsistent across the organization.','Documented change management procedures exist | Basic risk assessment conducted for changes and exceptions | Formal approval process defined with designated authorities | Changes and exceptions recorded in centralized system or repository','Look for documented change management processes with evidence of basic risk assessment and formal approval procedures being followed.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3130,364,3,'Integrated','Change management and exception processes are consistently applied across the organization with comprehensive risk assessment integrated into workflows. Changes are systematically tracked, and risk impact is thoroughly evaluated using standardized criteria and methodologies.','Standardized risk assessment criteria applied consistently | Comprehensive tracking system with status monitoring and reporting | Integration with broader risk management framework | Regular review and validation of approved changes and exceptions','Look for evidence of consistent application of change management processes with comprehensive risk assessment integrated across organizational functions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3131,364,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and automation enhance change management with predictive risk assessment capabilities. The organization uses data-driven insights to optimize change processes and proactively identifies potential issues before implementation.','Automated risk assessment tools and workflows implemented | Predictive analytics used to assess change impact | Real-time monitoring and alerting for change-related risks | Data-driven optimization of change management processes','Look for evidence of automated tools, predictive capabilities, and data-driven optimization in change management processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3132,364,5,'Adaptive','Change management processes continuously evolve and self-optimize based on real-time threat intelligence and organizational learning. The system dynamically adjusts risk thresholds and approval requirements based on changing threat landscapes and business context.','Self-optimizing change management processes that adapt to threats | Dynamic risk thresholds based on real-time intelligence | Continuous learning from change outcomes to improve processes | Integration with external threat feeds and industry intelligence','Look for evidence of self-adapting change management systems that continuously evolve based on threat intelligence and organizational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3133,365,1,'Ad Hoc','The organisation has no formal process for receiving vulnerability disclosures and typically relies on informal channels like general contact emails or support tickets. When vulnerabilities are reported, response is reactive and handled on a case-by-case basis without structured analysis or consistent timelines.','Vulnerability reports received through general email addresses or informal channels | No documented process for vulnerability disclosure handling | Response times and actions vary significantly between incidents | Limited or no tracking of vulnerability disclosures','Look for absence of formal vulnerability disclosure processes and evidence of ad-hoc, inconsistent handling of vulnerability reports.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3134,365,2,'Defined','The organisation has established a documented vulnerability disclosure process with designated contact methods and basic procedures for analysis and response. Clear roles and responsibilities are assigned, though the process may not be fully integrated with other security operations.','Documented vulnerability disclosure policy and procedures | Designated security contact or email for vulnerability reports | Defined roles and responsibilities for vulnerability response team | Basic service level agreements or response timeframes established','Look for documented vulnerability disclosure processes with clear procedures, designated contacts, and defined response roles.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3135,365,3,'Integrated','Vulnerability disclosure processes are fully integrated with the organisation''s broader security operations, incident response, and risk management activities. The organisation maintains consistent communication with reporters and has established coordination mechanisms with internal teams and external stakeholders.','Vulnerability disclosure process integrated with incident response and security operations | Consistent tracking and status updates provided to vulnerability reporters | Coordination mechanisms with product teams, legal, and communications established | Regular process reviews and improvements implemented','Look for vulnerability disclosure processes that are systematically integrated with other security and business operations, with consistent execution and stakeholder coordination.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3136,365,4,'Intelligent','The organisation leverages data analytics and intelligence to enhance vulnerability disclosure processes, including automated triage, threat intelligence correlation, and predictive analysis. Advanced metrics and reporting provide insights into vulnerability trends and process effectiveness.','Automated vulnerability triage and initial analysis capabilities | Integration with threat intelligence feeds for context and prioritisation | Advanced metrics and analytics on disclosure trends and response effectiveness | Predictive analysis to identify potential vulnerability patterns or emerging threats','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation, and intelligence integration that enhances the vulnerability disclosure process beyond standard procedures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3137,365,5,'Adaptive','The vulnerability disclosure process continuously evolves based on threat landscape changes, lessons learned, and emerging best practices. The organisation proactively engages with the security research community and adapts its approach based on real-time feedback and changing business needs.','Dynamic process adaptation based on threat landscape evolution and lessons learned | Proactive engagement with security research community and bug bounty programs | Continuous optimisation using machine learning and advanced analytics | Real-time process adjustment capabilities based on situational awareness','Look for evidence of continuous process evolution, proactive community engagement, and adaptive capabilities that respond to changing threats and business requirements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3138,366,1,'Ad Hoc','Hardware and software authenticity and integrity verification occurs sporadically and inconsistently, often only when security incidents arise. There are no standardized processes or tools in place, with verification activities dependent on individual awareness and initiative.','No documented procedures for verifying hardware/software authenticity | Verification activities are reactive and incident-driven | Limited or no use of digital signatures, checksums, or other integrity verification methods | Procurement teams lack awareness of authenticity verification requirements','Look for absence of formal verification processes and evidence that authenticity checks are performed only occasionally or in response to problems.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3139,366,2,'Defined','Basic procedures and policies exist for verifying hardware and software authenticity and integrity before acquisition and deployment. Verification activities follow documented processes but may not be consistently applied across all acquisitions and organizational units.','Documented policies and procedures for authenticity verification exist | Basic integrity checking tools and methods are available (checksums, digital signatures) | Procurement processes include some authenticity verification requirements | Training provided to relevant staff on verification procedures','Look for documented procedures and evidence of some structured verification activities, even if implementation is not fully consistent across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3140,366,3,'Integrated','Hardware and software authenticity and integrity verification is systematically integrated into procurement and deployment processes across the organization. Standardized verification methods are consistently applied with clear roles and responsibilities defined.','Verification activities are embedded in procurement workflows and system deployment processes | Standardized tools and techniques used consistently across the organization | Clear roles and responsibilities assigned for authenticity verification | Regular reporting on verification activities and outcomes to management','Look for consistent application of verification processes across different business units and evidence of systematic integration with procurement and deployment workflows.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3141,366,4,'Intelligent','Advanced automated tools and intelligence feeds enhance the verification of hardware and software authenticity and integrity. The organization leverages threat intelligence, supply chain risk data, and automated verification systems to make informed decisions about acquisitions.','Automated verification systems integrate with procurement and asset management platforms | Threat intelligence feeds inform authenticity verification decisions | Advanced techniques like software composition analysis and hardware attestation are employed | Metrics and analytics drive continuous improvement of verification processes','Look for sophisticated automated verification capabilities and evidence that threat intelligence and analytics are actively used to enhance authenticity verification decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3142,366,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a highly adaptive and resilient approach to hardware and software authenticity verification that continuously evolves based on emerging threats and supply chain risks. Verification processes are optimized through machine learning and predictive analytics.','Machine learning and AI enhance verification processes and risk prediction | Real-time adaptation of verification requirements based on threat landscape changes | Proactive supply chain risk assessment influences verification strategies | Organization contributes to industry best practices and threat intelligence sharing for authenticity verification','Look for evidence of adaptive verification processes that automatically adjust based on changing risk conditions and demonstrate innovation in authenticity verification approaches.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3143,367,1,'Ad Hoc','Critical supplier assessments are performed inconsistently or not at all, typically occurring only when problems arise or are mandated by specific projects. There is no formal process to identify which suppliers are critical or what assessment criteria should be applied. Assessment activities are reactive and depend heavily on individual knowledge and ad-hoc efforts.','No formal definition of critical suppliers exists | Supplier assessments occur sporadically or only after incidents | Assessment criteria and methods vary significantly between evaluations | Limited documentation of supplier risk evaluations','Look for absence of systematic supplier assessment processes and inconsistent or undocumented evaluation of supplier risks.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3144,367,2,'Defined','The organization has established formal processes and criteria for identifying critical suppliers and conducting pre-acquisition assessments. Standard assessment procedures are documented and include basic security, operational, and financial evaluation criteria. However, implementation may be inconsistent across different business units or procurement activities.','Documented process for identifying critical suppliers | Standardized assessment criteria and procedures exist | Basic security questionnaires or evaluation forms are used | Formal approval requirements for critical supplier engagements','Look for documented processes and standardized criteria for critical supplier identification and assessment, even if implementation is not fully consistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3145,367,3,'Integrated','Critical supplier assessments are consistently integrated into procurement and vendor management processes across the organization. Assessment results are systematically reviewed and inform supplier selection decisions, with clear escalation paths for high-risk findings. The process includes regular reassessment cycles and is coordinated with other risk management activities.','Assessments are consistently performed across all business units | Results are integrated into procurement decision-making processes | Regular reassessment schedules are maintained for existing critical suppliers | Cross-functional teams participate in supplier risk evaluations','Look for consistent implementation of supplier assessments across the organization with clear integration into procurement decisions and ongoing risk management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3146,367,4,'Intelligent','The organization employs advanced analytics and threat intelligence to enhance critical supplier assessments, incorporating real-time risk indicators and predictive modeling. Assessment processes are automated where possible and leverage multiple data sources including third-party risk intelligence, financial data, and cybersecurity threat feeds. Risk-based assessment frequency is dynamically adjusted based on supplier risk profiles and external threat landscape changes.','Advanced analytics and threat intelligence inform assessments | Automated tools and platforms support evaluation processes | Dynamic risk scoring adjusts assessment frequency and depth | Integration with external threat intelligence and financial monitoring services','Look for sophisticated assessment capabilities that leverage automation, analytics, and external intelligence sources to provide dynamic and predictive supplier risk insights.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3147,367,5,'Adaptive','Critical supplier assessment processes continuously evolve through machine learning, stakeholder feedback, and emerging threat analysis. The organization proactively shares threat intelligence with suppliers and industry peers while incorporating lessons learned to refine assessment methodologies. Assessment frameworks automatically adapt to new risk patterns, regulatory changes, and business model evolution.','Machine learning improves assessment accuracy over time | Bi-directional threat intelligence sharing with suppliers and industry | Assessment methodologies evolve based on emerging threats and lessons learned | Predictive models anticipate supplier risks before they materialize','Look for self-improving assessment capabilities that demonstrate continuous learning, proactive threat sharing, and automatic adaptation to evolving risk landscapes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3148,368,1,'Ad Hoc','Improvements are identified sporadically and reactively, typically only after significant issues or incidents occur. There is no systematic approach to evaluation or improvement identification, with efforts largely dependent on individual initiative or crisis response.','Improvements identified only after major incidents or failures | No formal process for capturing or documenting improvement opportunities | Improvement identification relies on ad-hoc individual observations | Limited or no follow-up on identified improvements','Look for evidence that improvement identification occurs only reactively without systematic evaluation processes or documentation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3149,368,2,'Defined','Basic processes exist for identifying improvements from evaluations, with documented procedures for capturing and recording improvement opportunities. Evaluations are conducted periodically, and improvements are identified through structured reviews, though implementation may be inconsistent.','Documented process for identifying improvements from evaluations | Regular evaluation activities with improvement identification components | Formal recording and tracking of identified improvements | Designated roles responsible for improvement identification activities','Look for documented processes and evidence of regular evaluation activities that systematically identify and record improvement opportunities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3150,368,3,'Integrated','Improvement identification is integrated across multiple evaluation types and organizational functions, with consistent processes applied enterprise-wide. There is systematic analysis of evaluation results to identify patterns and prioritize improvements based on risk and business impact.','Integrated improvement identification across multiple evaluation types (assessments, audits, reviews) | Systematic analysis and prioritization of identified improvements | Cross-functional involvement in improvement identification processes | Regular reporting on improvement opportunities to leadership','Look for evidence of integrated improvement identification processes across multiple evaluation types with systematic analysis and prioritization mechanisms.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3151,368,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence are used to identify improvements from evaluations, including trend analysis, predictive insights, and automated identification capabilities. The organization leverages data-driven approaches to proactively identify improvement opportunities before issues manifest.','Advanced analytics used to identify improvement patterns and trends | Automated tools and technologies support improvement identification | Predictive analysis identifies potential future improvement needs | Integration with threat intelligence and industry best practices for improvement identification','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation, and predictive capabilities that enable proactive and intelligent improvement identification from evaluations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3152,368,5,'Adaptive','The improvement identification process continuously evolves and adapts based on changing threat landscapes, business needs, and lessons learned. Machine learning and AI capabilities enhance the identification of subtle patterns and emerging improvement opportunities that traditional methods might miss.','Continuous evolution and adaptation of improvement identification methods | Machine learning and AI enhance pattern recognition for improvements | Real-time identification and adaptive response to emerging improvement opportunities | Self-improving evaluation and improvement identification capabilities','Look for evidence of continuously adaptive improvement identification processes that leverage AI/ML and demonstrate self-improving capabilities that evolve with the changing environment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3153,369,1,'Ad Hoc','Security testing and exercises occur sporadically with minimal systematic approach to identifying improvements. When improvements are identified from testing activities, they are handled on an ad-hoc basis without consistent documentation or follow-through.','Irregular or infrequent security testing activities | Improvements identified inconsistently or not at all | No formal process for capturing lessons learned | Limited coordination with suppliers or third parties during testing','Look for evidence that security testing occurs without systematic improvement identification or that identified improvements are handled inconsistently.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3154,369,2,'Defined','Formal processes exist for conducting security tests and exercises with defined procedures for identifying and documenting improvements. The organization has established basic methods for capturing lessons learned, though coordination with external parties may be limited.','Documented procedures for security testing and improvement identification | Regular security testing activities with improvement outcomes recorded | Basic coordination with some suppliers during security exercises | Formal improvement tracking mechanisms in place','Look for documented processes that systematically identify improvements from security testing with evidence of regular application and basic external coordination.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3155,369,3,'Integrated','Security testing and exercises are well-integrated across the organization with consistent improvement identification processes that include suppliers and third parties. Improvements are systematically captured, prioritized, and tracked through implementation with clear accountability.','Integrated security testing program across all business units | Consistent coordination with suppliers and third parties in security exercises | Systematic prioritization and tracking of identified improvements | Clear roles and responsibilities for improvement implementation','Look for evidence of organization-wide integration of security testing with systematic supplier coordination and mature improvement tracking processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3156,369,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages advanced analytics and intelligence to optimize security testing approaches and improvement identification. Data-driven insights inform testing strategies and improvement prioritization, with sophisticated coordination mechanisms for suppliers and third parties.','Advanced analytics used to optimize testing effectiveness and improvement identification | Risk-based prioritization of improvements using quantitative methods | Sophisticated supplier and third-party coordination platforms | Automated tracking and reporting of improvement implementation progress','Look for evidence of data-driven optimization of security testing programs with advanced analytics supporting improvement identification and prioritization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3157,369,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously evolves its security testing and improvement identification capabilities based on emerging threats, industry developments, and ecosystem feedback. The system self-adapts testing methodologies and automatically adjusts improvement priorities based on real-time intelligence and changing risk landscapes.','Continuous evolution of testing methodologies based on threat intelligence | Self-adapting improvement identification using AI/ML technologies | Dynamic ecosystem coordination that responds to emerging risks | Automated adjustment of improvement priorities based on real-time risk assessment','Look for evidence of continuous adaptation of security testing approaches with automated, intelligence-driven improvement identification that responds dynamically to changing threat landscapes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3158,370,1,'Ad Hoc','Improvements to operational processes are identified sporadically and reactively, typically only after significant issues or failures occur. There is no systematic approach to capturing lessons learned or identifying enhancement opportunities during routine operations.','Improvements only emerge after major incidents or failures | No formal mechanism exists to capture operational insights | Process enhancement discussions occur informally and irregularly | Limited documentation of lessons learned from operational activities','Look for evidence that improvements are identified only reactively after problems occur, with no systematic approach to learning from operations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3159,370,2,'Defined','Basic procedures exist for identifying improvements from operational processes, with designated roles responsible for collecting feedback and observations. Improvement identification occurs through defined channels such as regular reviews or incident post-mortems, though execution may be inconsistent.','Formal procedures define how operational improvements are identified | Designated roles exist for collecting operational feedback and observations | Regular operational reviews or post-incident analyses are conducted | Basic documentation captures improvement opportunities from operational activities','Look for documented procedures and assigned responsibilities for identifying improvements from operations, even if implementation is inconsistent.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3160,370,3,'Integrated','Improvement identification is systematically integrated into all operational processes, with consistent application across the organization. Multiple feedback mechanisms actively capture insights from day-to-day operations, and there are established workflows to evaluate and prioritize identified improvements.','Improvement identification is embedded in all operational processes | Multiple feedback channels consistently capture operational insights | Standardized workflows exist for evaluating and prioritizing improvements | Regular trend analysis identifies patterns in operational performance','Look for consistent integration of improvement identification across all operational processes with established evaluation and prioritization workflows.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3161,370,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and automated monitoring systems proactively identify improvement opportunities from operational data and performance metrics. The organization uses predictive insights and real-time operational intelligence to anticipate areas for enhancement before issues manifest.','Automated systems monitor operations and flag improvement opportunities | Advanced analytics identify patterns and predict areas for enhancement | Real-time dashboards provide operational intelligence for continuous improvement | Machine learning or AI assists in identifying optimization opportunities','Look for automated systems and advanced analytics that proactively identify improvement opportunities using operational data and predictive insights.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3162,370,5,'Adaptive','The organization demonstrates a self-improving capability where operational processes automatically adapt and evolve based on continuous learning. Improvement identification is seamlessly integrated with organizational learning systems that drive autonomous optimization and innovation in operational practices.','Self-adapting processes automatically evolve based on operational learning | Continuous learning systems drive autonomous operational optimization | Innovation emerges naturally from operational execution | Dynamic improvement cycles respond instantly to changing operational conditions','Look for evidence of self-adapting processes that automatically evolve and optimize based on continuous operational learning without manual intervention.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3163,371,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident response and cybersecurity plans are informal, incomplete, or non-existent. When incidents occur, response activities are reactive and improvised without documented procedures or clear coordination.','No formal incident response plan exists | Cybersecurity response relies on individual knowledge and ad-hoc decisions | Plans are not documented or communicated to relevant personnel | Response activities are inconsistent across different incidents','Look for absence of documented incident response plans and evidence that cybersecurity responses are handled informally without established procedures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3164,371,2,'Defined','Basic incident response plans and key cybersecurity operational plans are documented and established. Plans include fundamental response procedures and roles, though they may lack detail or comprehensive coverage of all scenarios.','Written incident response plan exists with basic procedures | Key cybersecurity plans are documented and accessible | Plans identify primary roles and responsibilities | Plans are communicated to relevant staff members','Look for documented incident response and cybersecurity plans that define basic procedures and roles, even if they are not comprehensive or regularly updated.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3165,371,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive incident response and cybersecurity plans are well-integrated across the organization and regularly maintained. Plans are coordinated with business operations and include clear escalation procedures and stakeholder communication protocols.','Plans are comprehensive and cover multiple incident types and scenarios | Regular plan maintenance and updates occur based on lessons learned | Plans are integrated with business continuity and operational procedures | Clear escalation paths and communication protocols are established','Look for evidence that plans are comprehensive, regularly maintained, and effectively integrated with broader organizational operations and business continuity efforts.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3166,371,4,'Intelligent','Incident response and cybersecurity plans leverage threat intelligence, analytics, and performance metrics to drive continuous improvement. Plans are dynamically updated based on emerging threats, industry best practices, and organizational performance data.','Plans incorporate threat intelligence and risk analytics | Performance metrics and KPIs are used to measure plan effectiveness | Automated tools support plan execution and monitoring | Regular tabletop exercises and simulations validate plan effectiveness','Look for evidence that plans are enhanced by threat intelligence and analytics, with measurable performance indicators and regular validation through exercises and simulations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3167,371,5,'Adaptive','Incident response and cybersecurity plans are highly adaptive and self-improving through advanced automation and machine learning. Plans automatically evolve based on real-time threat landscape changes and organizational learning, with seamless integration across the cybersecurity ecosystem.','Plans automatically adapt to emerging threats and changing risk profiles | Machine learning and AI enhance plan optimization and response effectiveness | Real-time plan adjustments based on ongoing incidents and threat intelligence | Seamless integration with external threat sharing communities and industry partnerships','Look for evidence of automated plan adaptation capabilities and advanced technologies that enable real-time plan optimization based on evolving threats and organizational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3168,372,1,'Ad Hoc','Identity and credential management is inconsistent and largely manual, with no standardized processes. User accounts, service credentials, and hardware identities are managed reactively when issues arise or access is needed.','Manual account creation and deletion processes | No centralized identity management system | Default or weak passwords commonly used | Shared accounts and credentials across multiple users','Look for evidence of manual, reactive identity management with no documented processes or centralized systems in place.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3169,372,2,'Defined','Basic identity and credential management processes are documented and followed. The organization has established standard procedures for creating, modifying, and removing user accounts, service credentials, and hardware identities.','Documented identity management procedures | Basic centralized directory service implemented | Standard password policies defined and communicated | Regular access reviews conducted manually','Look for documented procedures and basic centralized systems that are consistently followed across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3170,372,3,'Integrated','Identity and credential management is integrated across systems and business processes with automated workflows. The organization maintains a comprehensive view of all identities and their associated access rights across multiple systems.','Automated provisioning and deprovisioning workflows | Integration between HR systems and identity management | Centralized identity governance platform | Role-based access control consistently applied','Look for automated, integrated identity management systems that span multiple business functions and provide comprehensive visibility.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3171,372,4,'Intelligent','Identity and credential management leverages advanced analytics and intelligence to optimize access decisions and detect anomalies. The organization uses data-driven insights to continuously improve identity governance and reduce risk.','Behavioral analytics for identity risk assessment | Automated access certification with risk scoring | Machine learning for access recommendations | Real-time identity risk monitoring and alerting','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, machine learning, and intelligent automation in identity management decisions and risk assessment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3172,372,5,'Adaptive','Identity and credential management continuously adapts to changing threat landscape, business needs, and user behavior patterns. The organization maintains a self-optimizing identity ecosystem that automatically adjusts policies and controls based on real-time risk assessment.','Dynamic policy adjustment based on threat intelligence | Self-healing identity infrastructure | Predictive access management with contextual risk factors | Continuous optimization of identity processes through AI','Look for evidence of autonomous, self-adapting identity systems that continuously optimize based on changing conditions and predictive intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3173,373,1,'Ad Hoc','Identity proofing and credential binding processes are inconsistent and largely manual. Basic verification may occur for some systems but lacks standardization and relies heavily on individual judgment.','Inconsistent identity verification processes across systems | Manual credential creation without documented procedures | Limited or no verification of identity claims | Basic username/password combinations with minimal validation','Look for absence of formal identity proofing procedures and inconsistent credential binding practices across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3174,373,2,'Defined','Documented identity proofing procedures exist with defined credential binding processes. Standard verification methods are established but may not be consistently applied across all systems and contexts.','Documented identity proofing policies and procedures | Standardized credential binding processes for core systems | Basic identity verification requirements defined | Consistent application within major business systems','Look for documented procedures for identity proofing and credential binding that are implemented across primary systems with some consistency.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3175,373,3,'Integrated','Identity proofing and credential binding are consistently applied across all systems with risk-based approaches. Processes are integrated with broader identity management systems and consider contextual factors for verification levels.','Risk-based identity proofing aligned with access requirements | Integrated credential binding across all enterprise systems | Context-aware verification processes based on sensitivity levels | Centralized identity management with consistent binding policies','Look for consistent, risk-based identity proofing and credential binding processes that are integrated across all systems and consider contextual factors.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3176,373,4,'Intelligent','Advanced identity proofing leverages multiple verification methods and automated processes with intelligent analysis of identity claims. Credential binding incorporates behavioral analytics and continuous validation mechanisms.','Multi-factor identity proofing with automated verification | Behavioral analytics integrated into credential binding | Continuous identity validation and re-verification processes | Machine learning enhanced fraud detection during identity proofing','Look for automated, intelligent identity proofing processes that use multiple verification methods and incorporate behavioral analytics for credential binding.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3177,373,5,'Adaptive','Identity proofing and credential binding processes dynamically adapt based on real-time threat intelligence, contextual risk factors, and emerging attack patterns. The system continuously evolves verification requirements and binding strength based on environmental changes.','Dynamic identity proofing requirements based on threat landscape | Adaptive credential binding strength responding to risk context | Real-time adjustment of verification levels based on behavioral patterns | Self-learning systems that evolve proofing requirements automatically','Look for identity proofing and credential binding systems that automatically adapt verification requirements and binding strength based on real-time threat intelligence and contextual risk assessment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3178,374,1,'Ad Hoc','Authentication mechanisms exist but are inconsistently implemented across the organization. Basic password-based authentication is used for most systems, with limited multi-factor authentication deployment. Hardware and service authentication practices are informal and vary significantly between different systems and departments.','Basic password authentication is primary method | MFA implementation is sporadic or limited to critical systems | Service-to-service authentication relies on shared credentials or basic tokens | Hardware authentication is minimal or uses default manufacturer credentials','Look for inconsistent authentication practices with basic password requirements and limited formal authentication policies or standards.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3179,374,2,'Defined','Formal authentication policies and procedures are documented and implemented organization-wide. Multi-factor authentication is deployed for privileged accounts and critical systems. Service authentication uses dedicated service accounts, and hardware authentication follows established procedures with documented credential management.','Documented authentication policies and standards exist | MFA is implemented for administrative and privileged accounts | Service accounts are properly configured with appropriate permissions | Hardware authentication procedures are documented and followed','Look for documented authentication policies with consistent implementation of MFA for privileged access and formal service/hardware authentication procedures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3180,374,3,'Integrated','Authentication systems are centrally managed through integrated identity management platforms. Multi-factor authentication is widely deployed across all user types, with risk-based authentication policies. Service and hardware authentication is automated through centralized certificate or token management systems with regular rotation schedules.','Centralized identity management system controls authentication | Risk-based authentication policies adjust requirements based on context | Automated certificate or token management for services and hardware | Regular authentication credential rotation is implemented','Look for centralized authentication management with risk-based policies and automated credential lifecycle management for users, services, and hardware.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3181,374,4,'Intelligent','Authentication systems leverage advanced analytics and behavioral analysis to detect anomalies and adapt authentication requirements dynamically. Machine learning algorithms analyze authentication patterns to identify potential threats and automatically adjust security postures. Zero-trust principles guide all authentication decisions with continuous verification of users, services, and hardware.','Behavioral analytics monitor authentication patterns and detect anomalies | Dynamic authentication requirements adjust based on risk assessment | Zero-trust architecture requires continuous verification | Machine learning algorithms enhance authentication security decisions','Look for advanced analytics driving authentication decisions with behavioral analysis, continuous verification, and machine learning-enhanced threat detection capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3182,374,5,'Adaptive','Authentication systems continuously evolve through predictive intelligence and adaptive learning from internal and external threat landscapes. The organization proactively adjusts authentication mechanisms based on emerging threats and changing business contexts. Authentication strategies self-optimize and automatically implement new security measures while maintaining seamless user experience.','Predictive analytics anticipate and prevent authentication-based attacks | Authentication systems self-optimize based on threat intelligence feeds | Automatic deployment of new authentication technologies and methods | Seamless adaptive authentication maintains user experience while enhancing security','Look for predictive authentication capabilities that proactively adapt to emerging threats with self-optimizing systems that automatically enhance security measures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3183,375,1,'Ad Hoc','Identity assertions are handled inconsistently with minimal security controls and no standardized protection mechanisms. Basic authentication tokens or credentials may be transmitted in clear text or stored without proper safeguards. Protection of identity assertions relies on ad-hoc measures and individual awareness rather than systematic controls.','Identity assertions transmitted without encryption | Authentication tokens stored in plain text or unsecured locations | No formal processes for protecting identity credentials | Limited or no verification of identity assertion integrity','Look for absence of systematic protection measures for identity assertions, with evidence of insecure transmission or storage practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3184,375,2,'Defined','Basic security controls are established for protecting identity assertions with documented policies and procedures. Standard encryption methods are implemented for transmission and storage of authentication tokens and credentials. Verification processes are defined but may not be consistently applied across all systems and applications.','Documented policies for identity assertion protection | Basic encryption implemented for credential transmission | Standard procedures for token storage and handling | Basic integrity verification mechanisms in place','Look for documented policies and basic technical controls that provide consistent protection for identity assertions across most systems.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3185,375,3,'Integrated','Identity assertion protection is systematically integrated across the enterprise with comprehensive encryption, secure transmission protocols, and robust verification mechanisms. Strong cryptographic standards are consistently applied, and identity assertions are protected throughout their lifecycle. Integration with enterprise security architecture ensures coordinated protection across all systems.','Enterprise-wide identity assertion protection standards | Strong cryptographic controls consistently applied | Automated verification of assertion integrity | Integration with centralized identity management systems','Look for comprehensive and consistently applied protection mechanisms that are integrated across the enterprise identity management architecture.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3186,375,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligent monitoring continuously assess the security and integrity of identity assertions in real-time. Machine learning algorithms detect anomalous patterns in identity assertion usage and automatically trigger enhanced protection measures. Predictive capabilities identify potential threats to identity assertion security before they materialize.','Real-time monitoring and analytics of identity assertions | Machine learning-based anomaly detection for credential usage | Automated threat response for identity assertion compromise | Predictive risk assessment for identity-related threats','Look for advanced analytics capabilities that provide intelligent, automated monitoring and protection of identity assertions with predictive threat detection.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3187,375,5,'Adaptive','Identity assertion protection continuously evolves and adapts based on emerging threats, changing business requirements, and lessons learned from security incidents. The system automatically adjusts protection mechanisms, encryption standards, and verification processes in response to new attack vectors or regulatory changes. Continuous improvement processes ensure optimal security posture through dynamic adaptation.','Self-adapting protection mechanisms based on threat intelligence | Automatic adjustment of cryptographic standards and protocols | Dynamic policy updates based on risk assessment | Continuous optimization of identity assertion security through machine learning','Look for evidence of self-adapting systems that continuously evolve identity assertion protection capabilities based on threat landscape changes and organizational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3188,376,1,'Ad Hoc','Access permissions are granted on an informal, reactive basis without documented policies or consistent processes. Permissions are typically managed by individual system administrators or managers based on immediate needs and personal judgment. There is minimal oversight or systematic review of who has access to what resources.','Access requests handled informally through emails or verbal requests | No documented access control policy or procedures | Permissions granted based on individual judgment rather than defined criteria | Limited or no regular review of user access rights','Look for absence of formal access control policies and evidence that permissions are granted through informal processes without systematic oversight.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3189,376,2,'Defined','Basic access control policies and procedures are documented and communicated to relevant personnel. Standard processes exist for granting, modifying, and revoking access permissions, though implementation may be inconsistent across the organization. Periodic access reviews are conducted but may not be comprehensive or systematic.','Documented access control policy and basic procedures exist | Formal process for access requests and approvals established | Role-based access concepts beginning to be implemented | Periodic access reviews conducted but not necessarily comprehensive','Look for documented access control policies and evidence of formal processes for managing permissions, even if implementation is not yet consistent across all systems.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3190,376,3,'Integrated','Access control policies and procedures are consistently implemented across most systems and integrated with HR and business processes. Role-based access control is systematically applied with clearly defined roles and responsibilities. Regular, comprehensive access reviews are conducted with documented remediation of identified issues.','Access control policies consistently implemented across most systems | Role-based access control systematically applied with defined roles | Regular comprehensive access reviews with documented remediation | Integration with HR processes for joiner/mover/leaver activities','Look for evidence of consistent implementation of access controls across systems and regular, comprehensive access reviews with documented follow-up actions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3191,376,4,'Intelligent','Access management leverages advanced analytics and automation to continuously monitor and optimize permissions based on usage patterns and risk indicators. Intelligent systems provide real-time insights into access anomalies and automatically adjust permissions based on contextual factors. Predictive analytics help identify potential access-related risks before they materialize.','Advanced analytics used to monitor and optimize access permissions | Automated access provisioning and de-provisioning based on defined rules | Real-time anomaly detection for unusual access patterns | Predictive analytics identify potential access risks proactively','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation in access management, and proactive risk identification capabilities that go beyond traditional rule-based approaches.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3192,376,5,'Adaptive','The access control system continuously learns and adapts to changing business needs, threat landscape, and user behaviors through machine learning and AI. The organization maintains dynamic, context-aware access controls that automatically adjust based on real-time risk assessment and business requirements. The system provides continuous optimization and self-healing capabilities for access management processes.','AI-driven adaptive access controls that learn from user behavior and business context | Dynamic policy adjustment based on real-time threat intelligence and risk assessment | Self-healing access management processes with minimal human intervention | Continuous optimization of access controls based on business outcomes and security metrics','Look for evidence of AI-driven adaptive systems that continuously learn and self-optimize access controls with minimal human intervention while maintaining alignment with business objectives.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3193,377,1,'Ad Hoc','Physical access to assets is inconsistently controlled with minimal formal procedures or oversight. Access decisions are made on an ad-hoc basis without documented standards or risk considerations. Basic controls like locks or security personnel may exist but are not systematically managed.','Inconsistent use of physical barriers or access controls | No documented physical access policies or procedures | Access decisions made informally without approval processes | Limited or no monitoring of physical access events','Look for the absence of formal physical access policies and inconsistent implementation of basic physical security measures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3194,377,2,'Defined','Physical access control policies and procedures are documented and implemented across the organization. Access controls are consistently applied based on defined roles and responsibilities. Basic monitoring and logging of physical access activities is established.','Documented physical access control policies and procedures | Consistent implementation of access badges, locks, or entry systems | Defined roles and responsibilities for granting physical access | Basic logging and monitoring of access events in place','Look for documented policies with consistent implementation of physical access controls and basic monitoring capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3195,377,3,'Integrated','Physical access controls are integrated with overall security risk management and align with business processes. Access decisions are based on risk assessments and regularly reviewed. Monitoring systems provide comprehensive visibility into physical access activities across all locations.','Physical access controls integrated with risk management processes | Regular access reviews and recertification procedures | Comprehensive monitoring across all physical locations | Integration between physical and logical access control systems','Look for risk-based access decisions, regular review processes, and integration between physical security and broader organizational security management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3196,377,4,'Intelligent','Physical access management leverages advanced analytics and automation to optimize security decisions and detect anomalies. Real-time monitoring provides intelligent alerts and adaptive responses to potential security incidents. Access controls continuously adapt based on behavioral patterns and threat intelligence.','Advanced analytics for detecting anomalous physical access patterns | Automated access provisioning and deprovisioning based on role changes | Real-time alerting and incident response capabilities | Integration of threat intelligence into physical access decisions','Look for advanced analytics capabilities, automated processes, and the use of threat intelligence to enhance physical access security decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3197,377,5,'Adaptive','Physical access management continuously evolves through machine learning and predictive analytics to anticipate and prevent security threats. The system automatically adjusts access controls based on emerging risks, environmental factors, and organizational changes. Security measures seamlessly adapt to new technologies and evolving threat landscapes.','Machine learning algorithms predicting and preventing physical security incidents | Automatic adaptation of access controls based on real-time risk assessment | Seamless integration with emerging technologies and IoT devices | Continuous optimization based on threat landscape evolution','Look for machine learning capabilities, predictive analytics, and autonomous adaptation of physical access controls based on evolving threats and organizational needs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3198,378,1,'Ad Hoc','Cybersecurity awareness and training occurs sporadically and inconsistently across the organization. Personnel may receive some informal guidance or basic training, but there is no systematic approach to ensuring all staff understand cybersecurity risks related to their roles.','No formal cybersecurity training program exists | Training is delivered reactively after incidents occur | Limited documentation of training activities or attendance | Personnel awareness of cybersecurity risks varies significantly across departments','Look for absence of structured training programs and inconsistent delivery of cybersecurity awareness across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3199,378,2,'Defined','A formal cybersecurity awareness and training program has been established with documented procedures and content. Personnel receive standardized training covering general cybersecurity principles and basic risk awareness, though the program may not be fully tailored to specific roles or regularly updated.','Documented cybersecurity training program with defined curriculum | Regular training schedule established for all personnel | Basic tracking of training completion and attendance | Standard awareness materials covering common cybersecurity topics','Look for evidence of documented training programs with regular delivery schedules and basic tracking mechanisms in place.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3200,378,3,'Integrated','Cybersecurity training is integrated into broader organizational processes and tailored to different roles and risk levels. The program includes both general awareness and role-specific training, with regular assessments to measure effectiveness and ensure personnel can apply cybersecurity knowledge in their daily tasks.','Role-based training programs aligned with job responsibilities | Regular assessment and testing of personnel cybersecurity knowledge | Training integrated with onboarding and performance management processes | Feedback mechanisms to improve training effectiveness','Look for role-specific training programs with measurable outcomes and integration into standard HR and operational processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3201,378,4,'Intelligent','The organization uses data analytics and metrics to continuously optimize cybersecurity training effectiveness and delivery. Training content and methods are dynamically adjusted based on threat intelligence, incident patterns, and individual performance data to maximize learning outcomes and risk reduction.','Analytics-driven training program optimization based on performance metrics | Threat intelligence integration to update training content | Personalized learning paths based on individual risk profiles and performance | Predictive modeling to identify training gaps and needs','Look for evidence of data-driven decision making in training program design and continuous optimization based on performance analytics.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3202,378,5,'Adaptive','The cybersecurity training program automatically adapts in real-time to emerging threats, changing business contexts, and individual learning patterns. The organization maintains a learning culture where personnel continuously develop cybersecurity capabilities through adaptive, AI-driven training systems and peer-to-peer knowledge sharing.','Real-time adaptive training systems responding to emerging threats | AI-powered personalized learning experiences | Continuous learning culture with peer knowledge sharing | Automated integration of lessons learned from incidents into training content','Look for evidence of real-time adaptive training systems and a self-improving learning ecosystem that evolves automatically with the threat landscape.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3203,379,1,'Ad Hoc','Specialised role training occurs sporadically and inconsistently across the organization. Training is typically delivered reactively in response to incidents or immediate needs, with no formal structure or requirements. Individuals may receive some cybersecurity awareness but lack role-specific training tailored to their specialized responsibilities.','Training delivered reactively after incidents or problems arise | No formal training requirements or tracking for specialized roles | Inconsistent training delivery across different departments or teams | Limited or no role-specific cybersecurity content in training programs','Look for evidence of reactive, unstructured training approaches with no formal requirements or consistent delivery for individuals in specialized roles.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3204,379,2,'Defined','Formal training programs are established for individuals in specialized roles with documented requirements and content. Training curricula are defined and include role-specific cybersecurity knowledge and skills. There are basic processes in place to track training completion and maintain records.','Documented training requirements exist for specialized roles | Role-specific cybersecurity training curricula are developed and maintained | Training completion is tracked and recorded | Scheduled training delivery occurs according to defined timelines','Look for documented training programs with role-specific cybersecurity content and evidence of systematic tracking and delivery processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3205,379,3,'Integrated','Specialized role training is fully integrated with broader organizational processes and risk management activities. Training content is regularly updated based on threat intelligence, risk assessments, and business changes. There are established feedback mechanisms and training effectiveness measurements in place.','Training content updated based on current threat landscape and risk assessments | Training integrated with performance management and career development processes | Regular assessment of training effectiveness and knowledge retention | Coordination between training programs and incident response lessons learned','Look for evidence that specialized role training is integrated with risk management processes and demonstrates regular updates based on evolving threats and organizational needs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3206,379,4,'Intelligent','Training programs leverage analytics and intelligence to optimize delivery and effectiveness for specialized roles. The organization uses data-driven approaches to identify skill gaps, customize training content, and predict training needs. Advanced simulation and scenario-based training methods are employed to enhance practical skills.','Analytics used to identify skill gaps and optimize training delivery | Simulation-based and scenario-driven training methods implemented | Predictive modeling used to anticipate future training needs | Customized training paths based on individual role requirements and performance data','Look for evidence of data-driven training optimization, advanced training methods like simulations, and predictive approaches to identifying and addressing skill gaps.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3207,379,5,'Adaptive','Training programs for specialized roles continuously evolve and self-optimize based on real-time threat intelligence, emerging technologies, and changing business requirements. The organization maintains a learning ecosystem that adapts training content and delivery methods dynamically. There is seamless integration with external threat intelligence and industry best practices to ensure training remains cutting-edge.','Real-time adaptation of training content based on emerging threats and technologies | Continuous learning ecosystem with self-optimizing training delivery | Integration with external threat intelligence feeds and industry networks | Automated training recommendations and adaptive learning paths that evolve with changing role requirements','Look for evidence of dynamic, self-optimizing training systems that automatically adapt to emerging threats and changing requirements while maintaining continuous learning capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3208,380,1,'Ad Hoc','Data-at-rest protection is inconsistent and largely dependent on individual initiative or basic system defaults. Limited encryption may be applied to some systems, but there is no systematic approach to identifying or protecting sensitive data across the organization.','Some systems use default encryption settings | Ad hoc use of basic access controls | No formal data classification or inventory | Protection measures vary significantly across departments','Look for sporadic use of basic protection measures with significant gaps in coverage and no documented approach to data-at-rest protection.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3209,380,2,'Defined','The organization has documented policies and procedures for protecting data-at-rest, including encryption standards and access controls. Data classification schemes exist and encryption is consistently applied to identified sensitive data repositories.','Documented data protection policies and procedures | Consistent encryption of databases and file systems containing sensitive data | Defined data classification scheme with protection requirements | Regular access reviews for data repositories','Look for documented policies with evidence of consistent implementation of encryption and access controls across identified sensitive data stores.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3210,380,3,'Integrated','Data-at-rest protection is integrated across all systems and business processes with automated enforcement mechanisms. Centralized key management and data loss prevention tools provide comprehensive protection aligned with business risk tolerance.','Automated encryption deployment and management | Integrated data loss prevention (DLP) solutions | Centralized cryptographic key management | Data protection controls embedded in system development lifecycle','Look for automated, enterprise-wide protection mechanisms with centralized management and integration into business processes and system development.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3211,380,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and machine learning enhance data-at-rest protection through intelligent threat detection and dynamic risk assessment. The organization uses predictive insights to optimize protection strategies and automatically adjusts controls based on changing threat landscapes.','AI-driven data discovery and classification | Predictive analytics for data protection optimization | Dynamic encryption key rotation based on risk assessment | Automated anomaly detection for data access patterns','Look for advanced analytics capabilities that provide predictive insights and automated optimization of data protection measures based on threat intelligence and risk analysis.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3212,380,5,'Adaptive','The organization''s data-at-rest protection continuously evolves through real-time threat intelligence integration and self-optimizing security measures. Protection strategies automatically adapt to emerging threats while contributing insights back to the broader cybersecurity community.','Self-healing and adaptive protection mechanisms | Real-time integration with global threat intelligence feeds | Continuous optimization based on machine learning from security events | Active contribution to industry threat intelligence sharing','Look for autonomous adaptation capabilities that continuously evolve protection measures in real-time and demonstrate active contribution to external threat intelligence ecosystems.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3213,381,1,'Ad Hoc','Data-in-transit protection is implemented inconsistently across the organization with basic encryption used sporadically. Security measures rely heavily on default configurations and individual knowledge rather than established procedures. Protection mechanisms are reactive and applied on an as-needed basis without comprehensive coverage.','Basic encryption used for some email communications | Default HTTPS enabled on public-facing websites | VPN access available but not consistently used | No formal policy for data transmission security','Look for minimal, inconsistent use of encryption technologies with heavy reliance on vendor defaults and individual initiative rather than organizational standards.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3214,381,2,'Defined','Formal policies and procedures exist for protecting data-in-transit with standardized encryption protocols documented and implemented. The organization has established minimum security requirements for data transmission and uses consistent technologies across most systems. Staff are trained on proper procedures for secure data transmission.','Documented data-in-transit protection policies and procedures | Standardized encryption protocols (TLS 1.2+) implemented across systems | Regular staff training on secure transmission practices | Defined requirements for third-party data sharing','Look for documented policies with consistent implementation of encryption standards and evidence of staff awareness and training on data transmission security.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3215,381,3,'Integrated','Data-in-transit protection is fully integrated into business processes with automated enforcement of security policies and comprehensive coverage across all data flows. The organization maintains an inventory of data transmission channels and applies risk-based protection measures. Regular monitoring and validation ensure continuous compliance with protection requirements.','Automated enforcement of encryption policies across all systems | Comprehensive inventory and classification of data transmission channels | Integration with identity and access management systems | Regular monitoring and validation of transmission security','Look for systematic integration of protection measures into all business processes with automated policy enforcement and comprehensive monitoring of data transmission activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3216,381,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence capabilities provide real-time visibility into data transmission patterns and automatically adapt protection measures based on threat intelligence and risk assessment. The organization uses predictive capabilities to identify potential vulnerabilities in data transmission paths. Machine learning and automation optimize encryption and security controls dynamically.','Real-time analytics on data transmission patterns and anomalies | Threat intelligence integration for adaptive protection measures | Predictive analysis of transmission vulnerabilities | Dynamic optimization of encryption and security controls','Look for advanced analytics capabilities that provide predictive insights and automated adaptation of protection measures based on real-time threat intelligence and risk assessment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3217,381,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously evolves its data-in-transit protection capabilities through advanced AI-driven optimization and real-time adaptation to emerging threats and business requirements. Protection measures self-adjust based on contextual factors, user behavior, and environmental conditions. The organization contributes to industry knowledge and drives innovation in transmission security practices.','AI-driven continuous optimization of transmission security measures | Self-adapting protection based on contextual factors and user behavior | Industry leadership in transmission security innovation | Autonomous response to emerging transmission threats and attack patterns','Look for evidence of continuous innovation and autonomous adaptation of protection measures with AI-driven optimization that responds to emerging threats and contributes to industry advancement.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3218,382,1,'Ad Hoc','Data-in-use protection is minimal or inconsistent, with limited awareness of specific risks. Basic security measures may exist but are not systematically applied to protect data during processing or active use.','Limited or no encryption of data during processing | Inconsistent access controls for active data sessions | Ad hoc monitoring of data-in-use activities | Basic endpoint security with minimal data protection features','Look for reactive approaches to data-in-use protection with minimal documented processes and inconsistent implementation of protective measures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3219,382,2,'Defined','Documented policies and procedures exist for protecting data-in-use with standardized security controls. Organizations have established baseline protections but implementation may vary across different systems and processes.','Documented data-in-use protection policies and procedures | Standardized encryption requirements for data processing | Defined access controls and user authentication for active data | Regular security awareness training on data handling','Look for documented policies and standardized procedures that are consistently implemented across the organization''s data processing activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3220,382,3,'Integrated','Data-in-use protection is systematically integrated across all business processes and technology platforms. Comprehensive security controls are consistently applied with regular monitoring and risk assessment of data processing activities.','Integrated data-in-use protection across all systems and processes | Comprehensive monitoring of data processing activities | Regular risk assessments for data-in-use scenarios | Automated security controls and policy enforcement','Look for consistent integration of data-in-use protection across all organizational processes with evidence of regular monitoring and risk management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3221,382,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence drive data-in-use protection strategies with predictive threat detection. The organization leverages real-time monitoring, behavioral analysis, and automated response capabilities to protect data during processing.','Advanced threat detection and behavioral analytics for data-in-use | Real-time monitoring with automated incident response | Predictive risk assessment and proactive security measures | Integration with threat intelligence for data protection','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, predictive capabilities, and automated intelligent responses that enhance data-in-use protection beyond traditional security measures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3222,382,5,'Adaptive','Data-in-use protection continuously evolves and adapts based on changing threat landscapes, business needs, and technological advances. The organization demonstrates self-improving security posture with autonomous adjustment of protection mechanisms.','Continuously adaptive security controls that evolve with threats | Self-improving data protection mechanisms based on learning algorithms | Autonomous adjustment of security policies and controls | Innovation in data-in-use protection technologies and methodologies','Look for evidence of continuous adaptation and self-improvement in data-in-use protection capabilities that automatically adjust to new threats and changing business requirements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3223,383,1,'Ad Hoc','Backup activities are performed inconsistently and reactively, often triggered by incidents or requests. There is minimal documentation or standardized processes for creating, protecting, or testing backups.','Backups are created sporadically without defined schedules | No formal backup testing or verification processes exist | Backup storage lacks encryption or access controls | Recovery procedures are undocumented or unknown','Look for evidence of inconsistent backup practices with no formal policies, procedures, or regular testing activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3224,383,2,'Defined','Formal backup policies and procedures are documented and implemented across the organization. Regular backup schedules are established with basic protection measures and periodic testing protocols in place.','Documented backup policies and procedures exist | Scheduled backup processes are implemented | Basic backup encryption and access controls are in place | Periodic backup testing and restoration verification occurs','Look for documented backup policies, established schedules, and evidence of regular testing with defined procedures being followed.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3225,383,3,'Integrated','Backup processes are integrated across all systems and business functions with centralized management and monitoring. Automated backup validation and comprehensive testing procedures ensure data recoverability across the organization.','Centralized backup management system covers all critical systems | Automated backup monitoring and alerting is implemented | Regular restoration testing includes full system recovery scenarios | Backup retention policies align with business and regulatory requirements','Look for enterprise-wide backup integration with automated monitoring, comprehensive testing programs, and alignment with business continuity requirements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3226,383,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence drive backup optimization and risk-based decision making. Predictive capabilities identify potential backup failures and automatically adjust protection strategies based on data criticality and threat landscape changes.','AI/ML-driven backup optimization based on data usage patterns | Predictive analytics identify potential backup failures before they occur | Automated risk-based backup frequency and retention adjustments | Real-time backup integrity verification with anomaly detection','Look for advanced analytics driving backup decisions, predictive failure detection, and automated optimization based on risk assessments and data intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3227,383,5,'Adaptive','Backup systems continuously evolve and self-optimize based on emerging threats, changing business needs, and lessons learned from the broader ecosystem. The organization contributes to and benefits from industry-wide backup resilience intelligence and best practices.','Self-healing backup systems that automatically adapt to new threats | Continuous learning from industry incidents improves backup strategies | Dynamic backup architectures adjust to changing business requirements | Active contribution to industry backup resilience standards and threat intelligence sharing','Look for self-adapting backup systems that continuously evolve based on threat intelligence, industry learning, and dynamic business requirements while contributing to broader ecosystem resilience.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3228,384,1,'Ad Hoc','Configuration management activities occur sporadically and are driven by immediate needs or incidents. System configurations are managed manually by individual administrators without standardized processes or documentation. Changes are often made reactively without proper tracking or approval mechanisms.','Manual configuration changes performed by individual administrators | No standardized configuration baselines or templates | Configuration changes documented informally or not at all | Limited or no change approval processes','Look for evidence that configuration management is performed reactively without formal processes, documentation, or standardized approaches.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3229,384,2,'Defined','Basic configuration management policies and procedures have been documented and are beginning to be implemented across systems. Standard configuration baselines exist for common system types, and change management processes are defined but may not be consistently followed. Configuration documentation is maintained but may not be comprehensive.','Documented configuration management policies and procedures | Defined standard configuration baselines for key system types | Basic change management process with approval workflows | Configuration items tracked in centralized documentation or database','Look for documented configuration management processes, standard baselines, and evidence of defined change management procedures being implemented.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3230,384,3,'Integrated','Configuration management practices are consistently applied across the enterprise with integrated tools and processes. Automated configuration deployment and monitoring capabilities are implemented, and configuration baselines are regularly maintained and updated. Change management processes are well-established and consistently followed with proper authorization and testing procedures.','Consistent application of configuration management across all systems | Automated configuration deployment and compliance monitoring tools | Regular reviews and updates of configuration baselines | Integrated change management with testing and rollback procedures','Look for consistent enterprise-wide implementation of configuration management with automation tools and integrated change management processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3231,384,4,'Intelligent','Configuration management leverages advanced analytics and intelligence to proactively identify risks and optimize security posture. Real-time monitoring and automated remediation capabilities detect and respond to configuration drift immediately. Predictive analytics inform configuration decisions and risk assessments based on threat intelligence and operational data.','Real-time configuration monitoring with automated drift detection and remediation | Advanced analytics for configuration risk assessment and optimization | Threat intelligence integration for proactive configuration hardening | Predictive modeling for configuration change impact analysis','Look for advanced analytics capabilities, real-time monitoring with automated response, and evidence of predictive or intelligence-driven configuration management decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3232,384,5,'Adaptive','Configuration management practices continuously evolve and self-optimize based on changing threat landscapes, business requirements, and operational feedback. The system autonomously adapts configurations to maintain optimal security posture while supporting business objectives. Machine learning algorithms continuously improve configuration decisions and predict future optimization opportunities.','Autonomous configuration adaptation based on threat intelligence and business context | Machine learning-driven optimization of configuration baselines | Self-healing systems that automatically adapt to emerging threats | Continuous improvement processes that evolve configuration practices based on outcomes','Look for evidence of autonomous adaptation capabilities, machine learning-driven optimization, and systems that continuously evolve configuration practices based on changing conditions and outcomes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3233,385,1,'Ad Hoc','Software maintenance, replacement, and removal activities occur sporadically and are primarily reactive to immediate problems or security incidents. There is minimal coordination between teams and limited consideration of risk factors when making software lifecycle decisions.','Software updates applied only when critical issues arise | No formal process for software inventory or lifecycle management | Software removal decisions made ad-hoc without risk assessment | Limited coordination between IT, security, and business teams','Look for evidence of reactive software management with no documented processes and minimal risk consideration in software lifecycle decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3234,385,2,'Defined','Basic documented procedures exist for software maintenance, replacement, and removal activities. Risk factors are considered using simple criteria, and there is some coordination between relevant teams for major software lifecycle decisions.','Documented procedures for software patching and updates | Basic software inventory maintained | Simple risk criteria used for software lifecycle decisions | Regular but not comprehensive software maintenance schedules','Look for documented software lifecycle procedures and evidence that basic risk factors are considered in software maintenance decisions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3235,385,3,'Integrated','Software lifecycle management is integrated across the organization with standardized risk-based processes for maintenance, replacement, and removal. Regular assessments drive proactive software lifecycle decisions with clear accountability and coordination mechanisms.','Integrated software asset management system with risk-based prioritization | Standardized processes for evaluating software end-of-life and replacement needs | Cross-functional teams coordinate software lifecycle decisions | Regular vulnerability and performance assessments inform maintenance schedules','Look for evidence of integrated, risk-based software lifecycle processes with clear coordination mechanisms and proactive decision-making.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3236,385,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and automated tools drive intelligent software lifecycle decisions based on comprehensive risk analysis, performance metrics, and business impact assessments. Predictive capabilities enable proactive identification of software that requires maintenance, replacement, or removal.','Automated tools for software lifecycle analysis and risk scoring | Predictive analytics identify software maintenance needs before issues arise | Advanced metrics track software performance, security, and business value | Machine learning enhances risk-based prioritization of software lifecycle activities','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation, and predictive capabilities that drive intelligent software lifecycle decision-making.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3237,385,5,'Adaptive','Software lifecycle management continuously evolves through machine learning, threat intelligence integration, and dynamic risk assessment capabilities. The organization anticipates and automatically adapts to changing threat landscapes, business needs, and technology evolution with minimal human intervention.','AI-driven software lifecycle optimization that adapts to emerging threats | Continuous learning from internal and external threat intelligence | Autonomous software maintenance and replacement recommendations | Dynamic risk models that evolve with changing business and security contexts','Look for evidence of autonomous, continuously learning software lifecycle management systems that dynamically adapt to evolving risks and business requirements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3238,386,1,'Ad Hoc','Hardware maintenance, replacement, and removal activities occur reactively when equipment fails or becomes obviously obsolete. There are no formal processes or documentation governing these activities, and decisions are made on an ad-hoc basis without systematic risk consideration.','Hardware maintenance performed only when failures occur | No documented procedures for hardware lifecycle management | Equipment disposal lacks secure data sanitization processes | Hardware decisions made without risk assessment','Look for evidence of purely reactive hardware management with no formal processes, documentation, or risk-based decision making.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3239,386,2,'Defined','Basic procedures exist for hardware maintenance, replacement, and removal activities with some consideration of security risks. Hardware lifecycle processes are documented but may not be consistently applied across all systems and components.','Written procedures for hardware maintenance and replacement exist | Basic asset inventory tracking hardware components | Secure disposal procedures defined for sensitive equipment | Risk factors identified but not systematically evaluated','Look for documented hardware lifecycle procedures that include basic security considerations but may lack consistent implementation or comprehensive risk assessment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3240,386,3,'Integrated','Hardware lifecycle management is systematically integrated with organizational risk management processes and consistently applied across all critical systems. Maintenance schedules, replacement criteria, and removal procedures are based on standardized risk assessments and align with business requirements.','Risk-based hardware maintenance schedules established and followed | Standardized criteria for hardware replacement based on security and operational risks | Integrated asset management system tracks hardware throughout lifecycle | Secure disposal processes consistently applied with verification','Look for systematic integration of hardware lifecycle management with enterprise risk processes, showing consistent application of risk-based criteria across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3241,386,4,'Intelligent','Hardware lifecycle decisions leverage advanced analytics, threat intelligence, and predictive capabilities to optimize maintenance timing and replacement strategies. Real-time monitoring and automated systems provide intelligent insights for proactive hardware management based on current risk conditions.','Predictive analytics inform hardware maintenance and replacement decisions | Threat intelligence integrated into hardware lifecycle planning | Automated monitoring systems detect hardware degradation and security risks | Performance metrics drive continuous optimization of hardware lifecycle processes','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation, and intelligence-driven approaches that enable predictive and optimized hardware lifecycle management.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3242,386,5,'Adaptive','Hardware lifecycle management continuously adapts to emerging threats, changing business conditions, and technological innovations through machine learning and AI-driven optimization. The organization maintains a self-improving hardware security posture that automatically adjusts maintenance, replacement, and removal strategies based on real-time risk intelligence and operational feedback.','AI-driven systems automatically optimize hardware lifecycle strategies | Self-adapting processes respond to emerging threats and vulnerabilities | Continuous learning from hardware security incidents improves future decisions | Dynamic risk models automatically adjust maintenance and replacement criteria','Look for evidence of autonomous, self-improving hardware lifecycle management systems that continuously adapt strategies based on machine learning, emerging threats, and operational intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3243,387,1,'Ad Hoc','Log generation is inconsistent and reactive, occurring only when issues arise or are discovered. Most systems generate basic logs using default settings with no standardized approach to what should be logged or how logs should be made available.','Default system logging only with no customization | Ad-hoc log collection when problems occur | No centralized log management or standardized formats | Limited or no log retention policies','Look for evidence that logging occurs primarily through default system settings with reactive, incident-driven log collection and no systematic approach to log generation or availability.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3244,387,2,'Defined','Formal logging policies and procedures are documented and implemented across critical systems. Log generation requirements are defined with standardized formats and retention periods, though implementation may vary across different platforms.','Documented logging policies and procedures exist | Standardized log formats and retention requirements defined | Critical systems configured for comprehensive logging | Basic log aggregation and storage mechanisms in place','Look for documented logging standards that are consistently applied to critical systems with defined retention periods and standardized collection processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3245,387,3,'Integrated','Log generation is consistently implemented across all systems with centralized collection and management. Logs are automatically made available to security teams and integrated with monitoring tools for real-time visibility across the organization.','Comprehensive logging across all systems and platforms | Centralized log management system with real-time collection | Automated log parsing and normalization processes | Integration with security monitoring and SIEM tools','Look for enterprise-wide log management systems that automatically collect, normalize, and make logs available in real-time with integration into security monitoring workflows.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3246,387,4,'Intelligent','Advanced log analytics and correlation capabilities provide intelligent insights from log data. Machine learning and behavioral analysis enhance log utility, with automated filtering and prioritization to reduce noise and highlight security-relevant events.','Advanced log analytics with correlation and pattern recognition | Machine learning applied to log analysis for anomaly detection | Automated log filtering and event prioritization | Dynamic log generation based on threat intelligence and risk context','Look for advanced analytics capabilities that apply machine learning and correlation techniques to generate actionable insights from log data with automated prioritization and contextual analysis.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3247,387,5,'Adaptive','Log generation and availability continuously evolve based on threat landscape changes, organizational learning, and predictive analytics. The logging ecosystem self-optimizes to balance security visibility with performance, automatically adjusting collection parameters and retention based on emerging risks.','Self-optimizing log generation based on threat intelligence feeds | Predictive log analytics that anticipate security events | Adaptive log retention and collection policies that adjust to risk levels | Continuous learning system that improves log relevance and reduces false positives','Look for evidence of self-adapting logging systems that automatically adjust collection, retention, and analysis parameters based on threat intelligence and continuous learning from security events.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3248,388,1,'Ad Hoc','Software installation controls are inconsistent and rely primarily on user awareness and basic operating system defaults. Unauthorized software prevention occurs reactively when issues are discovered, with no systematic approach to blocking installations.','Limited or no centralized software installation policies | Users have local administrator rights on most systems | Software restrictions implemented on ad-hoc basis when problems arise | Reliance on antivirus scanning as primary prevention method','Look for absence of systematic software control policies and evidence that users can freely install software with minimal technical restrictions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3249,388,2,'Defined','Basic software installation policies and technical controls are documented and implemented across key systems. Application whitelisting or blacklisting approaches are used with defined approval processes for software installation requests.','Documented software installation and approval policies | Basic application control lists (whitelist/blacklist) implemented | Defined roles for software approval and installation | Standard user accounts with restricted installation privileges','Look for documented policies governing software installation and evidence of basic technical controls like application whitelisting or restricted user privileges.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3250,388,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive technical controls prevent unauthorized software installation across all platforms and are integrated with broader security management processes. Software approval workflows are standardized and consistently enforced through automated policy enforcement.','Enterprise-wide application control solutions deployed | Automated policy enforcement across all endpoints and servers | Integration with change management and asset management processes | Regular compliance monitoring and reporting on software controls','Look for enterprise-wide deployment of application control technologies with evidence of integration with other security and IT management processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3251,388,4,'Intelligent','Advanced behavioral analysis and machine learning capabilities enhance traditional software controls to detect and prevent sophisticated unauthorized software threats. The organization uses threat intelligence and risk analytics to dynamically adjust software control policies.','Behavioral analysis and anomaly detection for software execution | Threat intelligence integration for dynamic policy updates | Risk-based software approval processes with automated scoring | Advanced logging and analytics for software installation attempts','Look for advanced analytics capabilities that go beyond signature-based controls and evidence of threat intelligence integration for dynamic policy adjustment.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3252,388,5,'Adaptive','Software installation controls continuously evolve based on real-time threat landscape changes, organizational risk appetite, and business requirements. The system autonomously adapts policies and controls while maintaining optimal balance between security and operational efficiency.','Autonomous policy adaptation based on threat intelligence and business context | Self-healing and self-optimizing software control mechanisms | Predictive analytics for emerging software threats | Continuous feedback loops between business needs and security controls','Look for evidence of autonomous policy adaptation and self-optimizing controls that demonstrate continuous evolution based on changing threat landscape and business requirements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3253,389,1,'Ad Hoc','Secure software development practices are applied inconsistently and rely heavily on individual developer knowledge and initiative. Security considerations in software development are typically addressed reactively, often only after security issues are discovered in production systems.','Security practices vary significantly between development teams and projects | Security testing is performed sporadically or only when issues are reported | Security requirements are not systematically integrated into development processes | Limited or no formal security training for development teams','Look for evidence of inconsistent security practices across development teams with primarily reactive security measures and minimal formal integration of security into development workflows.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3254,389,2,'Defined','Basic secure software development practices are documented and standardized across the organization. Security requirements and coding standards are established, though implementation may still vary between teams and consistent enforcement is limited.','Documented secure coding standards and development procedures exist | Basic security training is provided to development teams | Security requirements are defined for most development projects | Static code analysis tools are deployed but may not be consistently used','Look for documented security development standards and procedures with evidence of basic security training and tools deployment, though consistent implementation may vary.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3255,389,3,'Integrated','Secure software development practices are consistently integrated throughout the software development lifecycle across all teams. Security controls are embedded into development processes, with regular security testing and validation performed as standard practice.','Security is integrated into all phases of the software development lifecycle | Automated security testing tools are consistently used across all projects | Regular security code reviews and threat modeling are performed | Security metrics are tracked and reported for development activities','Look for consistent implementation of security practices across all development teams with integrated security testing, regular reviews, and systematic tracking of security metrics.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3256,389,4,'Intelligent','Secure software development practices are optimized through advanced automation, analytics, and intelligence-driven approaches. The organization uses sophisticated tools and techniques to predict, prevent, and rapidly respond to security issues in the development process.','Advanced security analytics and AI-driven tools enhance development security | Predictive security analysis identifies potential vulnerabilities early in development | Automated security remediation is implemented where possible | Security practices are continuously optimized based on threat intelligence and performance data','Look for advanced automation and analytics in security practices with evidence of predictive capabilities, intelligent remediation, and data-driven optimization of security processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3257,389,5,'Adaptive','Secure software development practices continuously evolve and adapt in real-time based on emerging threats, changing business needs, and lessons learned. The organization demonstrates industry leadership in secure development practices and actively contributes to the broader security community.','Security practices automatically adapt to new threats and vulnerabilities in real-time | Organization contributes to and helps shape industry secure development standards | Advanced research and development of new security techniques is conducted | Security practices are continuously benchmarked and improved through external collaboration','Look for evidence of real-time adaptive security capabilities, industry leadership in secure development practices, and active contribution to advancing the field through research and community engagement.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3258,390,1,'Ad Hoc','Network protection is reactive and inconsistent, with basic security controls implemented on an ad-hoc basis. Access controls are primarily based on default configurations with minimal customization or oversight.','Default passwords and configurations remain unchanged | Basic firewall rules with minimal segmentation | Limited or no network access monitoring | Inconsistent application of security patches','Look for predominantly default security configurations with reactive, inconsistent implementation of basic network protection controls.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3259,390,2,'Defined','Network protection follows documented policies and procedures with standardized security controls. Access control mechanisms are formally defined but implementation may vary across different network segments.','Documented network security policies and procedures | Standardized firewall configurations and access control lists | Regular security patching process established | Basic network segmentation implemented','Look for documented network security policies with standardized controls that are consistently applied but may lack integration across all network environments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3260,390,3,'Integrated','Network protection is integrated across all environments with coordinated security controls and monitoring. Access controls are consistently enforced through centralized management systems with regular validation and updates.','Centralized network access control management | Integrated security monitoring across all network segments | Automated patch management and vulnerability remediation | Network segmentation aligned with business risk assessment','Look for integrated network security controls with centralized management, coordinated monitoring, and consistent enforcement across all network environments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3261,390,4,'Intelligent','Network protection leverages advanced analytics and threat intelligence to proactively identify and respond to security threats. Access controls dynamically adapt based on risk assessment and behavioral analysis.','AI-driven threat detection and response capabilities | Dynamic access controls based on risk and behavior analytics | Predictive vulnerability management and automated remediation | Advanced network segmentation with micro-segmentation','Look for advanced analytics-driven network protection with dynamic, risk-based access controls and proactive threat detection capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3262,390,5,'Adaptive','Network protection continuously evolves through machine learning and adaptive security architectures that automatically adjust to emerging threats. The organization maintains a self-healing network infrastructure that optimizes protection based on real-time threat landscape changes.','Self-healing network infrastructure with automated threat response | Machine learning-based adaptive security controls | Real-time optimization of network protection based on threat intelligence | Zero-trust architecture with continuous verification','Look for autonomous, self-adapting network protection systems that continuously optimize security postures based on machine learning and real-time threat intelligence.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3263,391,1,'Ad Hoc','Environmental protection for technology assets is reactive and inconsistent across the organisation. Basic measures may exist in some locations but are not systematically planned or implemented. Protection relies heavily on individual awareness and ad-hoc responses to environmental incidents.','Minimal or no formal environmental controls for critical technology assets | Reactive approach to environmental threats with limited preventive measures | Inconsistent application of basic protections like surge protectors or climate considerations | Environmental incidents frequently impact technology operations','Look for absence of systematic environmental protection planning and reactive responses to environmental threats affecting technology assets.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3264,391,2,'Defined','The organisation has established basic environmental protection standards and procedures for technology assets. Standard controls are documented and implemented consistently across most critical systems. Environmental risks are identified and addressed through defined processes.','Documented environmental protection standards for technology infrastructure | Basic environmental controls implemented (UPS, climate control, fire suppression) | Environmental risk assessments conducted for critical assets | Standard procedures exist for responding to environmental threats','Look for documented standards and consistent implementation of basic environmental protections across critical technology assets.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3265,391,3,'Integrated','Environmental protection is integrated into technology asset management and business continuity planning. Comprehensive controls are implemented based on risk assessments and regulatory requirements. Monitoring systems provide early warning of environmental threats to technology assets.','Environmental protection integrated with asset management and business continuity plans | Comprehensive monitoring systems for environmental conditions affecting technology | Regular testing and maintenance of environmental protection systems | Environmental resilience requirements integrated into technology procurement decisions','Look for integration of environmental protection with broader risk management and evidence of comprehensive monitoring and testing programs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3266,391,4,'Intelligent','Advanced environmental protection leverages automation, predictive analytics, and real-time monitoring to proactively protect technology assets. The organisation uses data-driven insights to optimise environmental controls and predict potential threats. Performance metrics drive continuous improvement of environmental resilience.','Automated environmental control systems with predictive capabilities | Real-time monitoring and alerting with integration to incident response systems | Data analytics used to optimise environmental protection and predict threats | Performance metrics and KPIs drive continuous improvement of environmental resilience','Look for evidence of automated systems, predictive capabilities, and data-driven optimisation of environmental protection for technology assets.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3267,391,5,'Adaptive','Environmental protection continuously evolves through machine learning, threat intelligence, and adaptive response capabilities. The organisation anticipates and adapts to emerging environmental threats through innovative technologies and cross-industry collaboration. Environmental resilience strategy dynamically adjusts based on changing conditions and emerging risks.','Machine learning and AI enhance environmental threat prediction and response | Adaptive environmental control systems that self-optimise based on conditions | Active participation in industry collaboration for environmental resilience best practices | Dynamic adjustment of environmental protection strategies based on emerging threats and climate changes','Look for evidence of adaptive systems, machine learning applications, and dynamic strategy adjustment in response to evolving environmental threats.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3268,392,1,'Ad Hoc','Resilience mechanisms are implemented reactively and inconsistently across the organization. Basic backup systems or redundant components may exist in some areas, but there is no systematic approach to ensuring resilience requirements are met.','Some backup systems exist but are not regularly tested | Resilience mechanisms are implemented on a case-by-case basis without coordination | Limited documentation of resilience capabilities | Resilience is primarily addressed after incidents occur','Look for evidence of basic resilience mechanisms that exist in isolation without systematic planning or consistent implementation across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3269,392,2,'Defined','Resilience requirements are formally documented and standard mechanisms are defined to achieve them. The organization has established policies and procedures for implementing resilience controls, though implementation may vary across different systems and departments.','Documented resilience requirements and standards exist | Standard resilience mechanisms are defined in policies and procedures | Regular backup and recovery procedures are established | Resilience mechanisms are implemented according to defined processes','Look for documented resilience requirements, established procedures, and evidence that standard resilience mechanisms are systematically implemented according to organizational policies.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3270,392,3,'Integrated','Resilience mechanisms are consistently implemented across all critical systems and integrated into business operations. The organization regularly tests and validates resilience capabilities, with coordinated approaches to maintaining resilience in both normal and adverse conditions.','Resilience mechanisms are consistently applied across all critical infrastructure | Regular testing and validation of resilience capabilities occurs | Integrated approach coordinates resilience across departments and systems | Performance metrics track resilience effectiveness','Look for consistent implementation of resilience mechanisms across the organization, regular testing programs, and evidence of coordinated resilience management with measurable outcomes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3271,392,4,'Intelligent','Resilience mechanisms leverage advanced technologies and data analytics to automatically adapt to changing conditions. The organization uses predictive capabilities and automated responses to maintain resilience, with continuous monitoring providing insights for optimization.','Automated resilience mechanisms that adapt to changing threat conditions | Predictive analytics inform resilience planning and response | Continuous monitoring provides real-time resilience status | Advanced technologies enable self-healing and automated failover capabilities','Look for evidence of automated and adaptive resilience mechanisms that use advanced technologies, predictive capabilities, and continuous monitoring to intelligently respond to changing conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3272,392,5,'Adaptive','Resilience mechanisms continuously evolve and self-optimize based on emerging threats, changing business requirements, and lessons learned. The organization maintains a dynamic resilience posture that automatically adjusts to new conditions and incorporates innovative approaches to maintaining operational continuity.','Self-optimizing resilience mechanisms that evolve with changing conditions | Dynamic adjustment of resilience strategies based on emerging threats and business changes | Continuous innovation in resilience approaches and technologies | Machine learning and AI enhance resilience decision-making and response','Look for evidence of self-evolving resilience mechanisms that continuously adapt and optimize themselves, incorporating emerging technologies and automatically adjusting to new threats and business requirements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3273,393,1,'Ad Hoc','Resource capacity planning is reactive and primarily driven by immediate needs or system failures. Organizations respond to capacity issues as they arise, often resulting in performance degradation or availability impacts before additional resources are provisioned.','Resource capacity planning occurs only when systems fail or performance degrades | No formal capacity monitoring or thresholds established | Resource provisioning decisions made on ad-hoc basis by individual administrators | Frequent system outages due to insufficient capacity','Look for evidence of reactive capacity management with no formal planning processes and regular availability issues due to resource constraints.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3274,393,2,'Defined','Basic capacity planning processes and procedures are documented and followed. Organizations have established minimum resource requirements and conduct periodic capacity assessments, though these may not be consistently applied across all systems.','Documented capacity planning procedures and resource allocation standards | Regular capacity monitoring with basic alerting thresholds | Defined roles and responsibilities for capacity management | Periodic capacity assessments conducted for critical systems','Look for documented capacity planning processes with evidence of regular monitoring and defined resource allocation standards being followed.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3275,393,3,'Integrated','Capacity planning is integrated across the organization with consistent application of standards and processes. Proactive capacity management includes forecasting, trend analysis, and coordinated resource provisioning aligned with business requirements and risk tolerance.','Integrated capacity planning across all critical systems and business units | Proactive capacity forecasting based on business growth and usage trends | Coordinated resource provisioning process with defined approval workflows | Regular capacity reports provided to management with risk assessments','Look for evidence of integrated capacity planning processes that proactively forecast needs and coordinate resource provisioning across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3276,393,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and automation drive intelligent capacity management decisions. Organizations leverage predictive modeling, machine learning, and automated provisioning to optimize resource utilization while maintaining availability targets with minimal human intervention.','Automated capacity provisioning and scaling based on predictive analytics | Machine learning models used for capacity forecasting and optimization | Real-time capacity optimization across hybrid and cloud environments | Integration of capacity management with performance and availability metrics','Look for evidence of automated, analytics-driven capacity management with predictive capabilities and minimal manual intervention required.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3277,393,5,'Adaptive','The organization demonstrates adaptive capacity management that continuously learns and evolves based on changing business conditions, threat landscape, and technology innovations. Capacity planning is dynamically adjusted based on real-time intelligence and emerging requirements.','Self-healing and adaptive resource allocation that responds to changing conditions | Continuous learning from capacity events to improve predictive models | Dynamic capacity optimization based on business priority and threat intelligence | Innovation in capacity management practices that influence industry standards','Look for evidence of self-adaptive capacity management systems that continuously evolve and innovate based on changing business and threat conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3278,394,1,'Ad Hoc','Network monitoring activities are sporadic and reactive, typically performed only when issues are suspected or reported. The organization relies on basic tools or manual checks without systematic processes for continuous network surveillance.','Network monitoring performed only during incident response | Use of basic ping/traceroute tools or simple network utilities | No documented network monitoring procedures | Monitoring activities depend on individual knowledge and availability','Look for evidence that network monitoring is performed reactively without systematic processes or dedicated monitoring infrastructure.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3279,394,2,'Defined','The organization has established basic network monitoring processes with documented procedures and assigned responsibilities. Network monitoring tools are deployed but may not provide comprehensive coverage across all network segments and services.','Documented network monitoring procedures and responsibilities | Basic network monitoring tools deployed (SNMP, basic IDS/IPS) | Regular monitoring of critical network segments and services | Network monitoring logs are collected and stored','Look for documented network monitoring procedures and evidence of regular monitoring activities covering key network infrastructure components.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3280,394,3,'Integrated','Network monitoring is comprehensively implemented across the entire network infrastructure with centralized monitoring systems. Monitoring data is correlated with other security tools and feeds into broader threat detection processes.','Comprehensive network monitoring coverage across all segments | Centralized network monitoring dashboard and alerting system | Integration between network monitoring and SIEM/security tools | Automated baseline establishment and anomaly detection for network traffic','Look for comprehensive network monitoring coverage with centralized systems that integrate with other security tools and provide automated threat detection capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3281,394,4,'Intelligent','Advanced network monitoring leverages machine learning and behavioral analytics to detect sophisticated threats and anomalies. The system provides intelligent alerting with reduced false positives and enhanced threat hunting capabilities across network traffic patterns.','Machine learning-based network traffic analysis and behavioral modeling | Advanced threat detection for encrypted traffic and lateral movement | Intelligent alert prioritization and false positive reduction | Network forensics capabilities with detailed packet analysis','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, machine learning capabilities, and intelligent threat detection that goes beyond signature-based monitoring to identify sophisticated network-based attacks.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3282,394,5,'Adaptive','Network monitoring continuously evolves and adapts to emerging threats through self-learning systems and automated threat intelligence integration. The system automatically adjusts monitoring parameters and detection rules based on the changing threat landscape and organizational context.','Self-adapting monitoring rules based on threat intelligence and attack patterns | Automated network segmentation and micro-segmentation based on traffic analysis | Predictive threat modeling for network-based attacks | Continuous optimization of monitoring coverage and detection algorithms','Look for evidence of self-adapting monitoring systems that automatically evolve detection capabilities and optimize monitoring strategies based on threat intelligence and organizational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3283,395,1,'Ad Hoc','Physical environment monitoring is inconsistent and reactive, often relying on basic security measures like locks and occasional visual checks. There is no systematic approach to detecting physical security incidents, and monitoring activities are performed sporadically when issues arise or are reported by staff.','Basic physical access controls (locks, keys) with no systematic monitoring | Incident detection relies primarily on employee reports or visual observation | No documented physical monitoring procedures or responsibilities | Physical security events are addressed reactively after discovery','The organization has minimal physical monitoring capabilities with no formal processes and relies primarily on basic access controls and reactive incident response.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3284,395,2,'Defined','The organization has established documented procedures for physical environment monitoring with assigned responsibilities. Basic monitoring systems such as security cameras or access card readers are implemented, though monitoring may not be continuous and response procedures are standardized but manual.','Documented physical security monitoring procedures and assigned responsibilities | Basic monitoring systems deployed (cameras, access controls, sensors) with periodic review | Standardized incident response procedures for physical security events | Regular but not continuous monitoring of critical physical areas','The organization has documented physical monitoring procedures with basic systems in place, but monitoring activities are not yet fully integrated or continuous.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3285,395,3,'Integrated','Physical environment monitoring is integrated across all facilities with continuous oversight of critical areas. Monitoring systems are centrally managed and coordinated with logical security systems, providing comprehensive coverage with defined escalation procedures and regular effectiveness reviews.','Continuous monitoring of physical environment across all facilities and critical areas | Integration between physical and logical security monitoring systems | Centralized security operations with defined escalation and response procedures | Regular assessment and testing of physical monitoring system effectiveness','The organization demonstrates continuous, integrated physical monitoring across all locations with coordinated response capabilities and regular effectiveness assessments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3286,395,4,'Intelligent','Physical monitoring systems utilize advanced analytics and automation to proactively identify potential threats and anomalies. The organization employs predictive capabilities, automated alerting, and machine learning to enhance detection accuracy while reducing false positives and enabling rapid response to emerging threats.','Advanced analytics and automated threat detection in physical monitoring systems | Predictive capabilities for identifying potential physical security risks | Machine learning algorithms to reduce false positives and improve detection accuracy | Real-time correlation of physical events with other security data sources','The organization demonstrates advanced, automated physical monitoring with predictive analytics and intelligent threat detection capabilities that proactively identify risks.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3287,395,5,'Adaptive','Physical monitoring systems continuously evolve and adapt based on threat intelligence, environmental changes, and lessons learned. The organization employs self-improving monitoring capabilities that automatically adjust detection parameters, integrate emerging technologies, and optimize performance based on real-world effectiveness and changing risk landscapes.','Self-adapting monitoring systems that evolve based on threat intelligence and environmental changes | Automatic optimization of detection parameters and monitoring coverage based on risk assessment | Integration of emerging technologies and innovative monitoring solutions | Continuous improvement process that incorporates lessons learned and industry best practices','The organization has adaptive physical monitoring systems that automatically evolve and optimize based on changing threats, environmental factors, and continuous learning from security events.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3288,396,1,'Ad Hoc','Personnel activity and technology usage monitoring occurs sporadically and reactively, typically only when incidents are suspected or reported. Monitoring capabilities are basic and rely heavily on manual processes or simple logging tools with limited analysis.','Basic system logs are collected but rarely reviewed | Monitoring efforts are triggered only by security incidents or complaints | Limited visibility into user activities across systems | No formal procedures for monitoring personnel or technology usage','Look for evidence of reactive, incident-driven monitoring with minimal proactive oversight of personnel activities and technology usage.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3289,396,2,'Defined','Formal policies and procedures exist for monitoring personnel activity and technology usage. Basic monitoring tools are deployed consistently across key systems, with defined roles and responsibilities for review and analysis of monitoring data.','Written policies define what personnel activities and technology usage should be monitored | Dedicated monitoring tools are deployed on critical systems | Regular review schedules are established for monitoring data | Clear roles assigned for monitoring oversight and incident response','Assessors should find documented monitoring procedures with consistent implementation across key systems and assigned responsibilities for oversight.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3290,396,3,'Integrated','Personnel activity and technology usage monitoring is comprehensively integrated across the organization''s systems and processes. Monitoring data is correlated and analyzed systematically, with established thresholds and alerting mechanisms for potentially adverse events.','Comprehensive monitoring coverage across all systems and user activities | Automated correlation and analysis of monitoring data from multiple sources | Established baselines and thresholds for normal vs. suspicious behavior | Integration with incident response and risk management processes','Evidence should show enterprise-wide monitoring integration with automated analysis capabilities and systematic correlation of personnel activity data.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3291,396,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics, machine learning, and behavioral analysis are used to intelligently monitor personnel activities and technology usage. The system can automatically identify anomalous patterns and adapt monitoring parameters based on evolving threat landscapes and user behavior patterns.','Machine learning algorithms detect behavioral anomalies and suspicious patterns | Predictive analytics identify potential insider threats before incidents occur | Dynamic risk scoring adjusts monitoring intensity based on user behavior and context | Automated response capabilities for low-risk anomalies','Look for evidence of advanced analytics and machine learning capabilities that provide predictive insights and automated behavioral anomaly detection.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3292,396,5,'Adaptive','The monitoring system continuously evolves and self-optimizes based on emerging threats, organizational changes, and lessons learned from security events. It seamlessly adapts monitoring strategies and integrates threat intelligence to proactively identify sophisticated insider threats and advanced persistent threats targeting personnel.','Self-learning systems automatically adjust monitoring parameters based on threat intelligence and organizational context | Continuous optimization of detection algorithms based on feedback loops and security outcomes | Seamless integration with external threat intelligence feeds and industry security communities | Proactive monitoring strategies evolve in real-time based on emerging attack patterns','Evidence should demonstrate self-optimizing monitoring capabilities that continuously adapt based on threat intelligence, organizational changes, and security event outcomes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3293,397,1,'Ad Hoc','External service provider monitoring is reactive and inconsistent, typically occurring only after incidents or problems arise. Organizations rely primarily on service provider self-reporting and ad-hoc manual checks with no systematic approach to monitoring third-party activities.','Monitoring occurs only after incidents or complaints | Reliance on vendor-provided reports without verification | No documented monitoring procedures or schedules | Limited visibility into external service provider security events','Look for evidence that external service provider monitoring is purely reactive with no proactive or systematic monitoring capabilities in place.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3294,397,2,'Defined','Basic monitoring procedures for external service providers are documented and implemented with defined roles and responsibilities. Organizations have established minimum monitoring requirements and regular review processes, though execution may be inconsistent across different providers.','Documented monitoring procedures and schedules for critical vendors | Defined roles and responsibilities for vendor oversight | Regular reviews of service provider security reports and SLA compliance | Basic incident notification requirements established with key providers','Look for documented procedures and evidence of regular, scheduled monitoring activities for at least critical external service providers.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3295,397,3,'Integrated','External service provider monitoring is systematically integrated across all business units with consistent processes and tools. Organizations maintain comprehensive visibility into provider activities through standardized monitoring frameworks and have established clear escalation procedures for adverse events.','Standardized monitoring applied across all external service providers | Integration with internal security monitoring systems and workflows | Established SLAs with monitoring and reporting requirements | Regular risk assessments incorporating provider monitoring data','Look for evidence of consistent, organization-wide monitoring processes that are integrated with internal security operations and risk management activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3296,397,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and automated tools provide intelligent monitoring of external service provider activities with predictive capabilities. Organizations leverage threat intelligence and behavioral analytics to proactively identify potential risks and adverse events before they impact operations.','Automated monitoring tools with analytics and alerting capabilities | Integration of threat intelligence for provider risk assessment | Predictive analysis of provider performance and security trends | Real-time dashboards providing comprehensive provider risk visibility','Look for evidence of automated, analytics-driven monitoring systems that provide predictive insights and proactive risk identification for external service providers.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3297,397,5,'Adaptive','External service provider monitoring continuously evolves through machine learning and AI-driven optimization that adapts to changing threat landscapes and business requirements. The organization maintains dynamic, risk-based monitoring that automatically adjusts based on provider behavior, threat intelligence, and business context.','AI/ML-driven adaptive monitoring that evolves with threat landscape | Dynamic risk-based monitoring intensity based on provider behavior | Automated response and remediation capabilities for provider-related risks | Continuous optimization of monitoring strategies based on outcomes and feedback','Look for evidence of self-adapting monitoring systems that use AI/ML to continuously optimize monitoring strategies and automatically adjust to evolving risks and business needs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3298,398,1,'Ad Hoc','Hardware and software monitoring is sporadic and reactive, typically occurring only when problems are already evident or during crisis situations. Basic system logs may be generated but are rarely reviewed systematically, and monitoring tools are limited or ad-hoc in nature.','Monitoring occurs only during incidents or outages | Basic system logs exist but lack regular review processes | Limited or no dedicated monitoring tools deployed | Manual checks performed inconsistently by individual staff members','Look for evidence that hardware and software monitoring is primarily reactive with no systematic approach to continuous observation of computing resources.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3299,398,2,'Defined','Formal procedures exist for monitoring critical hardware and software components with defined responsibilities and processes. Standard monitoring tools are deployed across key systems, and regular review schedules are established, though implementation may be inconsistent across different areas.','Documented monitoring procedures and responsibilities exist | Standard monitoring tools deployed on critical systems | Regular review schedules established for system logs and alerts | Basic alerting mechanisms configured for critical hardware/software failures','Look for documented monitoring procedures and evidence that standard monitoring tools are systematically deployed with defined review processes for critical systems.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3300,398,3,'Integrated','Hardware and software monitoring is consistently implemented across the entire computing environment with integrated toolsets and centralized management. Monitoring data is correlated across systems and automatically feeds into incident response and risk management processes.','Comprehensive monitoring coverage across all computing assets | Centralized monitoring dashboard with integrated alerting | Automated correlation of monitoring data across systems | Direct integration between monitoring alerts and incident response workflows','Look for evidence of comprehensive, centralized monitoring that consistently covers all computing assets with automated integration into broader security and operational processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3301,398,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and machine learning enhance monitoring capabilities to predict potential issues and automatically adapt monitoring parameters. The system provides intelligent insights about hardware and software behavior patterns and can proactively identify anomalies before they become critical problems.','Machine learning algorithms analyze monitoring data for predictive insights | Automated adjustment of monitoring thresholds based on behavioral patterns | Proactive identification of potential hardware/software issues before failure | Advanced analytics correlate monitoring data with threat intelligence and business context','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, machine learning, or AI-driven monitoring that provides predictive capabilities and intelligent automation beyond traditional threshold-based alerting.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3302,398,5,'Adaptive','The monitoring system continuously evolves and self-optimizes based on changing threat landscapes, business requirements, and lessons learned from monitoring effectiveness. It automatically adapts monitoring strategies, implements new detection capabilities, and optimizes resource allocation based on real-time risk assessments and business priorities.','Continuous optimization of monitoring strategies based on effectiveness metrics | Automatic deployment of new monitoring capabilities in response to emerging threats | Self-tuning monitoring systems that adapt to changing business and technical environments | Dynamic resource allocation for monitoring based on real-time risk assessment','Look for evidence of a self-evolving monitoring ecosystem that automatically adapts its strategies, capabilities, and resource allocation based on changing conditions and continuous learning from monitoring effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3303,399,1,'Ad Hoc','Analysis of potentially adverse events occurs sporadically and reactively, typically only when incidents have already caused significant impact. Event analysis is performed manually by individual staff members using basic tools and informal methods, with limited documentation or standardisation.','Event analysis only occurs after major incidents | Analysis relies on basic manual review of logs or alerts | No standardised methodology or documentation for event analysis | Limited or no collaboration between teams during analysis','Look for evidence that event analysis happens inconsistently and only in response to clear security incidents, with minimal structured processes or tools.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3304,399,2,'Defined','Formal procedures and methodologies exist for analysing potentially adverse events, with designated roles and responsibilities clearly defined. Analysis is conducted using documented processes and basic analytical tools, though execution may still be inconsistent across the organisation.','Documented procedures for event analysis exist | Specific roles assigned for conducting event analysis | Basic analytical tools and techniques are defined | Analysis results are documented and stored systematically','Look for evidence of documented event analysis procedures, assigned responsibilities, and consistent use of defined methodologies across the organisation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3305,399,3,'Integrated','Event analysis is fully integrated into security operations workflows with automated collection and correlation capabilities. Analysis processes consistently incorporate threat intelligence, historical data, and cross-functional expertise to provide comprehensive understanding of potentially adverse events.','Automated event correlation and analysis tools are deployed | Threat intelligence feeds integrated into analysis processes | Cross-functional teams collaborate systematically on event analysis | Analysis results inform security controls and incident response procedures','Look for evidence that event analysis is embedded in operational workflows with automated tools and consistent integration of multiple data sources and expertise areas.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3306,399,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics, machine learning, and artificial intelligence capabilities enhance event analysis to identify subtle patterns and predict potential threats. The organisation leverages behavioural analytics and advanced correlation techniques to proactively identify and analyse events before they escalate.','Machine learning and AI tools enhance event pattern recognition | Behavioural analytics identify anomalous activities automatically | Predictive capabilities help anticipate potential adverse events | Advanced correlation across multiple data sources and timeframes','Look for evidence of advanced analytical capabilities that can identify complex patterns and provide predictive insights about potentially adverse events.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3307,399,5,'Adaptive','Event analysis capabilities continuously evolve and adapt based on emerging threats, lessons learned, and changing business context. The system self-optimises analysis techniques and automatically adjusts detection parameters based on effectiveness metrics and environmental changes.','Analysis methods automatically adapt to new threat patterns | System learns from analysis outcomes to improve future detection | Dynamic adjustment of analysis parameters based on environmental changes | Continuous feedback loops optimize analysis effectiveness across the threat landscape','Look for evidence that event analysis capabilities automatically evolve and self-optimise based on effectiveness metrics, threat landscape changes, and organisational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3308,400,1,'Ad Hoc','Information correlation occurs sporadically and is largely dependent on individual initiative or crisis situations. Security teams manually collect and compare data from different sources on an ad-hoc basis when investigating specific incidents. There is no systematic approach to correlating information across security tools or data sources.','Manual correlation performed only during incident response | Limited to basic log comparison between 2-3 sources | No standardized correlation processes or procedures | Heavy reliance on individual analyst knowledge and experience','Look for evidence that information correlation is reactive, manual, and inconsistently applied across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3309,400,2,'Defined','The organization has established documented procedures for correlating information from multiple sources during security analysis. Basic correlation rules and processes are defined, though implementation may still be largely manual. Security teams follow standardized workflows when analyzing events from different security tools and data sources.','Documented correlation procedures and workflows exist | Standard operating procedures for multi-source analysis | Basic correlation rules implemented in security tools | Regular correlation activities scheduled for key security events','Look for documented processes and evidence of consistent application of correlation procedures across security analysis activities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3310,400,3,'Integrated','Information correlation is systematically integrated across security operations through automated tools and centralized platforms. The organization maintains a comprehensive inventory of data sources and has implemented technical solutions to aggregate and correlate information in near real-time. Correlation processes are embedded into standard security workflows and incident response procedures.','SIEM or security orchestration platform aggregates multiple data sources | Automated correlation rules cover majority of security use cases | Cross-functional teams participate in correlation analysis | Integration with threat intelligence feeds and external data sources','Look for evidence of systematic integration of correlation capabilities across security operations with automated aggregation from multiple sources.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3311,400,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages advanced analytics, machine learning, and artificial intelligence to enhance information correlation capabilities. Correlation processes continuously learn from patterns and adapt based on emerging threats and organizational context. The system can identify complex, multi-stage attacks by correlating seemingly unrelated events across diverse data sources and timeframes.','Machine learning algorithms enhance correlation accuracy | Behavioral analytics identify anomalous patterns across sources | Advanced persistent threat detection through timeline correlation | Predictive correlation capabilities based on threat intelligence and historical patterns','Look for evidence of advanced analytics and machine learning capabilities that enhance correlation beyond traditional rule-based approaches.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3312,400,5,'Adaptive','The correlation system continuously evolves and adapts in real-time based on changing threat landscapes, organizational context, and feedback loops. The organization maintains dynamic correlation capabilities that automatically adjust correlation logic, data sources, and analysis parameters based on effectiveness metrics and emerging threat intelligence. The system provides predictive insights and proactive threat hunting capabilities through adaptive correlation models.','Self-tuning correlation algorithms adjust based on effectiveness metrics | Dynamic integration of new data sources and threat intelligence | Proactive threat hunting through adaptive correlation patterns | Continuous feedback loops improve correlation accuracy and reduce false positives','Look for evidence of self-adapting correlation systems that continuously evolve based on effectiveness metrics and changing threat environments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3313,401,1,'Ad Hoc','Impact and scope assessment of adverse events occurs inconsistently and relies heavily on individual expertise or intuition. When adverse events are detected, there is limited systematic approach to understanding their full implications, often resulting in incomplete or inaccurate assessments.','Impact assessment performed reactively by available staff | No standardized criteria for measuring event scope or impact | Assessment quality varies significantly depending on personnel involved | Limited documentation of impact analysis decisions','Look for evidence that impact and scope assessments happen irregularly with no consistent methodology or criteria.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3314,401,2,'Defined','The organization has established basic procedures and criteria for assessing the impact and scope of adverse events. Standard templates and classification schemes exist to guide impact assessment activities, though implementation may still be inconsistent across different teams or event types.','Documented procedures for impact and scope assessment | Basic impact classification criteria established (e.g., high/medium/low) | Standard templates or forms used for assessment documentation | Designated roles responsible for conducting impact analysis','Look for documented procedures and standardized criteria that guide impact assessment, even if not consistently applied across all scenarios.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3315,401,3,'Integrated','Impact and scope assessment is systematically integrated into incident response workflows with consistent application across the organization. Assessment activities are coordinated across relevant teams and stakeholders, with clear communication channels for sharing impact analysis results.','Impact assessment integrated into incident response procedures | Cross-functional coordination for comprehensive scope analysis | Consistent application of assessment criteria across all event types | Regular communication of impact assessments to relevant stakeholders','Look for evidence that impact assessment is consistently integrated into response workflows with cross-organizational coordination and stakeholder communication.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3316,401,4,'Intelligent','The organization leverages data analytics, automation, and intelligence sources to enhance impact and scope assessment accuracy and speed. Historical event data and business context inform assessment decisions, with sophisticated modeling used to predict potential cascading effects.','Automated tools assist in impact and scope assessment | Historical data and trends inform assessment decisions | Business impact modeling considers cascading effects | Integration with threat intelligence to understand attack patterns and potential scope','Look for evidence of data-driven assessment capabilities using automation, historical analysis, and predictive modeling to enhance accuracy.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3317,401,5,'Adaptive','Impact and scope assessment capabilities continuously evolve through machine learning, feedback loops, and lessons learned integration. The organization proactively refines assessment models based on emerging threats, business changes, and assessment accuracy metrics, with real-time adjustment capabilities.','Machine learning enhances assessment accuracy over time | Continuous improvement of assessment models based on feedback | Real-time adjustment of scope assessment as events evolve | Proactive refinement based on threat landscape changes and business evolution','Look for evidence of self-improving assessment capabilities that adapt and evolve based on feedback, emerging threats, and changing business context.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3318,402,1,'Ad Hoc','Information about adverse events is shared informally and inconsistently across the organisation. Communication typically occurs through ad-hoc emails, phone calls, or verbal notifications with no standardised process or systematic approach.','Adverse event information shared through informal channels like email or verbal communication | No standardised process for information distribution | Limited or unclear identification of who should receive adverse event information | Inconsistent timing and completeness of information sharing','Evidence shows adverse event information sharing occurs sporadically through informal methods without defined processes or consistent recipient lists.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3319,402,2,'Defined','The organisation has established documented procedures for sharing adverse event information with authorised personnel. Clear roles and responsibilities are defined, though implementation may be manual and processes are applied consistently within individual teams or departments.','Documented procedures exist for adverse event information sharing | Authorised personnel and their roles are clearly identified | Standard communication templates or formats are used | Regular distribution lists are maintained for different types of adverse events','Documentation demonstrates defined processes and procedures for sharing adverse event information with identified authorised staff members.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3320,402,3,'Integrated','Adverse event information sharing is integrated across the organisation through centralised systems and standardised workflows. Automated notifications and escalation procedures ensure timely and consistent distribution to all relevant stakeholders and security tools.','Centralised incident management system facilitates information sharing | Automated notifications and alerts are configured for different stakeholder groups | Integration with security tools for automated information distribution | Cross-functional teams receive coordinated adverse event information','Evidence shows integrated systems and automated processes that consistently share adverse event information across organisational boundaries and with security tools.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3321,402,4,'Intelligent','The organisation uses intelligent analysis to contextualise and prioritise adverse event information before distribution. Advanced analytics determine the most relevant information for specific audiences, and machine learning helps optimise communication effectiveness and reduce information overload.','AI/ML algorithms analyse and contextualise adverse event information before sharing | Dynamic recipient selection based on event characteristics and relevance | Intelligent filtering reduces information overload while maintaining awareness | Advanced correlation provides enriched context to recipients','Systems demonstrate intelligent analysis and contextualisation of adverse event information with dynamic, risk-based distribution to optimise recipient relevance and effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3322,402,5,'Adaptive','The adverse event information sharing system continuously evolves and adapts based on feedback, threat landscape changes, and organisational learning. The system self-optimises communication patterns, recipient engagement, and information relevance through continuous improvement mechanisms.','System continuously adapts information sharing based on recipient feedback and effectiveness metrics | Self-learning algorithms improve information relevance and timing over time | Dynamic adjustment of communication strategies based on threat landscape evolution | Continuous optimisation of stakeholder engagement and response effectiveness','Evidence demonstrates a self-improving system that continuously adapts adverse event information sharing strategies based on effectiveness metrics, feedback, and evolving threat conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3323,403,1,'Ad Hoc','Cyber threat intelligence integration is sporadic and inconsistent, typically occurring only during major incidents. Analysis relies primarily on basic security tool outputs with minimal external context or threat intelligence feeds.','Threat intelligence used only reactively during major incidents | Analysis primarily based on internal security tool alerts | No formal process for incorporating external threat data | Limited or no access to threat intelligence feeds','Look for evidence that threat intelligence is only used occasionally during significant security events with no systematic integration into regular analysis processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3324,403,2,'Defined','Basic threat intelligence feeds are established and documented procedures exist for incorporating external threat data into incident analysis. Integration occurs through manual processes with defined roles and responsibilities for threat intelligence utilization.','Documented procedures for using threat intelligence in analysis | Access to commercial or open source threat feeds | Manual correlation of threat data with security events | Designated personnel responsible for threat intelligence activities','Look for documented processes and assigned responsibilities for integrating threat intelligence, even if the integration is primarily manual and reactive.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3325,403,3,'Integrated','Threat intelligence is systematically integrated into security analysis workflows through automated feeds and standardized processes. Multiple intelligence sources are correlated with internal security data to provide enriched context for event analysis across the organization.','Automated ingestion of multiple threat intelligence feeds | Standardized threat intelligence formats and data models | Integration with SIEM and other security tools | Regular threat briefings and intelligence sharing across teams','Look for evidence of systematic, automated integration of threat intelligence across security tools and processes with consistent organizational adoption.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3326,403,4,'Intelligent','Advanced threat intelligence capabilities include predictive analysis and automated contextualization of threats specific to the organization''s environment. Intelligence is dynamically integrated into security operations with machine learning enhancing relevance and reducing false positives.','Predictive threat modeling and analysis capabilities | Automated threat hunting based on intelligence feeds | Custom threat intelligence tailored to organizational context | Machine learning enhanced threat correlation and prioritization','Look for evidence of advanced analytical capabilities that proactively leverage threat intelligence for predictive security measures and automated threat hunting.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3327,403,5,'Adaptive','Threat intelligence integration is fully autonomous and self-optimizing, continuously adapting to emerging threats and organizational changes. The system learns from analysis outcomes to improve future threat detection and provides real-time, contextual intelligence that automatically adjusts security posture.','Autonomous threat intelligence collection and analysis | Self-optimizing threat models that adapt to organizational changes | Real-time threat landscape adaptation | Continuous learning from analysis outcomes to improve detection capabilities','Look for evidence of fully autonomous threat intelligence systems that continuously learn, adapt, and optimize without human intervention while providing real-time security posture adjustments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3328,404,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident declaration is inconsistent and reactive, typically occurring only when adverse events cause significant disruption or are reported by external parties. There are no formal criteria for determining when adverse events should be escalated to incidents, leading to delayed or missed declarations.','No documented criteria for incident declaration | Incident declaration depends on individual judgment | Significant delays between adverse event detection and incident declaration | External parties often report incidents before internal declaration','Look for absence of formal incident declaration criteria and evidence of inconsistent, reactive incident declaration practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3329,404,2,'Defined','Basic incident declaration criteria have been documented and established, with clear thresholds for escalating adverse events to incidents. Staff understand the criteria, though application may still be inconsistent across different teams or situations.','Documented incident declaration criteria exist | Clear escalation thresholds are defined | Basic training provided on incident declaration process | Some inconsistency in criteria application across teams','Look for documented incident declaration criteria and evidence that staff understand when to escalate adverse events to incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3330,404,3,'Integrated','Incident declaration criteria are consistently applied across the organization with standardized processes integrated into detection workflows. Automated systems support decision-making, and there is regular review and refinement of declaration criteria based on operational experience.','Consistent application of incident declaration criteria organization-wide | Automated tools support incident declaration decisions | Regular review and updates of declaration criteria | Integration with broader incident response workflows','Look for consistent application of incident declaration criteria across the organization and evidence of integrated, standardized processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3331,404,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and machine learning enhance incident declaration accuracy by analyzing patterns in adverse events and automatically triggering declarations based on intelligent criteria. The system learns from past incidents to continuously improve declaration timing and accuracy.','Machine learning algorithms support incident declaration decisions | Predictive analytics identify potential incidents before full manifestation | Automated correlation of multiple adverse events for incident declaration | Continuous learning improves declaration accuracy over time','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, machine learning, or AI capabilities that intelligently support and improve incident declaration processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3332,404,5,'Adaptive','The incident declaration system dynamically adapts criteria based on changing threat landscapes, business context, and risk appetite in real-time. Self-optimizing algorithms continuously refine declaration thresholds and processes, while the system proactively adjusts to emerging attack patterns and organizational changes.','Real-time adaptation of incident declaration criteria based on threat intelligence | Self-optimizing algorithms adjust thresholds automatically | Dynamic integration with business context and risk appetite | Proactive adjustment to emerging threats and organizational changes','Look for evidence of real-time, self-adapting incident declaration capabilities that automatically adjust to changing conditions and emerging threats.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3333,405,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident response plan execution is informal and reactive, with limited coordination structures in place. Third-party involvement is handled on a case-by-case basis without established protocols or clear communication channels.','Incident response activities are performed inconsistently without formal procedures | Third-party coordination is reactive and ad-hoc with no pre-established relationships | Communication during incidents relies on individual knowledge rather than documented processes | Response actions vary significantly between incidents and responders','Look for evidence of informal, inconsistent incident response execution with minimal third-party coordination protocols.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3334,405,2,'Defined','A documented incident response plan exists and is followed when incidents are declared. Basic coordination procedures with relevant third parties are established, though execution may still be somewhat manual and dependent on individual expertise.','Documented incident response procedures are consistently followed | Pre-identified third-party contacts and escalation procedures exist | Clear roles and responsibilities are defined for incident response team members | Standard communication templates and channels are established for incident coordination','Look for documented procedures that are consistently followed with established third-party coordination processes during incident response.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3335,405,3,'Integrated','Incident response plan execution is well-integrated across the organization with seamless coordination between internal teams and external parties. Third-party relationships are formalized through contracts and regular communication, enabling efficient collaborative response.','Incident response integrates seamlessly across all organizational functions and business units | Formal agreements and communication protocols exist with key third parties | Regular testing and exercises include third-party participants | Automated workflows facilitate coordination and information sharing during incidents','Look for integrated incident response execution with formalized third-party relationships and regular collaborative testing.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3336,405,4,'Intelligent','Incident response execution leverages advanced analytics and intelligence to optimize coordination and decision-making. Third-party coordination is enhanced through shared threat intelligence platforms and automated information exchange mechanisms.','Real-time analytics and metrics inform incident response decisions and third-party coordination | Automated threat intelligence sharing occurs with relevant third parties during incidents | Predictive capabilities help anticipate coordination needs and resource requirements | Advanced collaboration platforms enable seamless information sharing and joint response activities','Look for evidence of analytics-driven incident response with intelligent automation supporting third-party coordination and information sharing.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3337,405,5,'Adaptive','Incident response plan execution continuously adapts based on real-time threat landscape changes and lessons learned. The organization maintains dynamic third-party coordination capabilities that automatically adjust based on incident characteristics and emerging threat patterns.','Incident response procedures automatically adapt based on threat intelligence and incident characteristics | Dynamic third-party coordination adjusts in real-time based on incident severity and type | Machine learning capabilities optimize response coordination and resource allocation | Continuous feedback loops drive real-time improvements to response execution and third-party integration','Look for evidence of self-adapting incident response execution with dynamic third-party coordination that evolves based on real-time conditions and continuous learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3338,406,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident reports are handled inconsistently with no formal triage process in place. Response depends heavily on individual knowledge and availability, leading to unpredictable outcomes and delayed responses.','Incident reports pile up without systematic review | Response times vary dramatically based on who receives the report | No documented criteria for determining incident priority or validity | Critical incidents may be missed or delayed due to lack of structure','Look for absence of formal triage procedures and evidence that incident handling varies significantly depending on circumstances or personnel involved.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3339,406,2,'Defined','Basic triage procedures are documented and followed for incident report processing. Clear criteria exist for initial validation and prioritization, though execution may still be inconsistent across different teams or time periods.','Documented triage procedures and validation criteria exist | Incident reports are assigned priority levels based on defined categories | Basic validation checks are performed to confirm incident legitimacy | Initial response timeframes are established for different incident types','Look for documented triage processes with evidence of their regular use, including defined validation steps and prioritization criteria.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3340,406,3,'Integrated','Triage and validation processes are consistently applied across the organization with integrated workflows and systems. Cross-functional coordination ensures efficient routing and escalation of validated incidents to appropriate response teams.','Triage process integrated with incident management systems and workflows | Consistent application of validation criteria across all reporting channels | Automated routing of triaged incidents to appropriate response teams | Regular monitoring of triage effectiveness and response times','Look for evidence of consistent triage execution supported by integrated systems and measurable process adherence across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3341,406,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and automation enhance triage accuracy and speed, with intelligent filtering reducing false positives. Data-driven insights continuously improve validation criteria and prioritization accuracy based on historical patterns and emerging threats.','Automated pre-filtering and correlation of incident reports | Machine learning or AI assists in incident validation and prioritization | Predictive analytics help identify potential incident patterns | Real-time dashboards provide triage performance metrics and trends','Look for evidence of advanced technologies improving triage accuracy and efficiency, with data analytics driving continuous process optimization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3342,406,5,'Adaptive','The triage system dynamically adapts to evolving threat landscapes and organizational changes through continuous learning and optimization. Self-tuning algorithms and real-time threat intelligence integration ensure optimal incident validation and prioritization.','Dynamic adjustment of triage criteria based on emerging threats and organizational context | Self-learning systems improve validation accuracy over time | Real-time integration with external threat intelligence feeds | Automatic optimization of resource allocation based on incident trends and organizational capacity','Look for evidence of autonomous system adaptation and continuous optimization that responds to changing conditions without manual intervention.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3343,407,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident categorisation and prioritisation occurs inconsistently and is largely dependent on individual judgment. There are no formal criteria or processes for classifying incidents, leading to inconsistent handling and response priorities.','No documented categorisation scheme exists | Prioritisation decisions are made subjectively by whoever receives the incident | Response times and resource allocation vary wildly between similar incidents | Limited or no tracking of incident categories and priorities','Look for absence of formal incident classification processes and evidence that prioritisation is inconsistent and personality-driven.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3344,407,2,'Defined','Basic incident categorisation and prioritisation processes are documented with clear criteria for classification levels. Staff are trained on the categorisation scheme and follow established procedures for assigning priorities based on impact and urgency.','Documented incident categorisation framework with defined severity levels | Clear prioritisation criteria based on business impact and urgency | Staff trained on classification procedures | Consistent application of categories across the incident management team','Look for documented processes being consistently followed with evidence of staff training and standardised categorisation practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3345,407,3,'Integrated','Incident categorisation and prioritisation is fully integrated with business processes and stakeholder requirements. The classification system considers business context, regulatory requirements, and stakeholder impact with clear escalation pathways.','Categorisation aligned with business criticality and regulatory requirements | Automated workflows trigger based on incident categories | Regular stakeholder input on prioritisation criteria | Integration with business continuity and risk management processes','Look for evidence that categorisation reflects business priorities and integrates with broader organisational risk and continuity frameworks.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3346,407,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and threat intelligence inform dynamic incident categorisation and prioritisation decisions. The organisation uses data-driven insights to continuously refine classification criteria and predict incident impacts.','Machine learning or AI assists with initial incident categorisation | Threat intelligence feeds inform priority adjustments | Predictive analytics help forecast incident impact and resource needs | Real-time dashboards provide categorisation metrics and trends','Look for evidence of advanced analytics, automation, and data-driven decision making in the categorisation and prioritisation processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3347,407,5,'Adaptive','The incident categorisation and prioritisation system continuously evolves based on emerging threats, business changes, and lessons learned. The organisation proactively adjusts classification criteria and shares insights with industry peers and threat intelligence communities.','Self-learning systems automatically update categorisation criteria based on outcomes | Proactive adjustment of priorities based on threat landscape changes | Contribution to industry threat intelligence and categorisation standards | Continuous experimentation and improvement of classification methodologies','Look for evidence of self-improving systems, proactive threat adaptation, and active contribution to industry knowledge on incident classification.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3348,408,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident escalation occurs inconsistently and is primarily driven by individual judgment or crisis situations. There are no formal escalation criteria or procedures, leading to delays or inappropriate escalation decisions. Critical incidents may not receive proper attention while minor issues might be unnecessarily escalated.','No documented escalation criteria or procedures | Escalation decisions are made ad-hoc by individual responders | Inconsistent timing and appropriateness of escalations | Limited or no management involvement in escalation decisions','Look for absence of formal escalation procedures and evidence of inconsistent escalation practices across different incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3349,408,2,'Defined','Basic escalation procedures and criteria are documented and communicated to incident response teams. Escalation paths are established with clear roles and responsibilities, though execution may still be inconsistent. Standard escalation triggers are defined based on incident severity and impact levels.','Documented escalation procedures and criteria exist | Clear escalation paths and contact lists are maintained | Escalation triggers are defined based on incident severity | Basic training provided on escalation procedures','Look for documented escalation procedures with defined criteria and evidence that staff are aware of these procedures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3350,408,3,'Integrated','Escalation procedures are consistently implemented across all incident types with standardized processes integrated into incident management workflows. Escalation decisions are made systematically based on predefined criteria, and there are established feedback loops to ensure appropriate escalation outcomes. Multiple escalation paths exist for different types of incidents and organizational functions.','Escalation procedures are consistently followed across all incidents | Multiple escalation paths exist for different incident types | Escalation decisions are tracked and monitored for effectiveness | Regular review and updates of escalation criteria based on lessons learned','Look for consistent application of escalation procedures across incidents and evidence of systematic tracking and improvement of escalation processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3351,408,4,'Intelligent','Escalation processes are enhanced with intelligent automation and predictive capabilities that can recommend or automatically trigger escalations based on incident patterns and organizational impact. Real-time monitoring and analytics inform dynamic escalation decisions, while machine learning helps optimize escalation timing and paths. Advanced metrics provide insights into escalation effectiveness and organizational response capabilities.','Automated escalation triggers based on predefined rules and patterns | Predictive analytics inform escalation decisions | Real-time dashboards provide escalation status and metrics | Machine learning optimizes escalation paths and timing','Look for evidence of automated escalation capabilities, predictive analytics, and data-driven optimization of escalation processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3352,408,5,'Adaptive','Escalation processes continuously evolve and self-optimize based on changing threat landscapes, organizational structure, and business priorities. The system dynamically adjusts escalation criteria and paths in real-time based on contextual factors, organizational learning, and external intelligence. Advanced AI capabilities enable autonomous escalation decisions while maintaining human oversight for complex scenarios.','Escalation processes automatically adapt to changing threat landscapes and business priorities | AI-driven autonomous escalation decisions with human oversight | Dynamic adjustment of escalation criteria based on real-time context | Continuous learning from internal and external threat intelligence','Look for evidence of self-adapting escalation processes that automatically adjust to changing conditions and demonstrate continuous learning capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3353,409,1,'Ad Hoc','Recovery initiation decisions are made spontaneously without established criteria or formal processes. Recovery timing is determined by individual judgment or when immediate pressure mounts to restore services. There is no consistent approach to determining when it is safe or appropriate to begin recovery activities.','Recovery decisions made by individual judgment without formal criteria | No documented process for determining recovery readiness | Recovery timing driven by business pressure rather than technical readiness | Inconsistent approaches across different incidents','Look for evidence that recovery initiation is informal, inconsistent, and lacks documented criteria or systematic decision-making processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3354,409,2,'Defined','Basic criteria for initiating incident recovery are documented and understood by key personnel. Recovery decision-making follows established guidelines that consider fundamental factors such as threat containment and system stability. The criteria are applied consistently within individual teams or departments.','Documented recovery initiation criteria exist and are accessible | Key personnel understand when recovery should begin | Basic factors like containment status are considered before recovery | Recovery decisions follow established guidelines most of the time','Look for documented recovery criteria that are understood and generally followed, with evidence of consistent application within teams or departments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3355,409,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive recovery initiation criteria are systematically applied across the organization with clear approval processes and stakeholder involvement. The criteria integrate multiple factors including technical readiness, business impact, and risk assessment. Recovery decisions are coordinated across all relevant teams and consistently documented.','Standardized recovery criteria applied organization-wide | Clear approval processes with defined roles and responsibilities | Multiple factors systematically evaluated before recovery initiation | Recovery decisions coordinated across all relevant stakeholders','Look for evidence of systematic, organization-wide application of comprehensive recovery criteria with clear processes and consistent stakeholder coordination.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3356,409,4,'Intelligent','Recovery initiation criteria are enhanced by real-time data, automated assessments, and predictive analytics to optimize timing decisions. The organization leverages threat intelligence, system monitoring data, and business impact analysis to make informed recovery decisions. Criteria are continuously refined based on lessons learned and emerging threat patterns.','Real-time data and analytics inform recovery decision-making | Automated tools assess recovery readiness against established criteria | Threat intelligence integrated into recovery timing decisions | Criteria continuously improved based on post-incident analysis','Look for evidence of data-driven recovery decisions supported by automated assessments, real-time monitoring, and continuous improvement of criteria based on analytics.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3357,409,5,'Adaptive','Recovery initiation criteria dynamically adapt to changing threat landscapes, business contexts, and incident characteristics in real-time. The organization employs machine learning and AI to optimize recovery timing based on historical patterns and current conditions. Criteria automatically adjust based on threat intelligence, business priorities, and environmental factors.','AI-driven dynamic adjustment of recovery criteria based on current conditions | Machine learning optimizes recovery timing using historical incident data | Criteria automatically adapt to emerging threats and changing business context | Self-improving recovery decision framework based on continuous learning','Look for evidence of AI-powered, self-adapting recovery criteria that automatically optimize based on real-time conditions, historical patterns, and emerging threats.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3358,410,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident analysis is performed in an unstructured, reactive manner with inconsistent approaches across different incidents. Analysis typically focuses on immediate symptoms rather than establishing comprehensive understanding of what occurred or identifying root causes. Documentation and evidence collection practices are minimal and vary significantly between incidents and personnel.','Analysis performed by available personnel without defined methodology | Limited or inconsistent documentation of incident timeline and impacts | Root cause analysis rarely performed or lacks depth | Evidence collection is ad hoc and potentially incomplete','Look for inconsistent analysis approaches, minimal documentation standards, and limited evidence of systematic root cause identification across incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3359,410,2,'Defined','Formal incident analysis procedures and methodologies are established and documented. The organization has defined processes for collecting evidence, establishing incident timelines, and conducting root cause analysis. Standard templates and tools are used consistently, though execution may still vary based on analyst experience and incident complexity.','Documented incident analysis procedures and methodologies | Standardized evidence collection and documentation templates | Defined root cause analysis framework in place | Training provided to incident response personnel on analysis techniques','Evidence of documented analysis procedures, standardized templates, and consistent application of root cause analysis methodologies across incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3360,410,3,'Integrated','Incident analysis is systematically integrated with other organizational processes including threat intelligence, vulnerability management, and risk assessment. Analysis results are correlated with broader security context and organizational assets. The organization maintains centralized analysis capabilities with consistent quality and depth across all incident types.','Analysis integrated with threat intelligence and organizational risk context | Centralized forensic capabilities and specialized analysis tools | Correlation of incidents with asset criticality and business impact | Regular quality assurance reviews of analysis outputs','Look for evidence of analysis integration with other security processes, centralized capabilities, and consistent quality assurance mechanisms.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3361,410,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics, automation, and machine learning capabilities enhance incident analysis processes. The organization leverages predictive analytics to identify incident patterns and proactively addresses emerging threats based on analysis trends. Analysis incorporates behavioral analytics and advanced threat hunting techniques to establish comprehensive incident understanding.','Automated analysis tools and machine learning capabilities deployed | Predictive analytics used to identify incident patterns and trends | Advanced behavioral analytics integrated into incident analysis | Proactive threat hunting informed by historical analysis results','Evidence of advanced analytics capabilities, predictive analysis for pattern recognition, and proactive threat hunting based on analysis insights.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3362,410,5,'Adaptive','Incident analysis capabilities continuously evolve and adapt based on emerging threats, lessons learned, and industry intelligence. The organization''s analysis methodology self-optimizes through feedback loops and automatically adjusts techniques based on incident characteristics and effectiveness metrics. Analysis insights drive dynamic security posture improvements and real-time defensive adaptations.','Self-optimizing analysis methodologies that adapt to new threat vectors | Real-time integration with external threat intelligence and industry feeds | Dynamic adjustment of analysis techniques based on effectiveness metrics | Analysis insights automatically trigger security posture improvements','Look for evidence of self-adapting analysis systems, real-time external intelligence integration, and automated security posture adjustments based on analysis outcomes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3363,411,1,'Ad Hoc','Investigation actions are recorded inconsistently, often through informal methods like personal notes or ad hoc documentation. Records may be incomplete, stored in various locations, and lack proper chain of custody or integrity controls.','Investigation actions documented in personal notes or informal formats | No standardized recording procedures or templates | Records scattered across multiple systems or locations | Limited or no integrity protection for investigation records','Look for evidence that some investigation activities are documented but without consistent format, centralized storage, or integrity protection mechanisms.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3364,411,2,'Defined','Formal procedures exist for recording investigation actions with standardized templates and designated storage locations. Basic integrity controls are implemented, though they may not be consistently applied across all investigations.','Documented procedures for recording investigation actions | Standardized forms or templates for investigation documentation | Designated systems or repositories for storing investigation records | Basic access controls and backup procedures for investigation records','Look for documented procedures and standardized approaches to recording investigation actions, with some evidence of integrity protection measures being implemented.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3365,411,3,'Integrated','Investigation recording is fully integrated into the incident response process with automated logging capabilities and comprehensive chain of custody controls. Records are systematically protected with cryptographic integrity controls and proper provenance tracking.','Automated logging of investigation actions within incident response systems | Cryptographic hashing or digital signatures for record integrity | Comprehensive chain of custody documentation | Integration with case management systems for complete investigation tracking','Look for systematic integration of recording capabilities into incident response workflows with strong technical controls for maintaining record integrity and provenance.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3366,411,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and machine learning capabilities enhance investigation recording by automatically identifying and flagging potential gaps or inconsistencies. The system provides intelligent recommendations for documentation completeness and supports advanced forensic analysis of recorded actions.','AI-powered analysis of investigation records for completeness and quality | Automated detection of documentation gaps or anomalies | Machine learning models that suggest relevant investigation actions based on historical data | Advanced correlation between recorded actions and investigation outcomes','Look for evidence of intelligent systems that analyze and enhance investigation recording quality, with automated recommendations and advanced analytical capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3367,411,5,'Adaptive','The investigation recording system continuously evolves based on lessons learned, threat intelligence, and regulatory changes. It automatically adapts recording requirements and integrity controls based on incident type, severity, and emerging forensic best practices while maintaining interoperability with external systems.','Dynamic adaptation of recording requirements based on incident characteristics and threat landscape | Continuous improvement of recording processes based on investigation outcomes and feedback | Seamless integration with external forensic and legal systems | Self-optimizing integrity and provenance controls that adjust to emerging threats and regulatory requirements','Look for evidence of a self-improving system that automatically adapts recording practices based on changing requirements, threat landscape, and lessons learned from previous investigations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3368,412,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident data collection occurs sporadically and inconsistently across the organization. Data integrity is not systematically maintained, with evidence frequently lost, corrupted, or incomplete due to lack of formal processes.','Manual collection of incident data with no standardized format | Frequent loss or corruption of incident evidence | No designated personnel responsible for data preservation | Limited or no documentation of collection processes','Look for inconsistent, manual data collection practices with frequent evidence integrity issues and no formal accountability.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3369,412,2,'Defined','Documented procedures exist for collecting incident data and metadata with basic integrity preservation measures in place. Collection processes are standardized but may not be consistently followed across all incident types or organizational units.','Written procedures for incident data collection and preservation | Designated roles and responsibilities for data collection activities | Basic chain of custody processes implemented | Standard templates or tools used for data collection','Look for documented procedures and assigned responsibilities with evidence of basic integrity controls being implemented.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3370,412,3,'Integrated','Incident data collection is systematically integrated across security tools and organizational processes with robust integrity preservation mechanisms. Automated collection capabilities are deployed for most incident types with comprehensive metadata capture.','Automated data collection integrated with security tools and systems | Comprehensive metadata collection including timestamps, hashes, and chain of custody | Regular validation of data integrity through automated checks | Standardized collection processes across all business units','Look for systematic integration of automated collection tools with comprehensive integrity validation mechanisms across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3371,412,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and machine learning capabilities enhance incident data collection by automatically identifying relevant data sources and optimizing collection processes. Intelligent systems predict data integrity risks and proactively implement protective measures.','Machine learning algorithms identify and prioritize relevant incident data | Predictive analytics optimize collection strategies based on incident type and severity | Automated correlation of data across multiple sources and timeframes | Real-time integrity monitoring with automated remediation capabilities','Look for advanced analytics capabilities that intelligently optimize data collection and provide predictive integrity protection mechanisms.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3372,412,5,'Adaptive','The incident data collection system continuously evolves and adapts based on emerging threats, regulatory changes, and lessons learned from previous incidents. Self-optimizing capabilities automatically adjust collection parameters and integrity controls to maintain effectiveness against evolving attack vectors.','Self-adapting collection processes that evolve with threat landscape changes | Continuous optimization based on feedback from incident analysis outcomes | Dynamic adjustment of integrity controls based on risk assessment | Seamless integration with external threat intelligence to enhance collection strategies','Look for evidence of continuous adaptation and self-optimization of collection processes with dynamic response to changing threat environments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3373,413,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident magnitude estimation is performed inconsistently and relies heavily on individual judgment without structured criteria. Validation of estimates is informal or absent, leading to potentially inaccurate assessments of incident severity and impact.','Magnitude estimation varies significantly between different responders | No standardized criteria or metrics for assessing incident impact | Validation of magnitude estimates is informal or non-existent | Documentation of magnitude assessment rationale is minimal or missing','Look for evidence that incident magnitude estimation is inconsistent, lacks standardized criteria, and has minimal or no validation processes in place.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3374,413,2,'Defined','Basic procedures and criteria exist for estimating incident magnitude, with defined categories or scales for impact assessment. Validation processes are documented but may not be consistently applied across all incidents.','Documented procedures for incident magnitude estimation exist | Standard impact categories or severity scales are defined | Basic validation steps are outlined in procedures | Magnitude estimates are documented using consistent formats','Look for documented procedures and standardized criteria for magnitude estimation, with evidence of basic validation processes being defined.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3375,413,3,'Integrated','Incident magnitude estimation follows established procedures integrated across the incident response process, with consistent validation by designated personnel or teams. Multiple factors including business impact, technical scope, and stakeholder effects are systematically considered.','Magnitude estimation is integrated into incident response workflows | Multiple validation sources or reviewers are systematically engaged | Business impact, technical scope, and stakeholder effects are consistently evaluated | Estimation accuracy is tracked and reviewed for process improvement','Look for evidence that magnitude estimation is systematically integrated into incident response with consistent multi-factor validation and accuracy tracking.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3376,413,4,'Intelligent','Advanced tools and analytics support incident magnitude estimation with real-time data and historical trend analysis. Automated validation mechanisms cross-check estimates against multiple data sources and trigger alerts for significant discrepancies.','Automated tools assist in magnitude estimation using real-time data feeds | Historical incident data informs magnitude assessment accuracy | Machine learning or analytics enhance estimation precision | Automated validation checks flag inconsistencies or outliers for human review','Look for evidence of advanced tools, analytics, and automated validation mechanisms that enhance the accuracy and consistency of magnitude estimation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3377,413,5,'Adaptive','The magnitude estimation process continuously evolves based on lessons learned, emerging threats, and changing business contexts. Predictive analytics and AI-driven insights enable proactive magnitude assessment refinement and dynamic validation criteria adjustment.','Magnitude estimation criteria adapt based on emerging threat intelligence and lessons learned | Predictive analytics anticipate incident impact before full manifestation | AI-driven insights continuously improve estimation accuracy | Dynamic validation thresholds adjust based on organizational risk tolerance and context changes','Look for evidence that the magnitude estimation process continuously adapts and improves through predictive analytics, AI insights, and dynamic adjustment based on evolving threats and organizational context.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3378,414,1,'Ad Hoc','Stakeholder notification occurs inconsistently and relies heavily on individual judgment and memory. There are no established notification procedures, and communication happens through informal channels when incidents are discovered.','No formal stakeholder notification procedures exist | Incident notifications are sent on an ad-hoc basis when someone remembers | Communication relies on informal methods like phone calls or personal emails | No defined list of who should be notified for different incident types','Evidence shows stakeholder notifications happen sporadically without documented procedures or consistent communication channels.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3379,414,2,'Defined','Basic stakeholder notification procedures are documented with identified internal and external contacts for incident reporting. Notification processes are established but may not be consistently followed across all incident types.','Written procedures define who to notify for incidents | Basic stakeholder contact lists are maintained | Standard notification templates or formats are available | Roles and responsibilities for notifications are assigned','Documentation exists that defines stakeholder notification procedures and contact information for incident communications.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3380,414,3,'Integrated','Stakeholder notification is systematically integrated into incident response workflows with automated triggers and escalation paths. Communications are tailored to different stakeholder groups and consistently executed across the organization.','Notification procedures are integrated into incident response playbooks | Automated systems trigger stakeholder notifications based on incident criteria | Different communication approaches for various stakeholder types | Regular testing and validation of notification procedures','Evidence demonstrates that stakeholder notifications are systematically integrated into incident response processes with automated triggers and validated procedures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3381,414,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and intelligence drive dynamic stakeholder notification decisions based on incident characteristics, impact assessment, and stakeholder relevance. The system learns from past incidents to optimize communication timing and content.','AI or advanced analytics inform notification decisions | Dynamic stakeholder selection based on incident impact and context | Automated content customization for different audiences | Performance metrics track notification effectiveness and response times','Evidence shows intelligent systems that dynamically determine appropriate stakeholders and customize communications based on incident analysis and historical data.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3382,414,5,'Adaptive','The stakeholder notification system continuously evolves and adapts based on changing threat landscapes, stakeholder feedback, and emerging communication technologies. Real-time optimization ensures maximum effectiveness while maintaining compliance and relationship management.','Self-improving notification systems that adapt based on feedback and outcomes | Integration with emerging communication platforms and technologies | Predictive modeling anticipates stakeholder information needs | Continuous optimization of communication strategies based on effectiveness metrics','Evidence demonstrates a self-adapting stakeholder notification capability that continuously improves based on feedback, threat intelligence, and evolving communication technologies.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3383,415,1,'Ad Hoc','Information sharing during incidents occurs on an informal, reactive basis with no clear process or designated stakeholders. Communications happen through ad-hoc methods such as phone calls or emails to whoever is available at the time. There is no consistent approach to determining what information should be shared or with whom.','No documented process for incident information sharing | Communications rely on individual relationships and availability | Inconsistent or delayed sharing with key stakeholders | No clear authorization mechanisms for information release','Look for absence of formal information sharing procedures and evidence that communications occur only through informal, unstructured methods during incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3384,415,2,'Defined','Basic processes and procedures exist for sharing incident information with designated internal and external stakeholders. Clear roles and responsibilities are documented, and there are established communication channels and templates. Authorization requirements are defined but may not be consistently followed across all incident types.','Documented incident communication procedures and stakeholder lists | Defined roles and responsibilities for information sharing | Basic templates and communication channels established | Authorization processes documented but inconsistently applied','Look for documented procedures that specify who should receive what information and evidence that basic communication processes are established and generally followed.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3385,415,3,'Integrated','Incident information sharing is systematically integrated across the organization with consistent application of authorization controls. Stakeholder communications are coordinated through established governance structures and are tailored based on incident severity and type. Information sharing processes are regularly reviewed and updated to ensure effectiveness.','Systematic application of information sharing procedures across all incidents | Integrated governance and authorization controls consistently enforced | Tailored communications based on incident classification and stakeholder needs | Regular review and improvement of communication processes','Look for evidence that information sharing processes are consistently applied organization-wide with proper authorization controls and systematic coordination across different incident scenarios.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3386,415,4,'Intelligent','Information sharing leverages advanced analytics and automation to optimize communications with stakeholders based on real-time incident data and stakeholder preferences. The organization uses metrics and feedback to continuously improve sharing effectiveness and maintains dynamic stakeholder databases. Predictive capabilities help anticipate information needs and proactively share relevant updates.','Automated information sharing systems with intelligent routing capabilities | Real-time metrics and analytics drive communication optimization | Dynamic stakeholder management with preference-based customization | Predictive analysis informs proactive information sharing decisions','Look for automated systems that intelligently route information based on analytics, evidence of data-driven optimization of communications, and proactive sharing mechanisms.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3387,415,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a self-evolving information sharing ecosystem that continuously adapts to changing threat landscapes, stakeholder needs, and regulatory requirements. Machine learning algorithms optimize communication timing, content, and channels while maintaining strict authorization controls. The system learns from each incident to improve future information sharing effectiveness and stakeholder satisfaction.','Self-adapting communication systems that evolve based on threat intelligence and stakeholder feedback | Machine learning optimization of information sharing timing and content | Continuous adaptation to regulatory changes and emerging stakeholder requirements | Automated learning from incident outcomes to enhance future communications','Look for evidence of machine learning-driven adaptive systems that continuously evolve information sharing practices based on outcomes, stakeholder feedback, and changing environmental conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3388,416,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident containment occurs reactively with no established procedures or clear responsibilities. Staff respond to incidents using improvised methods, often leading to inconsistent or inadequate containment measures that may allow incidents to spread or persist.','No documented containment procedures exist | Containment actions are performed by whoever is available without clear role assignments | Response times are unpredictable and often lengthy | Limited or no coordination between different teams during containment efforts','Look for evidence of reactive, unstructured containment efforts with no documented procedures and inconsistent response across incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3389,416,2,'Defined','Basic incident containment procedures are documented and assigned to specific roles within the organization. Standard containment techniques are established for common incident types, though implementation may vary and coordination between teams remains limited.','Documented containment procedures exist for major incident categories | Specific roles and responsibilities are assigned for containment activities | Basic containment tools and techniques are available and known to response teams | Standard operating procedures include containment steps and timeframes','Look for documented containment procedures with assigned roles and evidence that standard containment practices are followed for routine incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3390,416,3,'Integrated','Incident containment is fully integrated into the organization''s incident response process with coordinated efforts across all relevant teams. Containment procedures are consistently executed with defined escalation paths and regular testing to ensure effectiveness.','Containment procedures are integrated with broader incident response workflows | Cross-functional coordination mechanisms ensure unified containment efforts | Regular testing and exercises validate containment procedures | Containment effectiveness is measured and tracked across incidents','Look for evidence of coordinated containment efforts across teams with consistent execution, regular testing, and integration with overall incident response processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3391,416,4,'Intelligent','Incident containment leverages automated tools, threat intelligence, and data analytics to enable rapid and precise containment decisions. The organization uses predictive capabilities and real-time monitoring to proactively contain incidents before they can spread or cause significant damage.','Automated containment tools are deployed and integrated with monitoring systems | Threat intelligence informs containment strategies and decision-making | Real-time analytics support dynamic containment boundary adjustments | Predictive modeling helps anticipate incident spread and optimize containment approaches','Look for evidence of intelligent automation, threat intelligence integration, and data-driven containment decisions that demonstrate proactive and optimized response capabilities.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3392,416,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a self-improving containment capability that continuously evolves based on emerging threats, lessons learned, and environmental changes. Containment strategies automatically adapt to new attack vectors and organizational changes while maintaining optimal effectiveness across diverse incident scenarios.','Containment procedures automatically evolve based on threat landscape changes and lessons learned | Machine learning enhances containment decision-making and strategy optimization | Continuous feedback loops drive real-time improvements to containment effectiveness | Containment capabilities seamlessly adapt to organizational and technological changes','Look for evidence of self-adapting containment systems that continuously improve based on threat intelligence, organizational learning, and environmental changes without manual intervention.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3393,417,1,'Ad Hoc','Incident eradication activities are performed reactively without standardized procedures or clear guidance. Teams rely on individual expertise and improvised solutions to remove threats and restore systems to a secure state. There is limited coordination between team members during eradication efforts.','Eradication actions vary significantly between incidents and responders | No documented procedures for threat removal or system remediation | Limited verification that threats have been completely eliminated | Eradication efforts often incomplete or require multiple attempts','Look for evidence of inconsistent, undocumented eradication practices that rely primarily on individual knowledge rather than established processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3394,417,2,'Defined','Standard procedures exist for incident eradication with documented steps for removing threats and restoring compromised systems. Teams follow established playbooks and checklists to ensure consistent eradication activities. Basic verification processes confirm that threats have been eliminated before systems are restored.','Documented eradication procedures and playbooks for common incident types | Standardized tools and techniques used for malware removal and system remediation | Basic verification steps to confirm threat elimination | Clear roles and responsibilities assigned for eradication activities','Look for documented eradication procedures that are consistently followed with evidence of basic verification that threats have been removed.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3395,417,3,'Integrated','Eradication processes are seamlessly integrated with broader incident response workflows and organizational security controls. Multiple verification methods ensure complete threat removal before system restoration, with coordination across security, IT operations, and business stakeholders. Lessons learned from eradication efforts inform improvements to security controls and response procedures.','Integrated eradication workflows spanning multiple teams and systems | Multiple verification methods including forensic analysis and security control validation | Coordinated restoration activities with business continuity considerations | Post-eradication reviews feed back into security improvements','Look for evidence of coordinated eradication processes that integrate multiple verification methods and feed lessons learned back into organizational security improvements.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3396,417,4,'Intelligent','Eradication activities leverage automated tools, threat intelligence, and predictive analytics to identify and remove threats efficiently. Machine learning and behavioral analysis enhance the ability to detect residual threats and predict eradication effectiveness. Real-time metrics and dashboards provide visibility into eradication progress and success rates.','Automated eradication tools integrated with threat intelligence feeds | Predictive analytics identify optimal eradication strategies based on threat characteristics | Real-time monitoring and metrics track eradication effectiveness | Machine learning enhances detection of residual threats and attack persistence','Look for evidence of automated, intelligence-driven eradication capabilities with real-time monitoring and predictive analytics that optimize threat removal effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3397,417,5,'Adaptive','The organization maintains a continuously evolving, self-optimizing eradication capability that adapts in real-time to emerging threats and attack techniques. Advanced AI-driven systems automatically adjust eradication strategies based on threat behavior, organizational context, and effectiveness metrics. The eradication capability proactively evolves based on global threat intelligence and organizational learning.','Self-adapting eradication systems that evolve based on threat landscape changes | AI-driven optimization of eradication strategies in real-time | Proactive capability enhancement based on emerging attack techniques | Continuous learning from internal and external threat intelligence to refine eradication approaches','Look for evidence of autonomous, self-improving eradication systems that continuously adapt and optimize based on evolving threats and organizational learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3398,418,1,'Ad Hoc','Recovery plan execution is reactive and informal, often improvised during incidents without structured procedures. Recovery activities are inconsistent and depend heavily on individual knowledge and availability of key personnel.','Recovery activities are performed informally without documented procedures | Recovery depends on specific individuals being available | No clear handoff process from incident response to recovery | Recovery success varies significantly between incidents','Look for evidence that recovery activities happen but are largely improvised, undocumented, and inconsistent across incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3399,418,2,'Defined','Recovery plans are documented with defined procedures and roles for execution. Recovery activities follow established processes, though execution may still be manual and require significant coordination effort.','Written recovery procedures exist and are followed | Clear roles and responsibilities defined for recovery execution | Formal trigger mechanisms exist to initiate recovery from incident response | Recovery activities are documented during execution','Look for evidence of documented recovery procedures that are consistently followed, with defined roles and formal initiation processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3400,418,3,'Integrated','Recovery plan execution is seamlessly integrated with incident response processes and broader business continuity activities. Recovery activities are coordinated across multiple teams and business functions with established communication channels.','Recovery execution integrates with business continuity and disaster recovery processes | Cross-functional coordination mechanisms are established | Recovery status is communicated to stakeholders through defined channels | Recovery activities align with business impact priorities','Look for evidence that recovery execution is well-coordinated across organizational boundaries with integrated processes and stakeholder communication.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3401,418,4,'Intelligent','Recovery plan execution leverages automated tools and real-time monitoring to optimize recovery activities. Data-driven decision making guides recovery prioritization and resource allocation based on business impact analysis.','Automated tools support recovery execution and monitoring | Real-time dashboards provide recovery status visibility | Data analytics inform recovery prioritization decisions | Recovery execution adapts based on real-time business impact assessment','Look for evidence of automation, real-time monitoring, and data-driven decision making that optimizes recovery execution based on current conditions.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3402,418,5,'Adaptive','Recovery plan execution continuously evolves through machine learning and predictive analytics that anticipate recovery needs. The organization proactively adjusts recovery strategies based on emerging threats, business changes, and lessons learned from previous incidents.','Machine learning optimizes recovery execution strategies | Predictive analytics anticipate recovery resource needs | Recovery plans automatically adapt based on threat intelligence and business changes | Continuous feedback loops improve recovery execution effectiveness','Look for evidence of self-improving recovery execution that uses advanced analytics and machine learning to continuously optimize and adapt recovery strategies.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3403,419,1,'Ad Hoc','Recovery actions are performed reactively without formal selection criteria or prioritization frameworks. Actions are typically determined by whoever is available at the time of incident, often leading to inconsistent and potentially conflicting recovery efforts.','Recovery actions determined by individual judgment without documented criteria | No formal prioritization process for recovery activities | Recovery scope and sequence vary significantly between incidents | Limited coordination between recovery team members','Look for evidence that recovery actions are performed without documented selection criteria, formal prioritization, or consistent coordination processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3404,419,2,'Defined','Basic procedures exist for selecting and prioritizing recovery actions based on documented criteria. Recovery activities follow established processes with clear roles and responsibilities, though execution may still be somewhat manual and dependent on individual expertise.','Documented procedures for recovery action selection and prioritization | Defined roles and responsibilities for recovery execution | Basic criteria established for scoping recovery efforts | Standard checklists or workflows guide recovery activities','Look for documented procedures that guide recovery action selection, prioritization, and execution with clearly defined roles and basic criteria.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3405,419,3,'Integrated','Recovery action selection and prioritization are systematically integrated with broader business continuity and risk management processes. Recovery decisions are made using established frameworks that consider business impact, technical dependencies, and resource availability across the organization.','Recovery prioritization integrated with business impact analysis and risk assessments | Systematic consideration of technical and business dependencies in recovery planning | Cross-functional coordination mechanisms for recovery execution | Regular review and update of recovery action criteria based on lessons learned','Look for systematic integration of recovery processes with business continuity planning and evidence of cross-functional coordination in recovery execution.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3406,419,4,'Intelligent','Recovery actions are intelligently selected and prioritized using data-driven approaches and predictive analytics. The organization leverages real-time monitoring, automated decision support tools, and historical incident data to optimize recovery sequences and resource allocation.','Data-driven recovery prioritization using real-time system status and business metrics | Automated tools assist in recovery action selection and sequencing | Predictive analytics inform recovery time and resource estimates | Dynamic adjustment of recovery priorities based on evolving incident conditions','Look for evidence of data-driven decision making, automated decision support tools, and dynamic prioritization capabilities in recovery processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3407,419,5,'Adaptive','The organization demonstrates advanced adaptive capabilities in recovery execution, with AI-enhanced decision making and self-optimizing recovery processes. Recovery strategies continuously evolve based on machine learning algorithms, threat intelligence, and real-time organizational learning from each incident.','AI-enhanced recovery decision making with continuous learning from incident outcomes | Self-optimizing recovery processes that adapt based on environmental changes | Integration with threat intelligence and predictive threat modeling for proactive recovery adjustments | Autonomous recovery capabilities for routine incidents with human oversight for complex scenarios','Look for evidence of AI-enhanced decision making, self-optimizing processes, and autonomous recovery capabilities that demonstrate continuous adaptation and learning.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3408,420,1,'Ad Hoc','Backup integrity verification occurs sporadically and only when individuals remember to perform it. There are no formal procedures or consistent methods for validating backup and restoration asset integrity before use.','No documented backup verification procedures | Verification performed only by individual initiative | No systematic integrity checking tools or processes | Restoration attempts sometimes fail due to corrupted backups','Look for absence of formal backup verification procedures and evidence that integrity checks are performed inconsistently or not at all.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3409,420,2,'Defined','The organization has documented procedures for verifying backup and restoration asset integrity. Basic verification methods such as checksums or hash validation are defined and occasionally implemented before restoration activities.','Written backup verification procedures exist | Basic integrity checking methods defined (checksums, hashes) | Verification performed for critical systems or major incidents | Some staff trained on verification processes','Look for documented backup verification procedures and evidence that basic integrity checking methods are defined and sometimes applied.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3410,420,3,'Integrated','Backup integrity verification is systematically integrated into incident recovery workflows. Automated tools and processes consistently verify backup integrity before restoration, with results documented and tracked across the organization.','Automated backup integrity verification tools deployed | Verification integrated into standard recovery procedures | Regular testing of backup integrity across all systems | Centralized tracking and documentation of verification results','Look for systematic integration of backup verification into recovery processes with automated tools and consistent documentation across the organization.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3411,420,4,'Intelligent','The organization employs advanced analytics and intelligence to optimize backup integrity verification processes. Real-time monitoring and predictive capabilities identify potential integrity issues before they impact recovery operations.','Real-time backup integrity monitoring with alerting | Predictive analytics identify potential backup corruption risks | Advanced verification techniques beyond basic checksums | Automated remediation of backup integrity issues','Look for advanced analytics, real-time monitoring, and predictive capabilities that proactively identify and address backup integrity issues before recovery operations.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3412,420,5,'Adaptive','Backup integrity verification processes continuously evolve and adapt based on emerging threats, lessons learned, and changing business requirements. The organization leverages machine learning and advanced technologies to optimize verification effectiveness and efficiency.','Machine learning optimizes verification processes based on historical data | Verification methods adapt to new backup technologies and threats | Continuous improvement driven by post-incident analysis | Industry threat intelligence integrated into verification strategies','Look for evidence that backup verification processes continuously evolve and adapt using advanced technologies, threat intelligence, and lessons learned to optimize effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3413,421,1,'Ad Hoc','Critical mission functions are identified informally during recovery incidents with minimal cybersecurity considerations. Recovery decisions are made reactively without established prioritization criteria or security integration.','Mission functions identified only when incidents occur | Cybersecurity considerations applied inconsistently during recovery | No documented prioritization of critical functions | Recovery decisions made without security impact assessment','Look for evidence that critical functions are only identified during actual incidents with ad-hoc consideration of cybersecurity implications.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3414,421,2,'Defined','Critical mission functions are formally documented and prioritized with basic cybersecurity considerations defined for recovery scenarios. Recovery procedures include standard security requirements and function prioritization guidance.','Documented inventory of critical mission functions with priorities | Basic cybersecurity requirements defined for recovery operations | Standard procedures reference both mission and security considerations | Recovery team trained on critical function identification','Look for documented critical functions list and defined cybersecurity considerations that are consistently referenced during recovery planning and execution.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3415,421,3,'Integrated','Critical mission functions and cybersecurity considerations are seamlessly integrated into recovery execution with automated prioritization and security validation. Recovery processes dynamically balance mission continuity with security requirements based on real-time threat intelligence.','Automated systems prioritize critical functions during recovery | Real-time security validation integrated into recovery workflows | Mission-security tradeoff decisions guided by established frameworks | Recovery metrics track both mission restoration and security posture','Look for evidence of integrated systems that automatically consider both mission criticality and cybersecurity requirements with measurable balance between recovery speed and security.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3416,421,4,'Intelligent','Recovery systems intelligently analyze mission dependencies and cybersecurity threats to optimize function restoration sequences. Machine learning and analytics predict optimal recovery paths that minimize both downtime and security exposure.','AI-driven analysis of mission function dependencies and security implications | Predictive modeling optimizes recovery sequences | Automated adjustment of security controls based on recovery context | Intelligence feeds inform dynamic prioritization of critical functions','Look for evidence of intelligent systems that use analytics and machine learning to optimize the balance between critical mission restoration and cybersecurity protection during recovery.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3417,421,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously evolves its understanding of critical mission functions and cybersecurity considerations through self-learning recovery systems. Recovery capabilities adapt in real-time to changing business priorities, threat landscapes, and mission requirements.','Self-learning systems continuously refine critical function definitions | Adaptive security controls automatically adjust to recovery contexts | Dynamic mission criticality assessment based on current business state | Recovery approaches evolve based on effectiveness analytics and threat evolution','Look for evidence of self-improving systems that continuously adapt critical function prioritization and cybersecurity considerations based on changing organizational needs and threat environments.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3418,422,1,'Ad Hoc','Asset restoration verification occurs sporadically and relies heavily on individual knowledge and informal processes. There are no standardized procedures for verifying integrity, and confirmation of normal operations depends on ad-hoc checks by available personnel.','Basic manual checks performed inconsistently | No documented verification procedures | Restoration relies on individual expertise | Limited or no integrity validation tools','Look for informal, inconsistent verification practices with heavy reliance on individual knowledge and no standardized integrity checking procedures.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3419,422,2,'Defined','Documented procedures exist for verifying the integrity of restored assets and confirming normal operations. Basic verification steps are defined and followed, though execution may vary between incidents and teams.','Written verification procedures and checklists | Basic integrity checking tools implemented | Defined roles for restoration verification | Documentation of verification steps performed','Look for documented procedures and basic tools for integrity verification with consistent application of defined verification steps.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3420,422,3,'Integrated','Asset integrity verification is systematically integrated into incident recovery workflows with standardized tools and processes. Verification procedures are consistently applied across all recovery scenarios and include both technical and operational validation.','Automated integrity checking integrated into recovery workflows | Standardized verification criteria and acceptance thresholds | Cross-functional validation involving multiple teams | Regular testing and validation of verification procedures','Look for systematic integration of integrity verification into recovery processes with standardized tools and consistent cross-functional validation practices.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3421,422,4,'Intelligent','Advanced analytics and monitoring capabilities provide real-time verification of asset integrity during restoration. The organization uses intelligent tools to detect anomalies and automatically validate system performance against baseline metrics.','Real-time integrity monitoring and anomaly detection | Automated baseline comparison and performance validation | Advanced forensic capabilities for integrity assessment | Predictive analytics for restoration success probability','Look for advanced analytics-driven verification capabilities with real-time monitoring and automated validation against established baselines and performance metrics.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3422,422,5,'Adaptive','The verification process continuously evolves based on threat intelligence, incident patterns, and emerging technologies. Machine learning and AI capabilities automatically adapt verification criteria and methods based on changing risk profiles and recovery outcomes.','AI-driven adaptive verification criteria based on threat landscape | Self-improving verification processes using machine learning | Dynamic baseline adjustment based on operational changes | Continuous optimization of verification effectiveness through feedback loops','Look for AI and machine learning capabilities that continuously adapt verification processes based on threat intelligence, operational changes, and recovery outcome analysis.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3423,423,1,'Ad Hoc','Recovery end declarations occur inconsistently and are often informal or undefined. Documentation of recovery activities is incomplete, inconsistent, or missing entirely.','No formal criteria for declaring recovery complete | Recovery end decisions made by individual judgment without documentation | Incident documentation is ad-hoc and often incomplete | Recovery status communicated informally if at all','Look for absence of formal recovery completion criteria and inconsistent or missing incident recovery documentation.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3424,423,2,'Defined','Basic criteria exist for declaring the end of incident recovery, though they may not be comprehensive. Standard documentation templates and processes are established but may not be consistently applied across all incidents.','Written criteria for recovery completion exist but may be basic | Standard incident documentation templates are available | Recovery end declarations follow defined process most of the time | Documentation completion is tracked but may have gaps','Look for documented recovery completion criteria and evidence of standardized documentation processes that are generally followed.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3425,423,3,'Integrated','Comprehensive criteria for recovery completion are consistently applied across all incidents and integrated with broader incident management processes. Documentation is complete, standardized, and feeds into organizational learning and improvement activities.','Comprehensive recovery completion criteria consistently applied | All incident recovery documentation is complete and standardized | Recovery declarations integrated with incident management workflow | Documentation review process ensures completeness before closure','Look for consistent application of comprehensive recovery criteria and evidence that documentation processes are fully integrated into incident management workflows.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3426,423,4,'Intelligent','Recovery completion decisions are supported by automated monitoring and intelligent analysis of recovery criteria. Documentation processes leverage automation and data analytics to ensure accuracy and completeness while providing insights for continuous improvement.','Automated monitoring supports recovery completion decisions | Analytics-driven validation of recovery criteria completion | Automated documentation generation and completeness checking | Recovery metrics and trends analyzed for process optimization','Look for automation and analytics supporting recovery completion decisions and evidence of data-driven optimization of recovery documentation processes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3427,423,5,'Adaptive','Recovery completion criteria and documentation processes continuously evolve based on threat landscape changes, organizational learning, and predictive analytics. The system adapts recovery completion thresholds dynamically based on incident context and organizational resilience posture.','Recovery criteria adapt based on incident context and threat evolution | Machine learning optimizes documentation requirements and processes | Predictive analytics inform recovery completion timing | Continuous feedback loops refine recovery declaration processes across the ecosystem','Look for evidence of adaptive recovery completion criteria that evolve based on context and continuous learning from incident patterns and organizational changes.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3428,424,1,'Ad Hoc','Recovery communication happens sporadically and inconsistently, often driven by urgent requests or escalations from stakeholders. Communication methods and content vary significantly between incidents, with no standard approach for keeping internal teams or external parties informed of recovery progress.','Communication occurs only when stakeholders demand updates | Recovery status updates are inconsistent in format and timing | No defined stakeholder list or communication responsibilities | Recovery progress information is shared through informal channels like emails or phone calls','Look for evidence that recovery communication happens reactively without established processes, procedures, or stakeholder identification.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3429,424,2,'Defined','Basic processes and templates exist for communicating recovery activities and progress to identified stakeholders. Communication roles and responsibilities are documented, though execution may still be inconsistent across different types of incidents.','Documented communication procedures for recovery activities | Identified list of internal and external stakeholders requiring updates | Standard templates or formats for recovery progress reporting | Designated communication roles during recovery operations','Look for documented communication processes and evidence of standardized approaches to recovery progress reporting with identified stakeholder groups.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3430,424,3,'Integrated','Recovery communication is systematically integrated with overall incident response processes and consistently executed across all incidents. Communication frequency, content, and channels are tailored to different stakeholder groups and incident types.','Integrated communication workflows within recovery procedures | Regular, scheduled updates to stakeholders during recovery operations | Tailored communication approaches for different stakeholder categories | Established escalation paths for communication issues during recovery','Look for evidence of consistent execution of recovery communication processes that are fully integrated with incident response workflows and tailored to stakeholder needs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3431,424,4,'Intelligent','Recovery communication leverages real-time data and automated tools to provide timely, accurate updates to stakeholders. The organization uses metrics and feedback to continuously optimize communication effectiveness and stakeholder satisfaction.','Automated recovery status dashboards and reporting tools | Real-time integration between recovery systems and communication platforms | Metrics tracking communication effectiveness and stakeholder satisfaction | Predictive communication capabilities based on recovery progress analytics','Look for evidence of automated communication capabilities, real-time data integration, and the use of metrics to optimize recovery communication effectiveness.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3432,424,5,'Adaptive','The organization continuously evolves its recovery communication approach based on lessons learned, stakeholder feedback, and changing business requirements. Communication strategies dynamically adapt to incident context, stakeholder needs, and external factors.','Dynamic communication strategies that adapt to incident characteristics | Continuous improvement of communication processes based on stakeholder feedback | Self-optimizing communication systems that learn from past incidents | Proactive communication strategy evolution based on threat landscape changes','Look for evidence of continuous evolution and self-optimization of recovery communication approaches with dynamic adaptation to changing conditions and stakeholder needs.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3433,425,1,'Ad Hoc','Public communication during incident recovery is reactive and inconsistent, often driven by external pressure or media attention. Communications are handled informally without established protocols, resulting in mixed messaging and potential stakeholder confusion.','No formal process for public incident recovery communications | Ad hoc messaging created reactively during incidents | Inconsistent communication channels and timing | Multiple departments may issue conflicting public statements','Look for absence of documented communication procedures and evidence of reactive, inconsistent public messaging during past incidents.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3434,425,2,'Defined','Basic procedures exist for public incident recovery communications with defined roles and approved messaging templates. Communications follow established protocols but may lack coordination across all stakeholder groups and communication channels.','Documented procedures for public incident recovery communications | Pre-approved messaging templates and communication channels identified | Designated spokesperson or communication team assigned | Basic stakeholder notification lists maintained','Look for documented communication procedures, pre-approved templates, and evidence of designated communication roles during incident recovery.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3435,425,3,'Integrated','Public incident recovery communications are well-coordinated across the organization with integrated processes linking technical recovery activities to public messaging. Communications are consistent, timely, and tailored to different stakeholder groups with regular updates throughout the recovery process.','Integrated communication process tied to recovery milestones | Stakeholder-specific messaging and communication channels | Regular training and testing of communication procedures | Coordinated messaging across all public-facing channels and departments','Look for evidence of coordinated communication processes that integrate with recovery activities and demonstrate consistent stakeholder-appropriate messaging.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3436,425,4,'Intelligent','Public incident recovery communications leverage data analytics and stakeholder feedback to optimize messaging effectiveness and timing. The organization uses metrics to measure communication impact and continuously refines its approach based on stakeholder response and recovery progress indicators.','Metrics-driven communication strategy with effectiveness measurements | Automated communication triggers based on recovery milestones | Stakeholder sentiment monitoring and feedback incorporation | Data-informed optimization of messaging timing and content','Look for evidence of data-driven communication strategies, automated communication systems, and measurable optimization of public messaging based on analytics.',2);
INSERT INTO Next_CapabilityLevel VALUES(3437,425,5,'Adaptive','Public incident recovery communications continuously evolve and adapt in real-time based on changing conditions, stakeholder needs, and emerging communication technologies. The organization demonstrates innovative communication approaches and contributes to industry best practices for incident recovery communications.','Real-time adaptive messaging based on dynamic conditions | Innovation in communication methods and technologies | Contribution to industry standards and best practices | Predictive communication strategies that anticipate stakeholder needs','Look for evidence of real-time adaptive communication capabilities, innovative approaches to stakeholder engagement, and leadership contributions to industry communication practices.',2);
